 2007 | title = Antigenic and genetic characteristics of H5N1 viruses and candidate H5N1 vaccine viruses developed for potential use as pre-pandemic vaccines, March 2007 | journal = Weekly Epidemiological Record | volume = 82 | issue = 19 | pages = 164\u201367 | hdl = 10665/240934 | pmid = 17500103 | url = https://www.who.int/wer/2007/wer8219/en/ | hdl-access=free }}\n* {{cite report | vauthors = ((World Health Organization)) | date = September 2006 | title = Influenza research at the human and animal interface : report of a WHO working group, Geneva, Switzerland 21\u201322 September 2006 | publisher = [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) | hdl = 10665/69391 | id = WHO/CDS/EPR/GIP/2006.3 | hdl-access=free }}\n{{Refend}}\n{{Col-end}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical condition classification and resources\n|DiseasesDB=6791\n|ICD10={{ICD10|J|10||j|09}}, {{ICD10|J|11||j|09}}\n|ICD9={{ICD9|487}}\n|OMIM=614680\n|MedlinePlus=000080\n|eMedicineSubj=med\n|eMedicineTopic=1170\n|eMedicine_mult={{eMedicine2|ped|3006}}\n|MeshID=D007251\n}}\n{{sisterlinks|wikt=influenza}}\n* {{cite web | title=Seasonal Influenza | website=[[Centre for Health Protection]] | url=https://www.chp.gov.hk/en/features/14843.html | location=Hong Kong }}\n* {{cite web | title=What you need to know about influenza (flu) from CDC | website=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) | url=https://www.cdc.gov/flu/index.htm | date=7 February 2020 }}\n\n{{featured article}}\n{{Influenza}}\n{{Respiratory pathology}}\n{{Viral diseases}}\n{{Portalbar|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Influenza| ]]\n[[Category:Animal viral diseases]]\n[[Category:Healthcare-associated infections]]\n[[Category:RTT]]\n[[Category:RTTEM]]\n[[Category:Vaccine-preventable diseases]]\n", "name_user": "Doc James", "label": "safe", "comment": "(GR)File renamed:File:Wikipedia-VideoWiki-Influenza.webm\u2192File:En.Wikipedia-VideoWiki-Influenza.webm", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Influenza"}
{"title_page": "Igor Volk", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Expand Russian|\u0412\u043e\u043b\u043a, \u0418\u0433\u043e\u0440\u044c \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Igor Petrovich Volk\n| image              = Igor Volk 2.jpg\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = Volk in 2008\n| native_name        = \u0418\u0433\u043e\u0440\u044c \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043a\n| native_name_lang   = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1937|04|12|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Zmiiv]], [[Kharkiv Oblast]], [[Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic|Ukrainian SSR]], [[Soviet Union|USSR]]\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2017|01|03|1937|04|12|df=y}}\n| death_place        = [[Plovdiv]], [[Bulgaria]]\n| nationality        = \n| other_names        = \n| education          = [[Kropyvnytskyi|Kirovograd]] Military Aviation School of Pilots (1956)<br>[[Fedotov Test Pilot School]] (1965)<br>[[Moscow Aviation Institute]] (1969)\n| occupation         = test pilot, cosmonaut\n| years_active       = 1956 {{endash}} 2016\n| employer           = [[Gromov Flight Research Institute]] (1965-2002)\n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = [[List of Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-21 variants|MiG-21I testbed]] maiden flight\n| signature          = Sign of I. P. Volk.png\n| signature_size     = 200px\n| signature_alt      = \n| awards           = [[Hero of the Soviet Union]]<br>[[Honoured Test Pilot of the USSR]]\n{{Infobox astronaut\n|embed = yes\n| type          = Cosmonaut\n| nationality   = \n| selection     = [[List of astronauts by year of selection#1980|Air Force Group 5]]\n| time          = 11d 19h 14min\n| mission       = [[Soyuz T-12]]\n| insignia      = \n}}\n}}\n\n'''Igor Petrovich Volk''' ({{lang-ru|\u0418\u0433\u043e\u0440\u044c \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043a}}, {{Lang-uk|\u0406\u0433\u043e\u0440 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043a}}; 12 April 1937&nbsp;\u2013 3 January 2017) was a Soviet [[Cosmonaut|cosmonaut]] and [[test pilot]].\n\n== Military and test pilot ==\nVolk became a pilot in the [[Soviet Air Forces|Soviet Air Force]] in 1956. After graduation from the [[Fedotov Test Pilot School]] in 1965, he has joined the [[Gromov Flight Research Institute]].<ref name=\"ShLI2002\">{{cite book |last1= |first1= |date=2002 |editor-last=\u0417\u043d\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f |editor-first=\u041d\u0430\u0442\u0430\u043b\u044c\u044f |title=\u0428\u041b\u0418 \u0441\u043e \u0432\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0435\u043c |trans-title=ShLI in Time |url=https://search.rsl.ru/ru/search#yf=2002&yt=2002&q=%D1%88%D0%BB%D0%B8%20%D1%81%D0%BE%20%D0%B2%D1%80%D0%B5%D0%BC%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%B5%D0%BC |language=RU |edition=2 |location=\u0416\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 |publisher=\u041e\u041e\u041e \"\u0420\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043a\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0433\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u044b \"\u0416\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\" |pages=400 |isbn=}}</ref><ref name=\"TTO2012\">{{Cite book |last=Evans |first=Ben |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k_uZiCp5icUC&pg=PA176&lpg=PA176&dq=savitskaya+14,252&source=bl&ots=y5E3UO0x5w&sig=nT67eQYBOGi2AqRRZ8lMB5yCLW0&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=test%20pilots%20school&f=false|title=Tragedy and Triumph in Orbit: The Eighties and Early Nineties |language=en |date=2012|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media |pages=614 |isbn=9781461434306 |DOI=10.1007/978-1-4614-3430-6}}</ref>  He logged over 7000 flight hours in over 80 different aircraft types. Over the years, he flew on all types of Soviet fighters, bombers, and transport aircraft. He showed outstanding abilities in complex tests of various airplanes at critical angles of attack, stall, and spin. He was the first who tested aircraft behavior at high super-critical angles of attack (around 90\u00b0) and performed aerobatics such as the \"[[Cobra maneuver|cobra]]\" maneuver.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book | title=Russia's Cosmonauts:  Inside the Yuri Gagarin Training Center | last=Hall | first=Rex | last2=Shayler | first2=Davide | last3=Vis | first3=Bert | publisher=Praxis Publishing | year=2005 | isbn=0-387-21894-7 | location=Chichester, UK | pages=335\u20136}}</ref>\n\n== Space program ==\n[[Image:Igor Volk, Thomas Reiter, Charlie M. Duke, Technik-Museum.jpg|thumb|280px|left|Cosmonaut Igor Volk, European Astronaut [[Thomas Reiter]], U.S. Astronaut [[Charles Duke|Charlie Duke]]]]\nIgor Volk was selected as a cosmonaut on 12 July 1977 and flew as Research Cosmonaut on [[Soyuz T-12]], the 7th expedition to [[Salyut 7]]. One goal of the mission was to evaluate the effects of long-duration spaceflight on a pilot skills and ability to fly and land an aeroplane safely (in order to prove Volk's ability to control [[Buran (spacecraft)|Space Shuttle Buran]] atmospheric segment of flight).<ref name=\":0\" /> He served as the head of pilot-cosmonaut training department for the Buran program and later (after the project's cancellation) worked for the [[Gromov Flight Research Institute]] as a Flight Tests Deputy Chief before retiring in 1996. He previously served as President of the [[National Aero Club of Russia]] and Vice President of the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration A\u00e9ronautique Internationale]]. As recognition for his contributions as a test pilot and cosmonaut he was awarded the [[Hero of the Soviet Union]] on 29 July 1984.\n\n== Other accomplishments ==\nVolk was also an inventor and was planning a new four-person [[concept car|concept]] [[Flying car (aircraft)|flying car]], called the [[Lark-4]] which takes off and lands at 45&nbsp;km/h (28&nbsp;mph) using a 27-meter (89 ft) [[runway]].{{citation needed|date=July 2016}} It consumes 11 litres (3 gallons) of [[fuel]] for every {{convert|100|km|mi|abbr=on}} traveled and [[Cruise (aeronautics)|cruises]] at around 637&nbsp;km/h (396&nbsp;mph).{{citation needed|date=July 2016}}<!-- Is this flying car real, or just a paper concept? Grammar should be adjusted if it is only hypothetical. -->\n\n==Personal life==\nVolk was married and had two children. \n\nHe died on 3 January 2017 while on holiday in [[Plovdiv]], [[Bulgaria]]. He is buried together with his daughter at the [https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/174934742/igor-petrovich-volk Bykovskoye Memorial Cemetery] in [[Zhukovsky, Moscow Oblast|Zhukovsky]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spaceflightinsider.com/obituary/cosmonaut-igor-volk-dead-79/|title=Cosmonaut Igor Volk dead at 79|work=SpaceFlight Insider|date=4 January 2017|accessdate=11 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Honours and awards==\n* [[Hero of the Soviet Union]]\n* [[Pilot-Cosmonaut of the USSR]]\n* [[Merited Test Pilot of the USSR]]\n* [[Zhukovsky, Moscow Oblast|Zhukovsky]] [[Honorary citizenship|Honorary Citizen]] \n* [[Order \"For Merit to the Fatherland\"]] 4th class\n* [[Order of Lenin]] \n* [[Order of the Red Banner of Labour]] \n* [[Order of Friendship of Peoples]] \n* [[Medal \"For Merit in Space Exploration\"]]\n\n==Memory==\nBust of Igor Volk is installed at Solnechnaya Street in the [[Zhukovsky, Moscow Oblast|city of Zhukovsky]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lii.ru/novosti/ustanovka-byusta-letchika-kosmonavta-geroya-sssr-igorya-petrovicha-volka/|title=\u0423\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043a\u0430 \u0431\u044e\u0441\u0442\u0430 \u0413\u0435\u0440\u043e\u044f \u0421\u0421\u0421\u0420 \u0418\u0433\u043e\u0440\u044f \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043a\u0430|trans-title=Installation of a bust of the Hero of the USSR Igor Petrovich Volk|date=2020-04-13|website=[[Gromov Flight Research Institute|\u041b\u0418\u0418 \u0438\u043c. \u041c.\u041c. \u0413\u0440\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0432\u0430]]|language=ru-RU|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline}}\n*[http://www.buran-energia.com/interviews/igor-volk-biography.php Detailed biography of Igor Volk]\n*[http://www.astronautix.com/v/volk.html Biography at Astronautix]\n\n{{Buran pilot test groups}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Volk, Igor}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:2017 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Zmiiv]]\n[[Category:Soviet cosmonauts]]\n[[Category:Soviet Air Force officers]]\n[[Category:Heroes of the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Russian inventors]]\n[[Category:Soviet test pilots]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Lenin]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Friendship of Peoples]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Medal \"For Merit in Space Exploration\"]]\n[[Category:Buran program]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Expand Russian|\u0412\u043e\u043b\u043a, \u0418\u0433\u043e\u0440\u044c \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Igor Petrovich Volk\n| image              = Igor Volk 2.jpg\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = Volk in 2008\n| native_name        = \u0418\u0433\u043e\u0440\u044c \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043a\n| native_name_lang   = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1937|04|12|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Zmiiv]], [[Kharkiv Oblast]], [[Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic|Ukrainian SSR]], [[Soviet Union|USSR]]\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2017|01|03|1937|04|12|df=y}}\n| death_place        = [[Plovdiv]], [[Bulgaria]]\n| nationality        = \n| other_names        = \n| education          = [[Kropyvnytskyi|Kirovograd]] Military Aviation School of Pilots (1956)<br>[[Fedotov Test Pilot School]] (1965)<br>[[Moscow Aviation Institute]] (1969)\n| occupation         = pilot, cosmonaut\n| years_active       = 1956 {{endash}} 2016\n| employer           = [[Gromov Flight Research Institute]] (1965-2002)\n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = [[List of Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-21 variants|MiG-21I testbed]] maiden flight\n| signature          = Sign of I. P. Volk.png\n| signature_size     = 200px\n| signature_alt      = \n| awards           = [[Hero of the Soviet Union]]<br>[[Honoured Test Pilot of the USSR]]\n{{Infobox astronaut\n|embed = yes\n| type          = Cosmonaut\n| nationality   = \n| selection     = [[List of astronauts by year of selection#1980|Air Force Group 5]]\n| time          = 11d 19h 14min\n| mission       = [[Soyuz T-12]]\n| insignia      = \n}}\n}}\n\n'''Igor Petrovich Volk''' ({{lang-ru|\u0418\u0433\u043e\u0440\u044c \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043a}}, {{Lang-uk|\u0406\u0433\u043e\u0440 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043a}}; 12 April 1937&nbsp;\u2013 3 January 2017) was a Soviet [[Cosmonaut|cosmonaut]] and [[test pilot]].\n\n== Military and test pilot ==\nVolk became a pilot in the [[Soviet Air Forces|Soviet Air Force]] in 1956. After graduation from the [[Fedotov Test Pilot School]] in 1965, he has joined the [[Gromov Flight Research Institute]].<ref name=\"ShLI2002\">{{cite book |last1= |first1= |date=2002 |editor-last=\u0417\u043d\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f |editor-first=\u041d\u0430\u0442\u0430\u043b\u044c\u044f |title=\u0428\u041b\u0418 \u0441\u043e \u0432\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0435\u043c |trans-title=ShLI in Time |url=https://search.rsl.ru/ru/search#yf=2002&yt=2002&q=%D1%88%D0%BB%D0%B8%20%D1%81%D0%BE%20%D0%B2%D1%80%D0%B5%D0%BC%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%B5%D0%BC |language=RU |edition=2 |location=\u0416\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 |publisher=\u041e\u041e\u041e \"\u0420\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043a\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0433\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u044b \"\u0416\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\" |pages=400 |isbn=}}</ref><ref name=\"TTO2012\">{{Cite book |last=Evans |first=Ben |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k_uZiCp5icUC&pg=PA176&lpg=PA176&dq=savitskaya+14,252&source=bl&ots=y5E3UO0x5w&sig=nT67eQYBOGi2AqRRZ8lMB5yCLW0&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=test%20pilots%20school&f=false|title=Tragedy and Triumph in Orbit: The Eighties and Early Nineties |language=en |date=2012|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media |pages=614 |isbn=9781461434306 |DOI=10.1007/978-1-4614-3430-6}}</ref>  He logged over 7000 flight hours in over 80 different aircraft types. Over the years, he flew on all types of Soviet fighters, bombers, and transport aircraft. He showed outstanding abilities in complex tests of various airplanes at critical angles of attack, stall, and spin. He was the first who tested aircraft behavior at high super-critical angles of attack (around 90\u00b0) and performed aerobatics such as the \"[[Cobra maneuver|cobra]]\" maneuver.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book | title=Russia's Cosmonauts:  Inside the Yuri Gagarin Training Center | last=Hall | first=Rex | last2=Shayler | first2=Davide | last3=Vis | first3=Bert | publisher=Praxis Publishing | year=2005 | isbn=0-387-21894-7 | location=Chichester, UK | pages=335\u20136}}</ref>\n\n== Space program ==\n[[Image:Igor Volk, Thomas Reiter, Charlie M. Duke, Technik-Museum.jpg|thumb|280px|left|Cosmonaut Igor Volk, European Astronaut [[Thomas Reiter]], U.S. Astronaut [[Charles Duke|Charlie Duke]]]]\nIgor Volk was selected as a cosmonaut on 12 July 1977 and flew as Research Cosmonaut on [[Soyuz T-12]], the 7th expedition to [[Salyut 7]]. One goal of the mission was to evaluate the effects of long-duration spaceflight on a pilot skills and ability to fly and land an aeroplane safely (in order to prove Volk's ability to control [[Buran (spacecraft)|Space Shuttle Buran]] atmospheric segment of flight).<ref name=\":0\" /> He served as the head of pilot-cosmonaut training department for the Buran program and later (after the project's cancellation) worked for the [[Gromov Flight Research Institute]] as a Flight Tests Deputy Chief before retiring in 1996. He previously served as President of the [[National Aero Club of Russia]] and Vice President of the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration A\u00e9ronautique Internationale]]. As recognition for his contributions as a test pilot and cosmonaut he was awarded the [[Hero of the Soviet Union]] on 29 July 1984.\n\n== Other accomplishments ==\nVolk was also an inventor and was planning a new four-person [[concept car|concept]] [[Flying car (aircraft)|flying car]], called the [[Lark-4]] which takes off and lands at 45&nbsp;km/h (28&nbsp;mph) using a 27-meter (89 ft) [[runway]].{{citation needed|date=July 2016}} It consumes 11 litres (3 gallons) of [[fuel]] for every {{convert|100|km|mi|abbr=on}} traveled and [[Cruise (aeronautics)|cruises]] at around 637&nbsp;km/h (396&nbsp;mph).{{citation needed|date=July 2016}}<!-- Is this flying car real, or just a paper concept? Grammar should be adjusted if it is only hypothetical. -->\n\n==Personal life==\nVolk was married and had two children. \n\nHe died on 3 January 2017 while on holiday in [[Plovdiv]], [[Bulgaria]]. He is buried together with his daughter at the [https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/174934742/igor-petrovich-volk Bykovskoye Memorial Cemetery] in [[Zhukovsky, Moscow Oblast|Zhukovsky]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spaceflightinsider.com/obituary/cosmonaut-igor-volk-dead-79/|title=Cosmonaut Igor Volk dead at 79|work=SpaceFlight Insider|date=4 January 2017|accessdate=11 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Honours and awards==\n* [[Hero of the Soviet Union]]\n* [[Pilot-Cosmonaut of the USSR]]\n* [[Merited Test Pilot of the USSR]]\n* [[Zhukovsky, Moscow Oblast|Zhukovsky]] [[Honorary citizenship|Honorary Citizen]] \n* [[Order \"For Merit to the Fatherland\"]] 4th class\n* [[Order of Lenin]] \n* [[Order of the Red Banner of Labour]] \n* [[Order of Friendship of Peoples]] \n* [[Medal \"For Merit in Space Exploration\"]]\n\n==Memory==\nBust of Igor Volk is installed at Solnechnaya Street in the [[Zhukovsky, Moscow Oblast|city of Zhukovsky]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lii.ru/novosti/ustanovka-byusta-letchika-kosmonavta-geroya-sssr-igorya-petrovicha-volka/|title=\u0423\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043a\u0430 \u0431\u044e\u0441\u0442\u0430 \u0413\u0435\u0440\u043e\u044f \u0421\u0421\u0421\u0420 \u0418\u0433\u043e\u0440\u044f \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043a\u0430|trans-title=Installation of a bust of the Hero of the USSR Igor Petrovich Volk|date=2020-04-13|website=[[Gromov Flight Research Institute|\u041b\u0418\u0418 \u0438\u043c. \u041c.\u041c. \u0413\u0440\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0432\u0430]]|language=ru-RU|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline}}\n*[http://www.buran-energia.com/interviews/igor-volk-biography.php Detailed biography of Igor Volk]\n*[http://www.astronautix.com/v/volk.html Biography at Astronautix]\n\n{{Buran pilot test groups}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Volk, Igor}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:2017 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Zmiiv]]\n[[Category:Soviet cosmonauts]]\n[[Category:Soviet Air Force officers]]\n[[Category:Heroes of the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Russian inventors]]\n[[Category:Soviet test pilots]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Lenin]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Friendship of Peoples]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Medal \"For Merit in Space Exploration\"]]\n[[Category:Buran program]]\n", "name_user": "Apetrov09703", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Igor_Volk"}
{"title_page": "Ant social networks", "text_new": "The social network of colonies of social insects have been extensively studied as model biological networks.\n\n==Social contact networks==\n===Information transfer===\n\n==Trophallaxis networks==\n\nThe network of [[trophallaxis]] events differs from the network of social contacts. In the trophallaxis network of [[Lasius niger]], foragers have higher betweenness and centrality than domestic workers, and the domestic workers appear to form three clusters.<ref name = \"Quque2020Hierarchical\">{{cite journal |first1= Martin|last1= Quque|first2= Olivier|last2= Bles|first3= Anna\u00eblle|last3= B\u00e9nard|first4=  Am\u00e9lie|last4= H\u00e9raud|first5= Bastien|last5= Meunier|first6= Fran\u00e7ois|last6= Criscuolo|first7= Jean\u2010Louis|last7= Deneubourg|first8= C\u00e9dric|last8= Sueur|title= Hierarchical networks of food exchange in the black garden ant Lasius niger|journal= Insect Science |date= 2020|url= https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/1744-7917.12792}}</ref> There also appear to be some domestic workers which act as intermediaries between foragers and other domestic workers.<ref name=\"Quque2020Hierarchical\" />\n\n==Recruitment networks==\n\nIn some species, during nest emigration there is a minority of workers who actively search new nest sites. When they find a promising site they recruit nest-mates to show them the site. The nest-mates can in turn recruit more workers and when a critical mass of ants moves back and forth between the old site and a particular new site then the whole colony moves. Recruitment generally occurs via [[tandem running]], and the emigration process can be modelled as a directed network where edges connect workers which performed a tandem run together, and the directionality shows which worker led and which worker followed. The density and complexity of these networks appears to increase with indecision,<ref name = \"Valenti2020Division\">{{cite journal |first1= Gabriele|last1= Valentini|first2= Naoki|last2= Masuda|first3= Zachary|last3= Shaffer|first4= Jake R.|last4= Hanson|first5= Takao|last5= Sasaki|first6= Sara Imari|last6= Walker|first7= Theodore P.|last7= Pavlic|first8= Stephen C.|last8= Pratt|title= Division of labour promotes the spread of information in colony emigrations by the ant Temnothorax rugatulus|journal= Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences|date= 2020|url= https://royalsocietypublishing.org/doi/10.1098/rspb.2019.2950#d3e884}}</ref> and the core of the networks consists predominantly of the subcaste of workers specialised in finding new sites and recruiting other workers.<ref name=\"Valenti2020Division\" />\n\n==Disease transmission==\nThe social contact network can dynamically respond to the presence of pathogens in a way which reduces transmission.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Ants]]\n", "text_old": "The social network of colonies of social insects have been extensively studied as model biological networks.\n\n==Social contact networks==\n===Information transfer===\n\n==Trophallaxis networks==\n\nThe network of [[trophallaxis]] events differs from the network of social contacts. In the trophallaxis network of [[Lasius niger]], foragers have higher betweenness and centrality than domestic workers, and the domestic workers appear to form three clusters<ref name = \"Quque2020Hierarchical\">{{cite journal |first1= Martin|last1= Quque|first2= Olivier|last2= Bles|first3= Anna\u00eblle|last3= B\u00e9nard|first4=  Am\u00e9lie|last4= H\u00e9raud|first5= Bastien|last5= Meunier|first6= Fran\u00e7ois|last6= Criscuolo|first7= Jean\u2010Louis|last7= Deneubourg|first8= C\u00e9dric|last8= Sueur|title= Hierarchical networks of food exchange in the black garden ant Lasius niger|journal= Insect Science |date= 2020|url= https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/1744-7917.12792}}</ref>. There also appear to be some domestic workers which act as intermediaries between foragers and other domestic workers<ref name=\"Quque2020Hierarchical\" />.\n\n==Recruitment networks==\n\nIn some species, during nest emigration there is a minority of workers who actively search new nest sites. When they find a promising site they recruit nest-mates to show them the site. The nest-mates can in turn recruit more workers and when a critical mass of ants moves back and forth between the old site and a particular new site then the whole colony moves. Recruitment generally occurs via [[tandem running]], and the emigration process can be modelled as a directed network where edges connect workers which performed a tandem run together, and the directionality shows which worker led and which worker followed. The density and complexity of these networks appears to increase with indecision<ref name = \"Valenti2020Division\">{{cite journal |first1= Gabriele|last1= Valentini|first2= Naoki|last2= Masuda|first3= Zachary|last3= Shaffer|first4= Jake R.|last4= Hanson|first5= Takao|last5= Sasaki|first6= Sara Imari|last6= Walker|first7= Theodore P.|last7= Pavlic|first8= Stephen C.|last8= Pratt|title= Division of labour promotes the spread of information in colony emigrations by the ant Temnothorax rugatulus|journal= Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences|date= 2020|url= https://royalsocietypublishing.org/doi/10.1098/rspb.2019.2950#d3e884}}</ref>, and the core of the networks consists predominantly of the subcaste of workers specialised in finding new sites and recruiting other workers<ref name=\"Valenti2020Division\" />.\n\n==Disease transmission==\nThe social contact network can dynamically respond to the presence of pathogens in a way which reduces transmission.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:Ants]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ant_social_networks"}
{"title_page": "List of United States political catchphrases", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{refexample|date=January 2017}}\n{{Dynamic list}}\nThe following is a chronological list of political catchphrases throughout the history of the [[United States]] [[Federal government of the United States|government]]. This is not necessarily a list of historical quotes, but phrases that have been commonly referenced or repeated within various political contexts.\n\n==19th-century==\n*\"We are all [[Democratic-Republican Party|Republicans]] \u2013 we are all [[Federalist Party|Federalists]]\", [[Thomas Jefferson]]'s [[First inauguration of Thomas Jefferson|First Inaugural Address]] in 1801.<ref>[http://etext.virginia.edu/journals/EH/EH35/onuf1.html Thomas Jefferson, Federalist Papers. Peter S. Onuf]. Retrieved May 26, 2008. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080612133105/http://etext.virginia.edu/journals/EH/EH35/onuf1.html |date=June 12, 2008 }}</ref>\n*\"Our Federal Union. It must be preserved\", toast famously made by [[Andrew Jackson]] during a formal gala commemorating Thomas Jefferson's birthday on April 13, 1830. The toast refers to the secessionist dispute that began during the [[Nullification Crisis]] and it became a slogan against nullification in the ensuing political affair.\n*\"[[Tippecanoe and Tyler too]]\", popular slogan for [[Whig Party (United States)|Whig Party]] candidates [[William Henry Harrison]] and [[John Tyler]] in the [[1840 United States presidential election|1840 U.S. Presidential election]].\n*\"Show me the spot\", [[Abraham Lincoln]] challenging the alleged incident of invasion by [[Mexico]] and loss of life, called the [[Thornton Affair]], that precipitated the [[Mexican\u2013American War]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Frank Moraga |title=Everybody, let's play nice |url=http://venturacountystar.com/news/2008/feb/08/everybody-lets-play-nice |work=Ventura County Star |date=February 8, 2009 |accessdate=May 26, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080709013551/http://www.venturacountystar.com/news/2008/feb/08/everybody-lets-play-nice/ |archivedate=July 9, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n*\"[[Lincoln's House Divided Speech|A house divided against itself cannot stand.]]\", opening lines of Abraham Lincoln's famous [[Lincoln's House Divided Speech|1858 \"A House Divided\" speech]], addressing the division between [[slave states and free states]] in the United States at the time.\n*\"Four score and seven years ago...\", opening of [[Abraham Lincoln]]'s [[Gettysburg Address]].<ref name=Gettysburg>[http://americancivilwar.com/north/lincoln.html Gettysburg Address Abraham Lincoln Civil War Speech]. Retrieved May 26, 2008. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080511211213/http://americancivilwar.com/north/lincoln.html |date=May 11, 2008 }}</ref>\n*\"... government of the people, by the people, for the people, shall not perish from the earth\", ending of [[Abraham Lincoln]]'s [[Gettysburg Address]].<ref name=\"Gettysburg\" />\n*\"Don't swap horses in the middle of the stream.\" - slogan of Abraham Lincoln and the [[National Union Party (United States)|National Union Party]] during the [[1864 United States presidential election|1864 presidential election]], arguing in favor of retaining Lincoln as President during the [[American Civil War]]. The slogan has since been adopted by various incumbents during times of crisis, most famously by [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] in the [[1944 United States presidential election|1944 presidential election]] during [[World War II]] and by [[George W. Bush]] in the [[2004 United States presidential election|2004 presidential election]] during the [[War on terror|War on Terror]].\n*[[Shermanesque statement|\"I will not accept if nominated and will not serve if elected,\"]] said by [[William Tecumseh Sherman]] when asked about a presidential bid during the [[1884 United States presidential election|1884 presidential election]]. Repeated and paraphrased by various politicians and public figures in later years, including [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] in 1968, [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] in the 1940s, [[Dick Cheney]] in 2008, and [[Stephen King]] in reference to the [[2018 Maine gubernatorial election]].\n*\"You shall not press down upon the brow of labor this crown of thorns. You shall not crucify mankind upon a [[Cross of Gold speech|cross of gold]].\" [[William Jennings Bryan]] in 1896, expressing his opposition to the [[gold standard]].\n\n==20th-century==\n===1900s\u20131950s===\n*\"[[Big Stick ideology|Speak softly, and carry a big stick]]\", [[Theodore Roosevelt]]'s [[Roosevelt Corollary|corollary]] to the [[Monroe Doctrine]].\n*\"[[Smoke-filled room]]\", used to describe the backroom at the [[Blackstone Hotel]] where senators gathered to secure [[Warren G. Harding]]'s nomination during the [[1920 Republican National Convention]]. The term now means a place behind the scenes, where cigar-smoking party bosses make political decisions.<ref name=EOCSFR>{{cite web |url=http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/3217.html|accessdate=May 27, 2007 |year=2005 |title=Smoke-Filled Room |publisher=Chicago Historical Society |encyclopedia=Electronic Encyclopedia of Chicago}}</ref>\n*\"[[First inauguration of Franklin D. Roosevelt#Inaugural address|The only thing we have to fear is fear itself.]]\", from [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]]'s [[First inauguration of Franklin D. Roosevelt|first inaugural address]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://historymatters.gmu.edu/d/5057/ |title=\"Only Thing We Have to Fear Is Fear Itself\": FDR's First Inaugural Address |publisher=History Matters |accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref>\n*\"[[Infamy Speech|Yesterday, December 7, 1941, a date which will live in infamy.]]\" said by President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] after the Japanese [[attack on Pearl Harbor]].<ref>[http://www.historyplace.com/speeches/fdr-infamy.htm President Franklin Roosevelt Speech For a Declaration of War]. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref>\n*\"[[Douglas MacArthur in World War II#Escape to Australia and Medal of Honor citation|I shall return.]]\" U.S. General [[Douglas MacArthur]] after leaving the Philippines.<ref>[https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/amex/macarthur/filmmore/reference/primary/macspeech02.html The American Experience | MacArthur | MacArthur's Speeches]. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref>\n* \"Is there anything we can do for you? For you are the one in trouble now.\" [[Eleanor Roosevelt]] to [[Harry Truman]], upon learning [[Franklin Roosevelt]] had died.\n* \"[[Buck passing#The buck stops here|The buck stops here]]\", paperweight on the desk of [[Harry Truman]].\n*\"[[I like Ike]]\", campaign slogan for President [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]].<ref>[http://www.presidentsusa.net/1952slogan.html I Like Ike]. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref>\n*[[The wrong war, at the wrong place, at the wrong time, and with the wrong enemy]] - said by [[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]] General [[Omar Bradley]] to the [[United States Senate|U.S. Senate]] in opposition to extending the [[Korean War]] into [[China]]. Contributed to President [[Harry S. Truman]]'s [[Relief of Douglas MacArthur|dismissal]] of the commander of [[United Nations Command|U.N. forces]] [[Douglas MacArthur]]. Later utilized in variations in opposition to the [[Vietnam War]] and the [[Iraq War]]. \n*\"Clean as a hound's tooth\", the standard promised by Republican candidate [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] in the 1952 campaign, which gained attention when [[Richard Nixon]], campaigning for vice president on the same ticket was accused of using campaign funds for personal use.\n*\"And you know, the kids, like all kids, love the dog and I just want to say this right now, that regardless of what they say about it, we're gonna keep it.\" \u2013 famous line from the [[Checkers speech]] delivered by Richard Nixon.\n*\"[[McCarthyism#House Committee on Un-American Activities|Are you now or have you ever been a member of the Communist Party?]]\" infamous question asked by the [[House Un-American Activities Committee]] during the height of the [[Cold War]].<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D01E6DB153BF935A15752C1A9669C8B63 Are You Now or Have You Ever? \u2013 ''The New York Times'']. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref>\n*\"[[Army\u2013McCarthy hearings#Joseph Welch confronts McCarthy|Have you no sense of decency, sir? At long last, have you left no sense of decency?]]\", [[Joseph N. Welch]] confronts Senator [[Joseph McCarthy]] during the televised [[Army\u2013McCarthy hearings]] on June 9, 1954.\n\n===1960s\u20131970s===\n*\"Ask not what your country can do for you\u2014ask what you can do for your country\",<ref>[http://www.wfu.edu/~louden/PresidentialRhetoric/2007GroupPPt/JFK%20Presentation.ppt John F. Kennedy Inaugural Speech]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref> part of the [[Inaugural address of John F. Kennedy]].\n*\"You won't have Nixon to kick around anymore,\" said by [[Richard Nixon]] in 1962 when he [[Richard Nixon's last press conference|announced his retirement from politics]] after losing the [[1962 California gubernatorial election]].<ref>[http://www.historyplace.com/unitedstates/impeachments/nixon.htm The History Place \u2013 Impeachment: Richard Nixon]. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref>\n*\"[[Ich bin ein Berliner]]\", said by [[John F. Kennedy]] in [[West Berlin]].\n*\u201cIn the name of the greatest people that have ever trod this earth, I draw the line in the dust and toss the gauntlet before the feet of tyranny, and I say [[Racial segregation in the United States|segregation]] now, segregation tomorrow, segregation forever.\u201d \u2014 Said by [[Alabama]] Governor [[George Wallace]] during his [[George Wallace's 1963 Inaugural Address|1963 inaugural address]] in [[Montgomery, Alabama|Montgomery]], defending the institution of segregation in the [[southern United States]] and characterizing the [[Federal government of the United States|federal government]]'s [[Civil rights movement|civil rights initiatives]] as authoritarian. Wallace emerged afterwards as one of the strongest defenders of segregation in the South during the 1960s. \n*\"[[I know it when I see it]]\", used by [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] Justice [[Potter Stewart]] to describe his threshold test for [[obscenity]] in ''[[Jacobellis v. Ohio]]'' (1964).\n*\"I would remind you that extremism in the defense of liberty is no vice. And let me remind you also that moderation in the pursuit of justice is no virtue.\" Said by [[Barry Goldwater]] in his acceptance speech at the [[1964 Republican National Convention]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Perlstein |first=Rick |title=1964 Republican Convention: Revolution From the Right |url=http://www.smithsonianmag.com/history-archaeology/1964-republican-convention.html |work=Smithsonian |date=August 2008 |accessdate=February 13, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20081023104558/http://www.smithsonianmag.com/history-archaeology/1964-republican-convention.html |archivedate=October 23, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n*\"Hey, hey, LBJ, how many kids did you kill today?\" slogan of [[Lists of protests against the Vietnam War|anti-war protests during the Vietnam War]]\n*\"America, love it or leave it,\" slogan of pro-war protests during the Vietnam War\n*\"Let me say this about that\", frequently said by President [[Richard Nixon]].\n*\"Let me make one thing perfectly clear\", frequently said by President Richard Nixon.\n*\"[[Only Nixon could go to China]]\", saying that became popular in the wake of [[Richard Nixon]]'s [[Richard Nixon's 1972 visit to China|visit]] to the [[China|People's Republic of China]].<ref>[http://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/klu/puch/1998/00000097/00000004/00119367 IngentaConnect Why only Nixon could go to China]. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref>\n*\"What did the President know and when did he know it?\", asked by Senator [[Howard Baker]] in the [[United States Senate Watergate Committee|Senate Watergate hearings]].\n*\"[[I'm not a crook]]\", said by [[Richard Nixon]] in reference to his never having profited through his government service. (Often misquoted as \"I am not a crook.\")<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/national/longterm/watergate/articles/111873-1.htm ''The Washington Post'']. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref>\n*\"[[Follow the money]]\", popularized by ''[[All The President's Men]]'', used in several contexts.\n*\"I'm a Ford, not a Lincoln\", said by [[Gerald Ford]] in his first speech as President.\n*\"[[Whip inflation now]]\", [[Gerald Ford]]'s widely ridiculed speech to Congress October 8, 1974.\n*\"When the president does it, that means that it is not illegal.\" Said by [[Richard Nixon]] during the [[Nixon interviews|Frost/Nixon interviews]], about his alleged participation in the [[Watergate scandal]] cover-up.\n\n===1980s===\n\n*\"Voodoo Economics\", a term used by [[George H. W. Bush]] in reference to President [[Ronald Reagan]]'s economic policies, which came to be known as \"[[Reaganomics]],\" during the [[1980 Republican Party presidential primaries]]. Before President Bush became Reagan's vice president, he viewed his eventual running mate's economic policies with great skepticism. Reagan was a proponent of [[supply-side economics]], favoring reduced [[Income tax in the United States|income]] and [[Capital gains tax in the United States|capital gains tax]] rates, which supporters claim actually increase government revenue over time. It was the last point that Bush initially took objection to.<ref>[http://www.investopedia.com/terms/v/voodooeconomics.asp Explaining 'Voodoo Economics']. Retrieved August 13, 2015.</ref>\n*\"[[There you go again (Reagan)|There you go again]]\", said by Ronald Reagan about [[Jimmy Carter]] during their 1980 presidential debate and was used by Reagan again about [[Walter Mondale]] in their 1984 Presidential debate. This quotation was also borrowed by [[Sarah Palin]] during the [[2008 Vice Presidential Debate]] against [[Joe Biden]].<ref>[https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/amex/carter/peopleevents/e_1980.html American Experience | Jimmy Carter | People & Events]. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref>\n*\"[[Make America Great Again|Let's make America great again!]]\" Slogan from the Reagan campaign in 1980, also used in 1992 by [[Bill Clinton]] and in 2016 by [[Donald Trump]].\n*\"Are you better off now than you were four years ago?\", a question posed by Ronald Reagan at the end of his debate with Jimmy Carter in 1980. Often invoked by future presidential candidates. \n*\"I'm from the government, and I'm here to help\", said by Ronald Reagan referring to the \"most terrifying words in the [[English language]]\" in opposition to [[Social programs in the United States|welfare policies]].<ref>[https://www.sec.gov/news/speech/2006/spch042706psa.htm SEC Speech: Remarks Before the Investment Adviser Association]. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref>\n*\"In this present crisis, government is not the solution to our problems; government is the problem\", said by [[Ronald Reagan]].<ref>[http://uwcr.rso.wisc.edu/quotes.html UW-Madison College Republicans \u2013 Quotes] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080512145247/http://uwcr.rso.wisc.edu/quotes.html |date=May 12, 2008 }}. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref>\n*\"I don't want to exploit ... my opponent's youth and inexperience\", said by Ronald Reagan in the second debate with [[Walter Mondale]], defusing the age issue.\n*\"It's [[Morning in America|morning again in America]]\": Ronald Reagan, in reference to the recovering economy and the dominating performance by the [[United States at the Olympics|U.S. athletes]] at the [[1984 Summer Olympics|Los Angeles Olympics]] that summer, among other things.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sok.se/inenglish/losangeles1984.4.18ea16851076df63622800011008.html|title=Los Angeles 1984|publisher=Swedish Olympic Committee|accessdate=March 7, 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061230123107/http://www.sok.se/inenglish/losangeles1984.4.18ea16851076df63622800011008.html|archivedate=December 30, 2006|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n*\"[[Where's the beef?]]\", said by presidential hopeful and former Democratic Vice President [[Walter Mondale]], when attacking Colorado Senator [[Gary Hart]] in a 1984 Democratic primary debate. Mondale meant that Hart was only doing lip service. The phrase was derived from a popular television ad for [[Wendy's]] hamburgers.\n*\"[[Trust, but verify]]\", used by Ronald Reagan when discussing relations with the [[Soviet Union]]. Originally a [[Russian proverbs|Russian proverb]].\n*\"[[Mistakes were made]]\", said by Ronald Reagan in the [[1987 State of the Union Address]] in reference to the [[Iran\u2013Contra affair|Iran-Contra affair]]. Repeated by many others, including Bill Clinton and [[George W. Bush]].<ref>[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=8972606 A Political Sidestep: 'Mistakes Were Made' : NPR]. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref>\n*\"[[Mikhail Gorbachev|Mr. Gorbachev]], [[tear down this wall!]]\", said by Ronald Reagan while speaking in West Berlin calling on the Soviet Union to dismantle the [[Berlin Wall]] separating West Berlin from [[East Germany]].<ref>[http://www.reaganfoundation.org/reagan/speeches/wall.asp Ronald Reagan-Tear Down this Wall] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080622043537/http://www.reaganfoundation.org/reagan/speeches/wall.asp |date=June 22, 2008 }}. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref>\n*\"[[George H. W. Bush#1988 presidential campaign|Oh, the vision thing]]\", said by George H. W. Bush, responding to concerns that his campaign lacked a unifying theme.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.askoxford.com/worldofwords/quotations/phrasefable/visionthing/?view=uk|title=Oxford Dictionaries \u2013 Dictionary, Thesaurus, & Grammar|accessdate=March 12, 2015}}</ref>\n*\"[[Read my lips: no new taxes]]\", said by George H. W. Bush during the [[U.S. presidential election, 1988|1988 U.S. presidential election]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/november/9/newsid_3655000/3655368.stm BBC on This Day | 9 | 1988: Bush wins with 'no new taxes' promise]. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref> Bush would famously agree to a tax increase as part of a deficit-reduction deal during his actual presidency.\n*[[Thousand points of light]], first used by George H. W. Bush in his speech accepting the presidential nomination at the [[1988 Republican National Convention]].\n*\"[[Senator, you're no Jack Kennedy]].\" Senator [[Lloyd Bentsen]] to Senator [[Dan Quayle]] in the 1988 Vice Presidential debate.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O-7gpgXNWYI YouTube \u2013 Lloyd Bentsen puts down Dan Quayle]. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref> Sometimes misquoted as \"you, sir, are no Jack Kennedy.\" \n\n===1990s===\n\n*\"Vote for the crook. It's important.\" A bumper sticker slogan created by [[Morton Blackwell]] urging people to vote for [[Edwin Edwards]] over noted [[White supremacy|white supremacist]] [[David Duke]] in the [[Louisiana gubernatorial election, 1991|1991 Louisiana gubernatorial election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://photos.nola.com/tpphotos/2011/12/175duke.html|title=Vote for the crook|access-date=November 16, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925004604/http://photos.nola.com/tpphotos/2011/12/175duke.html#|archive-date=September 25, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n*\"I'm Ross, and you're the Boss\", said by [[Ross Perot]] during the [[1992 United States presidential election|1992 presidential election]].<ref>[http://www.da.wvu.edu/archives/991310/news/991310,05,02.html The Daily Athenaeum Interactive] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060905113016/http://www.da.wvu.edu/archives/991310/news/991310,05,02.html |date=September 5, 2006 }}. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref>\n*\"That [[giant sucking sound]]\", said by Ross Perot in 1992 with regards to American jobs going to [[Mexico]] if the [[North American Free Trade Agreement]] (NAFTA) were ratified.\n*\"I didn't inhale\", said by [[Bill Clinton]] regarding experimenting with [[Cannabis (drug)|marijuana]] while attending [[University of Oxford|Oxford University]].<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E0CE0DF1F38F933A05750C0A964958260 ''The New York Times'']. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref>\n*\"[[It's the economy, stupid]]\" was a phrase in [[American politics]] widely used during Bill Clinton's successful [[Bill Clinton presidential campaign, 1992|1992 presidential campaign]] against George H. W. Bush. Widely attributed to Clinton advisor [[James Carville]].<ref>[http://www.thisblogrules.com/2010/12/top-twenty-worst-political-slogans.html Top 20 Worst Political Slogans]. Retrieved December 28, 2010.</ref>  The phrase, although now almost always quoted in its current form, is actually an incorrect quotation: Carville's original slogan, which he first wrote as part of a poster displayed in candidate Clinton's campaign headquarters, was \"The Economy, Stupid\", with no \"It's\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/10/31/us/1992-campaign-democrats-clinton-bush-compete-be-champion-change-democrat-fights.html|title=THE 1992 CAMPAIGN: The Democrats -- Clinton and Bush Compete to Be Champion of Change; Democrat Fights Perceptions of Bush Gain|first=Michael|last=Kelly|date=October 31, 1992|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n*\"[[I did not have sexual relations with that woman]]\", said by Bill Clinton regarding [[Monica Lewinsky]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/january/26/newsid_2672000/2672291.stm |title=BBC on this day: 1998: Clinton denies affair with intern |publisher=BBC News | accessdate=May 26, 2008 |date=January 26, 1998}}</ref>\n*\"[[Vast right-wing conspiracy]]\", used by [[Hillary Clinton]] in 1998 in defense of husband President [[Bill Clinton]] in reference to the [[Lewinsky scandal]].\n*\"It depends on what the meaning of the word 'is' is.\" Said by Bill Clinton during testimony regarding his relationship with Monica Lewinsky.<ref>{{cite news |author=Timothy Noah |date=September 13, 1998 |url=http://www.slate.com/id/1000162/ |title=Bill Clinton and the Meaning of \"Is\" |publisher=Slate |accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref>\n*\"During my service in the United States Congress, I took the initiative in creating the Internet.\" said by [[Al Gore]] during a [[Al Gore and information technology#1999 CNN interview controversy|1999 CNN interview]], and often interpreted as \"I invented the Internet.\"<ref name=\"Snopes\">[http://www.snopes.com/quotes/internet.asp], Questionable Quotes: Internet of Lies.</ref>\n\n==21st-century==\n===2000s===\n{{See also|Bushism}}\n* \"[[Fuzzy math (politics)|Fuzzy math]]\", initiated by [[George W. Bush]], and used often by others since\n* \"[[Axis of evil]]\", first used by Bush in his [[2002 State of the Union Address]], defining [[North Korea]], [[Iran]], and [[Ba'athist Iraq]].\n* \"[[There are known knowns]]\", used by [[Donald Rumsfeld]] when discussing the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|invasion of Iraq]].\n* \"[[Reality-based community]]\", attributed to a Bush administration official, widely believed to be [[Karl Rove]]\n* \"[[Si se puede#English translation|Yes, we can]]\" used by [[Barack Obama]] during the [[2008 United States presidential election|2008 presidential campaign]]\n\n===2010s===\n*\"[[The rent is too damn high]]\", a quotation and political platform of [[Jimmy McMillan]] in the [[2010 New York gubernatorial election]].\n*\"[[You didn't build that]]\", used by Barack Obama referring to federal infrastructure and used by his opponent's supporters to suggest that he meant there is no individual success in the United States. \n* [[War on Women]] \u2014 Political slogan used by the Democratic Party in attacks from 2010 onward.\n* \"[[Binders full of women]]\", a phrase used by [[Mitt Romney]] in the [[United States presidential debates, 2012|2012 presidential debates]]. Though intended as a supportive comment about resolving the [[gender pay gap]] through alternative hiring practices, it had the opposite effect among many voters and was frequently ridiculed.\n*\"[[Make America Great Again]]\", campaign slogan for [[Donald Trump]]; previously used by Ronald Reagan in 1980.\n*\"[[Basket of deplorables]]\", a phrase used by [[Hillary Clinton]] to describe some of Donald Trump's supporters.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Reilly|first1=Katie|title=Read Hillary Clinton's 'Basket of Deplorables' Remarks on Trump Supporters|url=http://time.com/4486502/hillary-clinton-basket-of-deplorables-transcript/|accessdate=January 23, 2017|work=TIME.com|date=January 22, 2017}}</ref> The phrase was embraced by many Trump supporters.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2016/09/12/deplorable-and-proud-some-trump-supporters-embrace-label/90290760/ |title='Deplorable' and proud: Some Trump supporters embrace the label |work=[[USA Today]] |first=William |last=Cummings |date=September 12, 2016}}</ref>\n*\"[[Drain the Swamp]]\", used by many politicians, including [[Ronald Reagan]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Reagan still draining the swamp (March 12, 1983)|url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1983/03/12/page/9/article/reagan-still-draining-the-swamp|accessdate=November 15, 2016|work=Chicago Tribune|issue=March 12, 1983}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Garcia|first1=Eric|title=A History of 'Draining the Swamp'|url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/history-of-draining-the-swamp|accessdate=November 15, 2016|work=Roll Call|date=October 18, 2016}}</ref> [[Nancy Pelosi]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Espo|first1=David|title=Pelosi Says She Would Drain GOP 'Swamp'|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/10/06/AR2006100600056.html|accessdate=November 15, 2016|work=The Washington Post|date=October 6, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Allison|first1=Bill|title=Trump Rhetoric Fails to Damp K-Street Hopes of Renaissance|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2016-11-10/trump-rhetoric-doesn-t-damp-k-street-hopes-of-renaissance|accessdate=November 15, 2016|work=Bloomberg|date=November 10, 2016}}</ref> and [[Donald Trump]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wallach|first1=Philip|title=What Trump Can Learn From Jimmy Carter's Failure to 'Drain the Swamp'|url=http://fortune.com/2016/11/15/trump-drain-swamp-establishment/|accessdate=November 15, 2016|work=Fortune|date=November 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Harrington|first1=Rebecca|title=Here's what Trump means when he says 'drain the swamp' \u2014 even though it's not an accurate metaphor|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/what-does-drain-the-swamp-mean-was-dc-built-on-a-swamp-2016-11|accessdate=November 15, 2016|work=Business Insider|date=November 11, 2016}}</ref>\n* \"[[Nasty woman|Such a nasty woman]]\", said by [[Donald Trump]] during the final presidential debate between him and [[Hillary Clinton]].<ref>{{cite web|title='Nasty': A Feminist History|date=October 12, 2016|author=Garber, Megan|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2016/10/nasty-a-feminist-history/504815/|work=[[The Atlantic]]}}\n* {{cite web|title=Nasty Women|date=November 1, 2016|author=Jones, Ann|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/nasty-women_us_5818b1fee4b0990edc338747|work=The Huffington Post}}\n* {{cite web|work=The Guardian|title='This is just the beginning': women who marched against Trump vow to fight on|author=Siddiqui, Sabrina|author2=Gambino, Lauren|author3=Redden, Molly|author4=Walters, Joanna|date=22 January 2017|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jan/21/womens-march-what-next-donald-trump}}</ref> The phrase was embraced by some women voters and has also launched a [[Nasty Woman Movement|feminist movement by the same name]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/nasty-woman-became-a-call-of-solidarity-for-women-voters_us_5808f6a8e4b02444efa20c92|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|title=How 'Nasty Woman' Became A Viral Call For Solidarity|author=Gray, Emma|date=October 20, 2016}}</ref>\n* \"[[Alternative facts]]\", a phrase used by U.S. Counselor to the President [[Kellyanne Conway]] during a ''[[Meet the Press]]'' interview in January 2017, in which she defended [[White House Press Secretary]] [[Sean Spicer]]'s false statement about the attendance at [[Donald Trump]]'s inauguration as [[President of the United States]].\n*[[Fake news]].\n* \"[[Nevertheless, she persisted]]\", used by [[Party leaders of the United States Senate|Senate Majority Leader]] [[Mitch McConnell]] to describe Senator Elizabeth Warren's insistence on reading a letter from [[Coretta Scott King]] into the ''[[Congressional Record]]'' during a debate on confirmation of then [[Alabama]] Senator [[Jeff Sessions]] to be [[Attorney General of the United States]]. The letter outlined opposition to Senator Sessions' confirmation for a federal judgeship in 1980s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/02/08/nevertheless-she-persisted-becomes-new-battle-cry-after-mcconnell-silences-elizabeth-warren/|title='Nevertheless, she persisted' becomes new battle cry after McConnell silences Elizabeth Warren}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.trust.org/item/20170306141029-z813u|title=\"Nevertheless, she persisted\" - U.S. women ink battle cry with tattoos|first=Thomson Reuters|last=Foundation}}</ref>\n* \"[[Covfefe]]\", an unintentional spelling error by President [[Donald Trump]] that was tweeted out; he had possibly meant to say \"coverage.\"\n* The \"[[Jimmy Kimmel test]]\", a [[Litmus test (politics)|political litmus test]] created by Senator [[Bill Cassidy]] in reference to a [[pre-existing condition]] affecting [[Jimmy Kimmel]]'s infant son, which measures a health care law by whether it would deny medical coverage to individuals with pre-existing conditions because it was unaffordable.\n* \"Reclaiming my time\", used by [[Maxine Waters]].\n* \u201cLordy, I hope there are tapes!\u201d, said by former [[Director of the Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI Director]] [[James Comey]] during a [[United States Senate Select Committee on Intelligence|Senate Intelligence Committee]] hearing when asked if his conversations with President [[Donald Trump]] were recorded.\n*\"[[Believe women]],\" slogan of the [[Me Too movement|\uff03MeToo movement]] popularized after Justice [[Brett Kavanaugh]]'s [[Brett Kavanaugh Supreme Court nomination|nomination hearings]]. \n* \"Working for the Clampdown\", used by Congressman [[Beto O'Rourke]] to describe [[Ted Cruz]] during the [[2018 United States Senate election in Texas]]. O'Rourke used a reference to [[Punk rock|punk-rock]] band [[The Clash]] to describe how Cruz is a [[Trump administration]] proxy.\n*\"[[JobsNotMobs]],\" slogan of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] during the [[2018 United States elections|2018 midterm elections]], referencing rising employment rates attributed by Republicans to [[Economic policy of Donald Trump|President Donald Trump's economic policy]] and a perceived tendency by the Democratic Party to resort to and encourage [[Riot|mob violence]]. Popularized by [[Scott Adams]], [[James Woods]], and [[Turning Point USA]]. \n*\"[[It's OK to be white]],\" poster campaign started on the [[/pol/]] board of [[4chan]]. \n*\"Look, fat, here's the deal,\" allegedly used by [[Joe Biden]] during a town hall meeting in Iowa in response to a voter raising questions about his son, [[Hunter Biden]]. The Biden campaign claimed that Biden said \"look, fact,\" instead of \"fat\" (the microphone quality in footage of the exchange makes it difficult to discern), though a different spokesperson later appeared to imply that Biden did, indeed, say \"fat.\" \n\n===2020s===\n*\"Go to the YouTube,\" used by [[Bernie Sanders]] in a debate against [[Joe Biden]] to encourage viewers to watch footage of Biden calling for cuts to [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]] on the Senate Floor, which Biden had repeatedly denied. The phrase was both embraced and mocked online, with supporters of Sanders adopting it.\n*\"That woman from Michigan,\" used by [[Donald Trump]] in an attack against Michigan Governor [[Gretchen Whitmer]] over her handling of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Michigan]]. The phrase was adopted by many of the governor's supporters, as well as the governor herself.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Democrat Party (epithet)|''Democrat Party'' (epithet)]]\n*[[List of U.S. presidential campaign slogans]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:American political catchphrases| ]]\n[[Category:Political communication|United States political catchphrases]]\n[[Category:Lists of phrases|United States political catchphrases]]\n[[Category:Political catchphrases| ]]\n[[Category:Politics-related lists|United States catchphrases]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{refexample|date=January 2017}}\n{{Dynamic list}}\nThe following is a chronological list of political catchphrases throughout the history of the [[United States]] [[Federal government of the United States|government]]. This is not necessarily a list of historical quotes, but phrases that have been commonly referenced or repeated within various political contexts.\n\n==19th-century==\n*\"We are all [[Democratic-Republican Party|Republicans]] \u2013 we are all [[Federalist Party|Federalists]]\", [[Thomas Jefferson]]'s [[First inauguration of Thomas Jefferson|First Inaugural Address]] in 1801.<ref>[http://etext.virginia.edu/journals/EH/EH35/onuf1.html Thomas Jefferson, Federalist Papers. Peter S. Onuf]. Retrieved May 26, 2008. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080612133105/http://etext.virginia.edu/journals/EH/EH35/onuf1.html |date=June 12, 2008 }}</ref>\n*\"Our Federal Union. It must be preserved\", toast famously made by [[Andrew Jackson]] during a formal gala commemorating Thomas Jefferson's birthday on April 13, 1830. The toast refers to the secessionist dispute that began during the [[Nullification Crisis]] and it became a slogan against nullification in the ensuing political affair.\n*\"[[Tippecanoe and Tyler too]]\", popular slogan for [[Whig Party (United States)|Whig Party]] candidates [[William Henry Harrison]] and [[John Tyler]] in the [[1840 United States presidential election|1840 U.S. Presidential election]].\n*\"Show me the spot\", [[Abraham Lincoln]] challenging the alleged incident of invasion by [[Mexico]] and loss of life, called the [[Thornton Affair]], that precipitated the [[Mexican\u2013American War]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Frank Moraga |title=Everybody, let's play nice |url=http://venturacountystar.com/news/2008/feb/08/everybody-lets-play-nice |work=Ventura County Star |date=February 8, 2009 |accessdate=May 26, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080709013551/http://www.venturacountystar.com/news/2008/feb/08/everybody-lets-play-nice/ |archivedate=July 9, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n*\"[[Lincoln's House Divided Speech|A house divided against itself cannot stand.]]\", opening lines of Abraham Lincoln's famous [[Lincoln's House Divided Speech|1858 \"A House Divided\" speech]], addressing the division between [[slave states and free states]] in the United States at the time.\n*\"Four score and seven years ago...\", opening of [[Abraham Lincoln]]'s [[Gettysburg Address]].<ref name=Gettysburg>[http://americancivilwar.com/north/lincoln.html Gettysburg Address Abraham Lincoln Civil War Speech]. Retrieved May 26, 2008. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080511211213/http://americancivilwar.com/north/lincoln.html |date=May 11, 2008 }}</ref>\n*\"... government of the people, by the people, for the people, shall not perish from the earth\", ending of [[Abraham Lincoln]]'s [[Gettysburg Address]].<ref name=\"Gettysburg\" />\n*\"Don't swap horses in the middle of the stream.\" - slogan of Abraham Lincoln and the [[National Union Party (United States)|National Union Party]] during the [[1864 United States presidential election|1864 presidential election]], arguing in favor of retaining Lincoln as President during the [[American Civil War]]. The slogan has since been adopted by various incumbents during times of crisis, most famously by [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] in the [[1944 United States presidential election|1944 presidential election]] during [[World War II]] and by [[George W. Bush]] in the [[2004 United States presidential election|2004 presidential election]] during the [[War on terror|War on Terror]].\n*[[Shermanesque statement|\"I will not accept if nominated and will not serve if elected,\"]] said by [[William Tecumseh Sherman]] when asked about a presidential bid during the [[1884 United States presidential election|1884 presidential election]]. Repeated and paraphrased by various politicians and public figures in later years, including [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] in 1968, [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] in the 1940s, [[Dick Cheney]] in 2008, and [[Stephen King]] in reference to the [[2018 Maine gubernatorial election]].\n*\"You shall not press down upon the brow of labor this crown of thorns. You shall not crucify mankind upon a [[Cross of Gold speech|cross of gold]].\" [[William Jennings Bryan]] in 1896, expressing his opposition to the [[gold standard]].\n\n==20th-century==\n===1900s\u20131950s===\n*\"[[Big Stick ideology|Speak softly, and carry a big stick]]\", [[Theodore Roosevelt]]'s [[Roosevelt Corollary|corollary]] to the [[Monroe Doctrine]].\n*\"[[Smoke-filled room]]\", used to describe the backroom at the [[Blackstone Hotel]] where senators gathered to secure [[Warren G. Harding]]'s nomination during the [[1920 Republican National Convention]]. The term now means a place behind the scenes, where cigar-smoking party bosses make political decisions.<ref name=EOCSFR>{{cite web |url=http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/3217.html|accessdate=May 27, 2007 |year=2005 |title=Smoke-Filled Room |publisher=Chicago Historical Society |encyclopedia=Electronic Encyclopedia of Chicago}}</ref>\n*\"[[First inauguration of Franklin D. Roosevelt#Inaugural address|The only thing we have to fear is fear itself.]]\", from [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]]'s [[First inauguration of Franklin D. Roosevelt|first inaugural address]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://historymatters.gmu.edu/d/5057/ |title=\"Only Thing We Have to Fear Is Fear Itself\": FDR's First Inaugural Address |publisher=History Matters |accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref>\n*\"[[Infamy Speech|Yesterday, December 7, 1941, a date which will live in infamy.]]\" said by President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] after the Japanese [[attack on Pearl Harbor]].<ref>[http://www.historyplace.com/speeches/fdr-infamy.htm President Franklin Roosevelt Speech For a Declaration of War]. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref>\n*\"[[Douglas MacArthur in World War II#Escape to Australia and Medal of Honor citation|I shall return.]]\" U.S. General [[Douglas MacArthur]] after leaving the Philippines.<ref>[https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/amex/macarthur/filmmore/reference/primary/macspeech02.html The American Experience | MacArthur | MacArthur's Speeches]. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref>\n* \"Is there anything we can do for you? For you are the one in trouble now.\" [[Eleanor Roosevelt]] to [[Harry Truman]], upon learning [[Franklin Roosevelt]] had died.\n* \"[[Buck passing#The buck stops here|The buck stops here]]\", paperweight on the desk of [[Harry Truman]].\n*\"[[I like Ike]]\", campaign slogan for President [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]].<ref>[http://www.presidentsusa.net/1952slogan.html I Like Ike]. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref>\n*[[The wrong war, at the wrong place, at the wrong time, and with the wrong enemy]] - said by [[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]] General [[Omar Bradley]] to the [[United States Senate|U.S. Senate]] in opposition to extending the [[Korean War]] into [[China]]. Contributed to President [[Harry S. Truman]]'s [[Relief of Douglas MacArthur|dismissal]] of the commander of [[United Nations Command|U.N. forces]] [[Douglas MacArthur]]. Later utilized in variations in opposition to the [[Vietnam War]] and the [[Iraq War]]. \n*\"Clean as a hound's tooth\", the standard promised by Republican candidate [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] in the 1952 campaign, which gained attention when [[Richard Nixon]], campaigning for vice president on the same ticket was accused of using campaign funds for personal use.\n*\"And you know, the kids, like all kids, love the dog and I just want to say this right now, that regardless of what they say about it, we're gonna keep it.\" \u2013 famous line from the [[Checkers speech]] delivered by Richard Nixon.\n*\"[[McCarthyism#House Committee on Un-American Activities|Are you now or have you ever been a member of the Communist Party?]]\" infamous question asked by the [[House Un-American Activities Committee]] during the height of the [[Cold War]].<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D01E6DB153BF935A15752C1A9669C8B63 Are You Now or Have You Ever? \u2013 ''The New York Times'']. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref>\n*\"[[Army\u2013McCarthy hearings#Joseph Welch confronts McCarthy|Have you no sense of decency, sir? At long last, have you left no sense of decency?]]\", [[Joseph N. Welch]] confronts Senator [[Joseph McCarthy]] during the televised [[Army\u2013McCarthy hearings]] on June 9, 1954.\n\n===1960s\u20131970s===\n*\"Ask not what your country can do for you\u2014ask what you can do for your country\",<ref>[http://www.wfu.edu/~louden/PresidentialRhetoric/2007GroupPPt/JFK%20Presentation.ppt John F. Kennedy Inaugural Speech]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref> part of the [[Inaugural address of John F. Kennedy]].\n*\"You won't have Nixon to kick around anymore,\" said by [[Richard Nixon]] in 1962 when he [[Richard Nixon's last press conference|announced his retirement from politics]] after losing the [[1962 California gubernatorial election]].<ref>[http://www.historyplace.com/unitedstates/impeachments/nixon.htm The History Place \u2013 Impeachment: Richard Nixon]. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref>\n*\"[[Ich bin ein Berliner]]\", said by [[John F. Kennedy]] in [[West Berlin]].\n*\u201cIn the name of the greatest people that have ever trod this earth, I draw the line in the dust and toss the gauntlet before the feet of tyranny, and I say [[Racial segregation in the United States|segregation]] now, segregation tomorrow, segregation forever.\u201d \u2014 Said by [[Alabama]] Governor [[George Wallace]] during his [[George Wallace's 1963 Inaugural Address|1963 inaugural address]] in [[Montgomery, Alabama|Montgomery]], defending the institution of segregation in the [[southern United States]] and characterizing the [[Federal government of the United States|federal government]]'s [[Civil rights movement|civil rights initiatives]] as authoritarian. Wallace emerged afterwards as one of the strongest defenders of segregation in the South during the 1960s. \n*\"[[I know it when I see it]]\", used by [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] Justice [[Potter Stewart]] to describe his threshold test for [[obscenity]] in ''[[Jacobellis v. Ohio]]'' (1964).\n*\"I would remind you that extremism in the defense of liberty is no vice. And let me remind you also that moderation in the pursuit of justice is no virtue.\" Said by [[Barry Goldwater]] in his acceptance speech at the [[1964 Republican National Convention]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Perlstein |first=Rick |title=1964 Republican Convention: Revolution From the Right |url=http://www.smithsonianmag.com/history-archaeology/1964-republican-convention.html |work=Smithsonian |date=August 2008 |accessdate=February 13, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20081023104558/http://www.smithsonianmag.com/history-archaeology/1964-republican-convention.html |archivedate=October 23, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n*\"Hey, hey, LBJ, how many kids did you kill today?\" slogan of [[Lists of protests against the Vietnam War|anti-war protests during the Vietnam War]]\n*\"America, love it or leave it,\" slogan of pro-war protests during the Vietnam War\n*\"Let me say this about that\", frequently said by President [[Richard Nixon]].\n*\"Let me make one thing perfectly clear\", frequently said by President Richard Nixon.\n*\"[[Only Nixon could go to China]]\", saying that became popular in the wake of [[Richard Nixon]]'s [[Richard Nixon's 1972 visit to China|visit]] to the [[China|People's Republic of China]].<ref>[http://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/klu/puch/1998/00000097/00000004/00119367 IngentaConnect Why only Nixon could go to China]. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref>\n*\"What did the President know and when did he know it?\", asked by Senator [[Howard Baker]] in the [[United States Senate Watergate Committee|Senate Watergate hearings]].\n*\"[[I'm not a crook]]\", said by [[Richard Nixon]] in reference to his never having profited through his government service. (Often misquoted as \"I am not a crook.\")<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/national/longterm/watergate/articles/111873-1.htm ''The Washington Post'']. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref>\n*\"[[Follow the money]]\", popularized by ''[[All The President's Men]]'', used in several contexts.\n*\"I'm a Ford, not a Lincoln\", said by [[Gerald Ford]] in his first speech as President.\n*\"[[Whip inflation now]]\", [[Gerald Ford]]'s widely ridiculed speech to Congress October 8, 1974.\n*\"When the president does it, that means that it is not illegal.\" Said by [[Richard Nixon]] during the [[Nixon interviews|Frost/Nixon interviews]], about his alleged participation in the [[Watergate scandal]] cover-up.\n\n===1980s===\n\n*\"Voodoo Economics\", a term used by [[George H. W. Bush]] in reference to President [[Ronald Reagan]]'s economic policies, which came to be known as \"[[Reaganomics]],\" during the [[1980 Republican Party presidential primaries]]. Before President Bush became Reagan's vice president, he viewed his eventual running mate's economic policies less than favorably. Reagan was a proponent of [[supply-side economics]], favoring reduced [[Income tax in the United States|income]] and [[Capital gains tax in the United States|capital gains tax]] rates.<ref>[http://www.investopedia.com/terms/v/voodooeconomics.asp Explaining 'Voodoo Economics']. Retrieved August 13, 2015.</ref>\n*\"[[There you go again (Reagan)|There you go again]]\", said by Ronald Reagan about [[Jimmy Carter]] during their 1980 presidential debate and was used by Reagan again about [[Walter Mondale]] in their 1984 Presidential debate. This quotation was also borrowed by [[Sarah Palin]] during the [[2008 Vice Presidential Debate]] against [[Joe Biden]].<ref>[https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/amex/carter/peopleevents/e_1980.html American Experience | Jimmy Carter | People & Events]. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref>\n*\"[[Make America Great Again|Let's make America great again!]]\" Slogan from the Reagan campaign in 1980, also used in 1992 by [[Bill Clinton]] and in 2016 by [[Donald Trump]].\n*\"Are you better off now than you were four years ago?\", question posed by Ronald Reagan at the end of his debate with Jimmy Carter in 1980.\n*\"I'm from the government, and I'm here to help\", said by Ronald Reagan referring to the \"most terrifying words in the [[English language]]\" in opposition to [[Social programs in the United States|welfare policies]].<ref>[https://www.sec.gov/news/speech/2006/spch042706psa.htm SEC Speech: Remarks Before the Investment Adviser Association]. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref>\n*\"In this present crisis, government is not the solution to our problems; government is the problem\", said by [[Ronald Reagan]].<ref>[http://uwcr.rso.wisc.edu/quotes.html UW-Madison College Republicans \u2013 Quotes] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080512145247/http://uwcr.rso.wisc.edu/quotes.html |date=May 12, 2008 }}. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref>\n*\"I don't want to exploit ... my opponent's youth and inexperience\", said by Ronald Reagan in the second debate with [[Walter Mondale]], defusing the age issue.\n*\"It's [[Morning in America|morning again in America]]\": Ronald Reagan, in reference to the recovering economy and the dominating performance by the [[United States at the Olympics|U.S. athletes]] at the [[1984 Summer Olympics|Los Angeles Olympics]] that summer, among other things.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sok.se/inenglish/losangeles1984.4.18ea16851076df63622800011008.html|title=Los Angeles 1984|publisher=Swedish Olympic Committee|accessdate=March 7, 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061230123107/http://www.sok.se/inenglish/losangeles1984.4.18ea16851076df63622800011008.html|archivedate=December 30, 2006|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n*\"[[Where's the beef?]]\", said by presidential hopeful and former Democratic Vice President [[Walter Mondale]], when attacking Colorado Senator [[Gary Hart]] in a 1984 Democratic primary debate. Mondale meant that Hart was only doing lip service. The phrase was derived from a popular television ad for [[Wendy's]] hamburgers.\n*\"[[Trust, but verify]]\", used by Ronald Reagan when discussing relations with the [[Soviet Union]]. Originally a [[Russian proverbs|Russian proverb]].\n*\"[[Mistakes were made]]\", said by Ronald Reagan in the [[1987 State of the Union Address]] in reference to the [[Iran\u2013Contra affair|Iran-Contra affair]]. Repeated by many others, including Bill Clinton and [[George W. Bush]].<ref>[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=8972606 A Political Sidestep: 'Mistakes Were Made' : NPR]. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref>\n*\"[[Mikhail Gorbachev|Mr. Gorbachev]], [[tear down this wall!]]\", said by Ronald Reagan while speaking in West Berlin calling on the Soviet Union to dismantle the [[Berlin Wall]] separating West Berlin from [[East Germany]].<ref>[http://www.reaganfoundation.org/reagan/speeches/wall.asp Ronald Reagan-Tear Down this Wall] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080622043537/http://www.reaganfoundation.org/reagan/speeches/wall.asp |date=June 22, 2008 }}. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref>\n*\"[[George H. W. Bush#1988 presidential campaign|Oh, the vision thing]]\", said by George H. W. Bush, responding to concerns that his campaign lacked a unifying theme.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.askoxford.com/worldofwords/quotations/phrasefable/visionthing/?view=uk|title=Oxford Dictionaries \u2013 Dictionary, Thesaurus, & Grammar|accessdate=March 12, 2015}}</ref>\n*\"[[Read my lips: no new taxes]]\", said by George H. W. Bush during the [[U.S. presidential election, 1988|1988 U.S. presidential election]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/november/9/newsid_3655000/3655368.stm BBC on This Day | 9 | 1988: Bush wins with 'no new taxes' promise]. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref> Bush raised taxes later in his presidency.\n*[[Thousand points of light]], first used by George H. W. Bush in his speech accepting the presidential nomination at the [[1988 Republican National Convention]].\n*\"[[Senator, you're no Jack Kennedy]].\" Senator [[Lloyd Bentsen]] to Senator [[Dan Quayle]] in the 1988 Vice Presidential debate.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O-7gpgXNWYI YouTube \u2013 Lloyd Bentsen puts down Dan Quayle]. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref>\n\n===1990s===\n\n*\"Vote for the crook. It's important.\" A bumper sticker slogan created by [[Morton Blackwell]] urging people to vote for [[Edwin Edwards]] over noted [[White supremacy|white supremacist]] [[David Duke]] in the [[Louisiana gubernatorial election, 1991|1991 Louisiana gubernatorial election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://photos.nola.com/tpphotos/2011/12/175duke.html|title=Vote for the crook|access-date=November 16, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925004604/http://photos.nola.com/tpphotos/2011/12/175duke.html#|archive-date=September 25, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n*\"I'm Ross, and you're the Boss\", said by [[Ross Perot]] during the [[1992 United States presidential election|1992 presidential election]].<ref>[http://www.da.wvu.edu/archives/991310/news/991310,05,02.html The Daily Athenaeum Interactive] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060905113016/http://www.da.wvu.edu/archives/991310/news/991310,05,02.html |date=September 5, 2006 }}. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref>\n*\"That [[giant sucking sound]]\", said by Ross Perot in 1992 with regards to American jobs going to [[Mexico]] if the [[North American Free Trade Agreement]] (NAFTA) were ratified.\n*\"I didn't inhale\", said by [[Bill Clinton]] regarding experimenting with [[Cannabis (drug)|marijuana]] while attending [[University of Oxford|Oxford University]].<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E0CE0DF1F38F933A05750C0A964958260 ''The New York Times'']. Retrieved May 26, 2008.</ref>\n*\"[[It's the economy, stupid]]\" was a phrase in [[American politics]] widely used during Bill Clinton's successful [[Bill Clinton presidential campaign, 1992|1992 presidential campaign]] against George H. W. Bush. Widely attributed to Clinton advisor [[James Carville]].<ref>[http://www.thisblogrules.com/2010/12/top-twenty-worst-political-slogans.html Top 20 Worst Political Slogans]. Retrieved December 28, 2010.</ref>  The phrase, although now almost always quoted in its current form, is actually an incorrect quotation: Carville's original slogan, which he first wrote as part of a poster displayed in candidate Clinton's campaign headquarters, was \"The Economy, Stupid\", with no \"It's\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/10/31/us/1992-campaign-democrats-clinton-bush-compete-be-champion-change-democrat-fights.html|title=THE 1992 CAMPAIGN: The Democrats -- Clinton and Bush Compete to Be Champion of Change; Democrat Fights Perceptions of Bush Gain|first=Michael|last=Kelly|date=October 31, 1992|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n*\"[[I did not have sexual relations with that woman]]\", said by Bill Clinton regarding [[Monica Lewinsky]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/january/26/newsid_2672000/2672291.stm |title=BBC on this day: 1998: Clinton denies affair with intern |publisher=BBC News | accessdate=May 26, 2008 |date=January 26, 1998}}</ref>\n*\"[[Vast right-wing conspiracy]]\", used by [[Hillary Clinton]] in 1998 in defense of husband President [[Bill Clinton]] in reference to the [[Lewinsky scandal]].\n*\"It depends on what the meaning of the word 'is' is.\" Said by Bill Clinton during testimony regarding his relationship with Monica Lewinsky.<ref>{{cite news |author=Timothy Noah |date=September 13, 1998 |url=http://www.slate.com/id/1000162/ |title=Bill Clinton and the Meaning of \"Is\" |publisher=Slate |accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref>\n*\"During my service in the United States Congress, I took the initiative in creating the Internet.\" said by [[Al Gore]] during a [[Al Gore and information technology#1999 CNN interview controversy|1999 CNN interview]], and often interpreted as \"I invented the Internet.\"<ref name=\"Snopes\">[http://www.snopes.com/quotes/internet.asp], Questionable Quotes: Internet of Lies.</ref>\n\n==21st-century==\n===2000s===\n{{See also|Bushism}}\n* \"[[Fuzzy math (politics)|Fuzzy math]]\", initiated by [[George W. Bush]], and used often by others since\n* \"[[Axis of evil]]\", first used by Bush in his [[2002 State of the Union Address]], defining [[North Korea]], [[Iran]], and [[Ba'athist Iraq]].\n* \"[[There are known knowns]]\", used by [[Donald Rumsfeld]] when discussing the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|invasion of Iraq]].\n* \"[[Reality-based community]]\", attributed to a Bush administration official, widely believed to be [[Karl Rove]]\n* \"[[Si se puede#English translation|Yes, we can]]\" used by [[Barack Obama]] during the [[2008 United States presidential election|2008 presidential campaign]]\n\n===2010s===\n*\"[[The rent is too damn high]]\", a quotation and political platform of [[Jimmy McMillan]] in the [[2010 New York gubernatorial election]].\n*\"[[You didn't build that]]\", used by Barack Obama referring to federal infrastructure and used by his opponent's supporters to suggest that he meant there is no individual success in the United States. \n* [[War on Women]] \u2014 Political slogan used by the Democratic Party in attacks from 2010 onward.\n* \"[[Binders full of women]]\", a phrase used by [[Mitt Romney]] in the [[United States presidential debates, 2012|2012 presidential debates]]. Though intended as a supportive comment about resolving the [[gender pay gap]] through alternative hiring practices, it had the opposite effect among many voters and was frequently ridiculed.\n*\"[[Make America Great Again]]\", campaign slogan for [[Donald Trump]]; previously used by Ronald Reagan in 1980.\n*\"[[Basket of deplorables]]\", a phrase used by [[Hillary Clinton]] to describe some of Donald Trump's supporters.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Reilly|first1=Katie|title=Read Hillary Clinton's 'Basket of Deplorables' Remarks on Trump Supporters|url=http://time.com/4486502/hillary-clinton-basket-of-deplorables-transcript/|accessdate=January 23, 2017|work=TIME.com|date=January 22, 2017}}</ref> The phrase was embraced by many Trump supporters.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2016/09/12/deplorable-and-proud-some-trump-supporters-embrace-label/90290760/ |title='Deplorable' and proud: Some Trump supporters embrace the label |work=[[USA Today]] |first=William |last=Cummings |date=September 12, 2016}}</ref>\n*\"[[Drain the Swamp]]\", used by many politicians, including [[Ronald Reagan]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Reagan still draining the swamp (March 12, 1983)|url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1983/03/12/page/9/article/reagan-still-draining-the-swamp|accessdate=November 15, 2016|work=Chicago Tribune|issue=March 12, 1983}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Garcia|first1=Eric|title=A History of 'Draining the Swamp'|url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/history-of-draining-the-swamp|accessdate=November 15, 2016|work=Roll Call|date=October 18, 2016}}</ref> [[Nancy Pelosi]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Espo|first1=David|title=Pelosi Says She Would Drain GOP 'Swamp'|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/10/06/AR2006100600056.html|accessdate=November 15, 2016|work=The Washington Post|date=October 6, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Allison|first1=Bill|title=Trump Rhetoric Fails to Damp K-Street Hopes of Renaissance|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2016-11-10/trump-rhetoric-doesn-t-damp-k-street-hopes-of-renaissance|accessdate=November 15, 2016|work=Bloomberg|date=November 10, 2016}}</ref> and [[Donald Trump]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wallach|first1=Philip|title=What Trump Can Learn From Jimmy Carter's Failure to 'Drain the Swamp'|url=http://fortune.com/2016/11/15/trump-drain-swamp-establishment/|accessdate=November 15, 2016|work=Fortune|date=November 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Harrington|first1=Rebecca|title=Here's what Trump means when he says 'drain the swamp' \u2014 even though it's not an accurate metaphor|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/what-does-drain-the-swamp-mean-was-dc-built-on-a-swamp-2016-11|accessdate=November 15, 2016|work=Business Insider|date=November 11, 2016}}</ref>\n* \"[[Nasty woman|Such a nasty woman]]\", said by [[Donald Trump]] during the final presidential debate between him and [[Hillary Clinton]].<ref>{{cite web|title='Nasty': A Feminist History|date=October 12, 2016|author=Garber, Megan|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2016/10/nasty-a-feminist-history/504815/|work=[[The Atlantic]]}}\n* {{cite web|title=Nasty Women|date=November 1, 2016|author=Jones, Ann|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/nasty-women_us_5818b1fee4b0990edc338747|work=The Huffington Post}}\n* {{cite web|work=The Guardian|title='This is just the beginning': women who marched against Trump vow to fight on|author=Siddiqui, Sabrina|author2=Gambino, Lauren|author3=Redden, Molly|author4=Walters, Joanna|date=22 January 2017|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jan/21/womens-march-what-next-donald-trump}}</ref> The phrase was embraced by some women voters and has also launched a [[Nasty Woman Movement|feminist movement by the same name]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/nasty-woman-became-a-call-of-solidarity-for-women-voters_us_5808f6a8e4b02444efa20c92|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|title=How 'Nasty Woman' Became A Viral Call For Solidarity|author=Gray, Emma|date=October 20, 2016}}</ref>\n* \"[[Alternative facts]]\", a phrase used by U.S. Counselor to the President [[Kellyanne Conway]] during a ''[[Meet the Press]]'' interview in January 2017, in which she defended [[White House Press Secretary]] [[Sean Spicer]]'s false statement about the attendance at [[Donald Trump]]'s inauguration as [[President of the United States]].\n*[[Fake news]].\n* \"[[Nevertheless, she persisted]]\", used by [[Party leaders of the United States Senate|Senate Majority Leader]] [[Mitch McConnell]] to describe Senator Elizabeth Warren's insistence on reading a letter from [[Coretta Scott King]] into the ''[[Congressional Record]]'' during a debate on confirmation of then [[Alabama]] Senator [[Jeff Sessions]] to be [[Attorney General of the United States]]. The letter outlined opposition to Senator Sessions' confirmation for a federal judgeship in 1980s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/02/08/nevertheless-she-persisted-becomes-new-battle-cry-after-mcconnell-silences-elizabeth-warren/|title='Nevertheless, she persisted' becomes new battle cry after McConnell silences Elizabeth Warren}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.trust.org/item/20170306141029-z813u|title=\"Nevertheless, she persisted\" - U.S. women ink battle cry with tattoos|first=Thomson Reuters|last=Foundation}}</ref>\n* \"[[Covfefe]]\", an unintentional spelling error by President [[Donald Trump]] that was tweeted out; he had possibly meant to say \"coverage.\"\n* The \"[[Jimmy Kimmel test]]\", a [[Litmus test (politics)|political litmus test]] created by Senator [[Bill Cassidy]] in reference to a [[pre-existing condition]] affecting [[Jimmy Kimmel]]'s infant son, which measures a health care law by whether it would deny medical coverage to individuals with pre-existing conditions because it was unaffordable.\n* \"Reclaiming my time\", used by [[Maxine Waters]].\n* \u201cLordy, I hope there are tapes!\u201d, said by former [[Director of the Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI Director]] [[James Comey]] during a [[United States Senate Select Committee on Intelligence|Senate Intelligence Committee]] hearing when asked if his conversations with President [[Donald Trump]] were recorded.\n*\"[[Believe women]],\" slogan of the [[Me Too movement|\uff03MeToo movement]] popularized after Justice [[Brett Kavanaugh]]'s [[Brett Kavanaugh Supreme Court nomination|nomination hearings]]. \n* \"Working for the Clampdown\", used by Congressman [[Beto O'Rourke]] to describe [[Ted Cruz]] during the [[2018 United States Senate election in Texas]]. O'Rourke used a reference to [[Punk rock|punk-rock]] band [[The Clash]] to describe how Cruz is a [[Trump administration]] proxy.\n*\"[[JobsNotMobs]],\" slogan of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] during the [[2018 United States elections|2018 midterm elections]], referencing rising employment rates attributed by Republicans to [[Economic policy of Donald Trump|President Donald Trump's economic policy]] and a perceived tendency by the Democratic Party to resort to and encourage [[Riot|mob violence]]. Popularized by [[Scott Adams]], [[James Woods]], and [[Turning Point USA]]. \n*\"[[It's OK to be white]],\" poster campaign started on the [[/pol/]] board of [[4chan]]. \n*\"Look, fat, here's the deal,\" allegedly used by [[Joe Biden]] during a town hall meeting in Iowa in response to a voter raising questions about his son, [[Hunter Biden]]. The Biden campaign claimed that Biden said \"look, fact,\" instead of \"fat\" (the microphone quality in footage of the exchange makes it difficult to discern), though a different spokesperson later appeared to imply that Biden did, indeed, say \"fat.\" \n\n===2020s===\n*\"Go to the YouTube,\" used by [[Bernie Sanders]] in a debate against [[Joe Biden]] to encourage viewers to watch footage of Biden calling for cuts to [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]] on the Senate Floor, which Biden had repeatedly denied. The phrase was both embraced and mocked online, with supporters of Sanders adopting it.\n*\"That woman from Michigan,\" used by [[Donald Trump]] in an attack against Michigan Governor [[Gretchen Whitmer]] over her handling of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Michigan]]. The phrase was adopted by many of the governor's supporters, as well as the governor herself.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Democrat Party (epithet)|''Democrat Party'' (epithet)]]\n*[[List of U.S. presidential campaign slogans]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:American political catchphrases| ]]\n[[Category:Political communication|United States political catchphrases]]\n[[Category:Lists of phrases|United States political catchphrases]]\n[[Category:Political catchphrases| ]]\n[[Category:Politics-related lists|United States catchphrases]]\n", "name_user": "Pickle Mon", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_United_States_political_catchphrases"}
{"title_page": "R\u00fcppell's vulture", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| image = Ruppells Griffon Vulture (4872536563).jpg\n| image_caption = At [[London Zoo]] in London\n| status = CR\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn | author = BirdLife International | title = R\u00fcppell's Vulture | page = e.T22695207A118595083 | year = 2017 | accessdate = 2020-04-22}}</ref>\n| genus = Gyps\n| species = rueppelli\n| authority = ([[Alfred Brehm]], 1852)\n}}\n\n'''R\u00fcppell's vulture''' or '''R\u00fcppell's griffon vulture''' (''Gyps rueppelli''), named after [[Eduard R\u00fcppell]], is a large [[vulture]] that can be found throughout the [[Sahel region]] of central Africa. The current population of 22,000 is decreasing due to loss of habitat, incidental poisoning, and other factors.<ref name=birdlife>{{Cite web|url=http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/species/factsheet/22695207|title=R\u00fcppell's Vulture (Gyps rueppelli) - BirdLife species factsheet|website=www.birdlife.org|access-date=2016-02-29}}</ref> Known also as R\u00fcppell's griffon, Rueppell's griffon, R\u00fcppell's griffin vulture, Rueppell's vulture and other variants, it is not to be confused with a different species, the [[griffon vulture]] (''Gyps fulvus''). R\u00fcppell's vulture is named in honor of [[Eduard R\u00fcppell]], a 19th-century German explorer, collector, and zoologist.<ref>{{cite book |last=Beolens |first=Bo |title=Whose Bird? Men and Women Commemorated in the Common Names of Birds |year=2003 |publisher=Christopher Helm |location=London|page=294|author2=Watkins, Michael }}</ref> R\u00fcppell's vulture is considered to be the highest-flying bird, with confirmed evidence of a flight at an altitude of {{convert|37000|ft|-2|abbr=on|disp=flip}} above [[sea level]].<ref name=\"laybourne\" />\n\n== Distribution ==\nTheir range extends through the Sahel region of Africa where they can be found in grasslands, mountains, and woodlands. Once considered common in these habitats, the R\u00fcppell's vultures are experiencing steep declines, especially in the Western portion of their range.<ref name=birdlife/> They are relatively slow birds, cruising at {{convert|35|km/h}}, but fly for 6\u20137 hours every day and will fly as far as {{convert|150|km|mi}} from a nest site to find food.\n\n== Description ==\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = vertical\n| header_align = center\n| image1 = VautourCrane2.jpg\n| width1 = 230\n| caption1 = <center>Skull</center>\n| image2 = R\u00fcppell's vulture (Masai Mara, Kenya) - Lip Kee (2).jpg\n| width2 = 180\n| caption2 = <center>Head of an adult</center>\n| background color=;border:none;\n}}\nThese are large vultures, noticeably outsizing the closely related [[white-backed vulture]], with which they often occur in the wild. Adults are {{convert|85|to|103|cm|in|abbr=on}} long,<ref name=birdlife/><ref>''Field Guide to the Birds of East Africa: Kenya, Tanzania, Uganda, Rwanda, Burundi'' by Stevenson & Fanshawe. Elsevier Science (2001), {{ISBN|978-0856610790}}</ref> with a wingspan of {{convert|2.26|to|2.6|m|ft}}, and a weight that ranges from {{convert|6.4|to|9|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.<ref name=birdlife/><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jZTl2rn9uTYC&pg=PA86#v=onepage&q=&f=false |title=Sasol: The Larger Illustrated Guide to Birds of Southern Africa |edition=2nd |first=Ian |last=Sinclair |author2=Phil Hockey  |publisher=Struik Publishers |location=Cape Town |year=2005 |accessdate=July 27, 2013 |isbn=978-1-77007-243-5 |others=Illustrated by Norman Arlott and Peter Hayman}}</ref><ref>''Raptors of the World'' by Ferguson-Lees, Christie, Franklin, Mead & Burton. Houghton Mifflin (2001), {{ISBN|0-618-12762-3}}</ref> Both sexes look alike: mottled brown or black overall with a whitish-brown underbelly and thin, dirty-white fluff covering the head and neck. The base of the neck has a white collar, the eye is yellow or amber, the crop patch deep brown. The head does not have feathers. This is an adaptation that occurred because of the R\u00fcppell vulture's tendency to stick its head inside of its prey when eating. Without the adaptation, feeding would become extremely messy.<ref name=nationalzoo>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalzoo.si.edu/animals/ruppells-griffon-vulture|title=Ruppell's griffon vulture|website=Smithsonian's National Zoo|language=en|access-date=2018-02-18|date=2016-04-25}}</ref> Silent as a rule, they become vocal at their nest and when at a carcass, squealing a great deal. R\u00fcppell's vultures commonly fly at altitudes as high as {{convert|6000|m}}.{{citation needed|date=February 2014}} The birds have a specialized variant of the [[hemoglobin]] alpha<sup>D</sup> subunit; this protein has a great affinity for oxygen, which allows the species to absorb oxygen efficiently despite the low [[partial pressure]] in the upper [[troposphere]].<ref name=\"hemoglobin\" /> A R\u00fcppell's vulture was confirmed to have been ingested by a jet engine of an airplane flying over [[Abidjan]], [[Ivory Coast]] on November 29, 1973 at an altitude of 11,300 m (37,000&nbsp;ft).<ref name=\"laybourne\" /> During August 2010 a R\u00fcppell's vulture escaped a bird of prey site in [[Scotland]], prompting warnings to pilots in the area to watch carefully due to the danger of collision.<ref name=\"VultureMenace\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2010/08/18/vulture_menace|title=Giant vulture menaces Scottish skies|last=Haines|first=Lester|date=2010-08-18|publisher=TheRegister.co.uk|accessdate=2011-05-31}}</ref>\n\n<gallery mode = packed heights = 130px>\nFile:Gyps rueppellii -Nairobi National Park, Kenya-8-4c.jpg|''G. r. rueppellii'' trying to fly<br>[[Nairobi National Park]], Kenya\nFile:R\u00fceppell's griffon vulture (Gyps rueppellii erlangeri) in flight.jpg|''G. r. erlangeri'' in flight<br>[[Ethiopia]]\n</gallery>\n\n== Behavior ==\n\n=== Social ===\nR\u00fcppell's vultures are very social, roosting, nesting, and gathering to feed in large flocks.\n\n=== Feeding ===\n[[File:Gyps rueppellii -Mara river crossing -Africa.jpg|230px|thumb|upright|left|At a [[blue wildebeest]] carcass in the [[Mara River]] at the [[Masai Mara National Reserve|Masai Mara]], Kenya]]\nR\u00fcppell's vultures have several [[adaptation (biology)|adaptation]]s to their diet and are specialized feeders even among the Old World vultures of Africa. They have an especially powerful build and, after the most attractive soft parts of a carcass have been consumed, they will continue with the hide, and even the bones, gorging themselves until they can barely fly. They have backward-pointing spikes on the tongue to help remove meat from bone. Despite their size, power and adaptations, they are not the most dominant vulture in their range, which is considered to be the even larger [[lappet-faced vulture]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://vultures.homestead.com/Ruppells.html | title=Website Disabled}}</ref>\n\n=== Reproduction ===\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = vertical\n| header_align = center\n| image1 = Vautour de R\u00fcppell MHNT.jpg\n| width1 = 180\n| caption1 = <center>Egg</center>\n| image2 = Nestling Sperbergeier.JPG\n| width2 = 180\n| caption2 = <center>Nestling</center>\n| background color=;border:none;\n}}\nThis species of vulture is considered to be monogamous, forming lifelong breeding pairs. After courtship the pair will work together to build a nest using sticks, grass, and leaves that they have gathered or stolen from other nests.<ref name=nationalzoo/><ref name=Animalia>{{Cite web|url=http://animalia.bio/ruppells-vulture|title=R\u00fcppell's Vulture - Facts, Diet, Habitat & Pictures on Animalia.bio|publisher=Animalia|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref> R\u00fcppell's vultures build these nests on cliffs, and in key breeding areas they are known to nest in large colonies containing hundreds of breeding pairs. Both parents share in incubation of their egg over a period of 55 days. Once the chick hatches, both parents will feed and tend to it for about 150 days when it fledges.<ref name=Animalia/><ref name=nationalzoo/><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.arkive.org/rueppells-griffon/gyps-rueppellii/|title = Rueppell's griffon videos, photos and facts - Gyps rueppellii|website = ARKive|language = en-GB|access-date = 2016-02-29|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160322105430/http://www.arkive.org/rueppells-griffon/gyps-rueppellii/|archive-date = 2016-03-22|url-status = dead}}</ref> Young remain dependent on their parents after fledging, not reaching independence until the next breeding season.  During this time they learn how to find and compete for food.\n\n== Status ==\nSince first being assessed by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] during 1988, populations of R\u00fcppell's vulture have decreased. The species has been listed with an [[IUCN Red List]] status of \"near threatened\" since 2007 and the IUCN predicts that populations of the species will continue to decrease.<ref name=\"iucn\"/><ref name=Animalia/> From 2012 to 2014 the R\u00fcppell's vulture was listed as [[Endangered species|Endangered]]; however, the species was reassessed in 2015 and was declared [[Critically endangered|Critically Endangered]].<ref name=\"iucn\"/>\n\nThe R\u00fcppell's vulture is currently listed as an Appendix II species under [[CITES]], which regulates the international trade of animals and plants.<ref name=\"iucn\"/> Under this designation, the R\u00fcppell's vulture is defined as not being immediately at risk of extinction, although the current population could become threatened without a careful regulation of trade.<ref>{{Cite web|url =https://cites.org/eng/app/index.php|title = The CITES Appendices {{!}} CITES|website = cites.org|access-date = 2016-02-29}}</ref>\n\nThe total population of R\u00fcppell's vulture has been estimated to be somewhere around 22,000 individuals, with specific populations in the following areas: [[Tanzania]] (3,000 pairs); [[Kenya]] (2,000 pairs); [[Ethiopia]] (2,000 pairs); [[Sudan]] (2,000 pairs); and West Africa (2,000 pairs).<ref name=Animalia/>\n\nSince 1992, R\u00fcppell's vulture has been occurring as a [[vagrancy in birds|vagrant]] in Spain and Portugal, with annual records since 1997, mainly in the Cadiz / Straits of Gibraltar area, but also further north.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Guti\u00e9rrez |first=Ricard |year=2003 |title=Occurrence of R\u00fcppell's Griffon Vulture in Europe |journal=[[Dutch Birding]] |volume=25 |issue=5 |pages=289\u2013303 |url=https://www.dutchbirding.nl/journal/pdf/DB_2003_25_5.pdf }}</ref>\n\n== Threats ==\n\nR\u00fcppell's vulture populations are experiencing declining populations throughout their entire range. These declines can be attributed to loss of habitat related to human-related land use, poisoning, human use for medicine or meat,<ref>{{Cite journal\n| last = Thiollay\n| first = Jean-Marc\n| date = 2006-04-01\n| title = The decline of raptors in West Africa: long-term assessment and the role of protected areas\n| journal = Ibis\n| language = en\n| volume = 148\n| issue = 2\n| pages = 240\u2013254\n| doi = 10.1111/j.1474-919X.2006.00531.x\n| issn = 1474-919X\n}}</ref> loss of nesting sites, and declining availability of food sources.<ref>{{Cite journal\n| last = Virani\n| first = Munir Z.\n| last2 = Kendall\n| first2 = Corinne\n| last3 = Njoroge\n| first3 = Peter\n| last4 = Thomsett\n| first4 = Simon\n| date = 2011-02-01\n| title = Major declines in the abundance of vultures and other scavenging raptors in and around the Masai Mara ecosystem, Kenya\n| journal = Biological Conservation\n| volume = 144\n| issue = 2\n| pages = 746\u2013752\n| doi = 10.1016/j.biocon.2010.10.024\n}}</ref> Poisoning is currently thought to be the most serious threat to all vulture populations in Africa, although they are not usually the intended target. In events where predators such as lions or hyenas have killed livestock, [[carbofuran]] poisons have been placed into carcasses as retaliation against the predators.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal\n| last = Ogada\n| first = Darcy L.\n| date = 2014-08-01\n| title = The power of poison: pesticide poisoning of Africa's wildlife\n| journal = Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences\n| language = en\n| volume = 1322\n| issue = 1\n| pages = 1\u201320\n| doi = 10.1111/nyas.12405\n| issn = 1749-6632\n| pmid=24716788\n}}</ref> Unfortunately, vultures utilize carrion as their main food source and one carcass has the potential to attract hundreds of birds to feed because this species identifies food by sight. One evaluation of 10 poisoning events found that each event caused the death of 37 to 600 individuals.<ref>{{Cite journal\n| last = Ogada\n| first = Darcy\n| last2 = Shaw\n| first2 = Phil\n| last3 = Beyers\n| first3 = Rene L.\n| last4 = Buij\n| first4 = Ralph\n| last5 = Murn\n| first5 = Campbell\n| last6 = Thiollay\n| first6 = Jean Marc\n| last7 = Beale\n| first7 = Colin M.\n| last8 = Holdo\n| first8 = Ricardo M.\n| last9 = Pomeroy\n| first9 = Derek\n| date = 2015-06-01\n| title = Another Continental Vulture Crisis: Africa's Vultures Collapsing toward Extinction\n| journal = Conservation Letters\n| language = en\n| pages = 89\u201397\n| doi = 10.1111/conl.12182\n| issn = 1755-263X\n| volume=9\n| issue = 2\n| url = https://research-repository.st-andrews.ac.uk/bitstream/10023/8817/1/Ogada_Shaw_et_al_2016_African_vulture_Cons_Letters.pdf\n}}</ref>\n\nKilling of R\u00fcppell's vultures for use in medicine has also greatly contributed to the rapid population decline. In many African cultures, vultures are used for medicine and magic related to superstitions that they are clairvoyant and can be used to increase a child's intelligence.<ref name=\":1\" /> Establishing protected wildlife areas is thought to be an effective route to protect the R\u00fcppell's vulture from extinction. The R\u00fcppell's vulture breed and nests in cliffs in northern and southern Kenya, as well as Tanzania. These breeding and nesting grounds amass huge numbers of R\u00fcppell's vultures which will raise young and forage in the surrounding area.<ref>{{Cite journal\n| last = Virani \n| first = Munir Z. \n| last2 = Monadjem\n| first2 = Ara\n| last3 = Thomsett\n| first3 = Simon\n| last4 = Kendall\n| first4 = Corinne\n| date = 2012-09-01\n| title = Seasonal variation in breeding R\u00fcppell's Vultures Gyps rueppellii at Kwenia, southern Kenya and implications for conservation\n| url = http://journals.cambridge.org/article_S0959270911000505\n| journal = Bird Conservation International\n| volume = 22\n| issue = 3\n| pages = 260\u2013269\n| doi = 10.1017/S0959270911000505\n| issn = 1474-0001\n| doi-access = free\n}}</ref> Considering that the detection rate of R\u00fcppell's vultures was found to be lower in protected areas than outside of them, extending protection to these key breeding sites could help support their population.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* The [[white-backed vulture]], which is slightly smaller and has a shorter neck.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2\n| refs =\n\n\n<ref name=\"laybourne\">{{cite journal | title=Collision between a Vulture and an Aircraft at an Altitude of 37,000 Feet | date=December 1974 | last=Laybourne | first=Roxie C. | journal=The Wilson Bulletin | volume=86 | issue=4 | pages=461\u2013462 | issn=0043-5643 | jstor=4160546 | url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/wilson/v086n04/p0461-p0462.pdf | oclc=46381512}}</ref>\n\n<!--  <ref name=\"size\">{{cite web | url=http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/species/index.html?action=SpcHTMDetails.asp&sid=3376&m=0 | title=Bird Life Species Factsheet&nbsp;\u2014 Rueppell's Vulture ''Gyps rueppellii'' | publisher=Bird Life International | work=Bird Life International website | accessdate=2010-06-10 | year=2010 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090104160056/http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/species/index.html?action=SpcHTMDetails.asp&sid=3376&m=0 | archivedate=2009-01-04 | quote=Identification 85-97 cm. Medium-sized vulture. | url-status=dead}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"iucn_redlist\">{{cite iucn | url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22695207/0 | title=''Gyps rueppellii'' | accessdate=2010-06-09 | year=2010 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111143559/http://www.iucnredlist.org/apps/redlist/details/144351/0 | archivedate=2012-11-11 | quote=This long-lived vulture has experienced a moderately rapid reduction in its global population which is likely to continue. For these reasons it is listed as Near Threatened. | url-status=live}}</ref>-->\n\n<ref name=\"hemoglobin\">{{cite journal | title=High altitude and hemoglobin function in the vultures Gyps rueppellii and Aegypius monachus | date=April 1988 | last=Weber | first=RE | last2=Hiebl | first2=I | last3=Braunitzer | first3=G. | journal=Biological Chemistry Hoppe-Seyler | volume=369 | issue=4 | pages=233\u201340 | issn=0177-3593 | doi=10.1515/bchm3.1988.369.1.233 | pmid=3401328}}</ref>\n\n}}\n* {{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22695207/0 |title=''Gyps rueppellii'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013\n  | ref = {{harvid|IUCN Red List|2012}}\n  }}\n* BirdLife International (2007a): [http://www.birdlife.org/action/science/species/global_species_programme/whats_new.html 2006\u20132007 Red List status changes]. Retrieved 26 August 2007.\n* BirdLife International (2007b): [http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/search/species_search.html?action=SpcHTMDetails.asp&sid=3376&m=0 R\u00fcppell's Vulture - BirdLife Species Factsheet]. Retrieved 26 August 2007.\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Gyps rueppellii}}\n{{wikispecies|Gyps rueppelli}}\n*{{InternetBirdCollection|ruppells-vulture-gyps-rueppelli|R\u00fcppell's vulture}}\n\n{{Vulture}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q648745}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ruppell's vulture}}\n[[Category:Birds of prey of Sub-Saharan Africa]]\n[[Category:Gyps]]\n[[Category:Old World vultures]]\n[[Category:Critically endangered fauna of Africa]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1852]]\n[[Category:Biological records]]<!--Highest flying bird -->\n[[Category:Taxa named by Alfred Brehm]]\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| image = Ruppells Griffon Vulture (4872536563).jpg\n| image_caption = At [[London Zoo]] in London\n| status = CR\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>BirdLife International 2017. ''Gyps rueppelli'' (amended version of 2016 assessment). The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species 2017: e.T22695207A118595083. https://dx.doi.org/10.2305/IUCN.UK.2017-3.RLTS.T22695207A118595083.en. Downloaded on 22 April 2020.</ref>\n| genus = Gyps\n| species = rueppelli\n| authority = ([[Alfred Brehm]], 1852)\n}}\n\n'''R\u00fcppell's vulture''' or '''R\u00fcppell's griffon vulture''' (''Gyps rueppelli''), named after [[Eduard R\u00fcppell]], is a large [[vulture]] that can be found throughout the [[Sahel region]] of central Africa. The current population of 22,000 is decreasing due to loss of habitat, incidental poisoning, and other factors.<ref name=birdlife>{{Cite web|url=http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/species/factsheet/22695207|title=R\u00fcppell's Vulture (Gyps rueppelli) - BirdLife species factsheet|website=www.birdlife.org|access-date=2016-02-29}}</ref> Known also as R\u00fcppell's griffon, Rueppell's griffon, R\u00fcppell's griffin vulture, Rueppell's vulture and other variants, it is not to be confused with a different species, the [[griffon vulture]] (''Gyps fulvus''). R\u00fcppell's vulture is named in honor of [[Eduard R\u00fcppell]], a 19th-century German explorer, collector, and zoologist.<ref>{{cite book |last=Beolens |first=Bo |title=Whose Bird? Men and Women Commemorated in the Common Names of Birds |year=2003 |publisher=Christopher Helm |location=London|page=294|author2=Watkins, Michael }}</ref> R\u00fcppell's vulture is considered to be the highest-flying bird, with confirmed evidence of a flight at an altitude of {{convert|37000|ft|-2|abbr=on|disp=flip}} above [[sea level]].<ref name=\"laybourne\" />\n\n== Distribution ==\nTheir range extends through the Sahel region of Africa where they can be found in grasslands, mountains, and woodlands. Once considered common in these habitats, the R\u00fcppell's vultures are experiencing steep declines, especially in the Western portion of their range.<ref name=birdlife/> They are relatively slow birds, cruising at {{convert|35|km/h}}, but fly for 6\u20137 hours every day and will fly as far as {{convert|150|km|mi}} from a nest site to find food.\n\n== Description ==\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = vertical\n| header_align = center\n| image1 = VautourCrane2.jpg\n| width1 = 230\n| caption1 = <center>Skull</center>\n| image2 = R\u00fcppell's vulture (Masai Mara, Kenya) - Lip Kee (2).jpg\n| width2 = 180\n| caption2 = <center>Head of an adult</center>\n| background color=;border:none;\n}}\nThese are large vultures, noticeably outsizing the closely related [[white-backed vulture]], with which they often occur in the wild. Adults are {{convert|85|to|103|cm|in|abbr=on}} long,<ref name=birdlife/><ref>''Field Guide to the Birds of East Africa: Kenya, Tanzania, Uganda, Rwanda, Burundi'' by Stevenson & Fanshawe. Elsevier Science (2001), {{ISBN|978-0856610790}}</ref> with a wingspan of {{convert|2.26|to|2.6|m|ft}}, and a weight that ranges from {{convert|6.4|to|9|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.<ref name=birdlife/><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jZTl2rn9uTYC&pg=PA86#v=onepage&q=&f=false |title=Sasol: The Larger Illustrated Guide to Birds of Southern Africa |edition=2nd |first=Ian |last=Sinclair |author2=Phil Hockey  |publisher=Struik Publishers |location=Cape Town |year=2005 |accessdate=July 27, 2013 |isbn=978-1-77007-243-5 |others=Illustrated by Norman Arlott and Peter Hayman}}</ref><ref>''Raptors of the World'' by Ferguson-Lees, Christie, Franklin, Mead & Burton. Houghton Mifflin (2001), {{ISBN|0-618-12762-3}}</ref> Both sexes look alike: mottled brown or black overall with a whitish-brown underbelly and thin, dirty-white fluff covering the head and neck. The base of the neck has a white collar, the eye is yellow or amber, the crop patch deep brown. The head does not have feathers. This is an adaptation that occurred because of the R\u00fcppell vulture's tendency to stick its head inside of its prey when eating. Without the adaptation, feeding would become extremely messy.<ref name=nationalzoo>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalzoo.si.edu/animals/ruppells-griffon-vulture|title=Ruppell's griffon vulture|website=Smithsonian's National Zoo|language=en|access-date=2018-02-18|date=2016-04-25}}</ref> Silent as a rule, they become vocal at their nest and when at a carcass, squealing a great deal. R\u00fcppell's vultures commonly fly at altitudes as high as {{convert|6000|m}}.{{citation needed|date=February 2014}} The birds have a specialized variant of the [[hemoglobin]] alpha<sup>D</sup> subunit; this protein has a great affinity for oxygen, which allows the species to absorb oxygen efficiently despite the low [[partial pressure]] in the upper [[troposphere]].<ref name=\"hemoglobin\" /> A R\u00fcppell's vulture was confirmed to have been ingested by a jet engine of an airplane flying over [[Abidjan]], [[Ivory Coast]] on November 29, 1973 at an altitude of 11,300 m (37,000&nbsp;ft).<ref name=\"laybourne\" /> During August 2010 a R\u00fcppell's vulture escaped a bird of prey site in [[Scotland]], prompting warnings to pilots in the area to watch carefully due to the danger of collision.<ref name=\"VultureMenace\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2010/08/18/vulture_menace|title=Giant vulture menaces Scottish skies|last=Haines|first=Lester|date=2010-08-18|publisher=TheRegister.co.uk|accessdate=2011-05-31}}</ref>\n\n<gallery mode = packed heights = 130px>\nFile:Gyps rueppellii -Nairobi National Park, Kenya-8-4c.jpg|''G. r. rueppellii'' trying to fly<br>[[Nairobi National Park]], Kenya\nFile:R\u00fceppell's griffon vulture (Gyps rueppellii erlangeri) in flight.jpg|''G. r. erlangeri'' in flight<br>[[Ethiopia]]\n</gallery>\n\n== Behavior ==\n\n=== Social ===\nR\u00fcppell's vultures are very social, roosting, nesting, and gathering to feed in large flocks.\n\n=== Feeding ===\n[[File:Gyps rueppellii -Mara river crossing -Africa.jpg|230px|thumb|upright|left|At a [[blue wildebeest]] carcass in the [[Mara River]] at the [[Masai Mara National Reserve|Masai Mara]], Kenya]]\nR\u00fcppell's vultures have several [[adaptation (biology)|adaptation]]s to their diet and are specialized feeders even among the Old World vultures of Africa. They have an especially powerful build and, after the most attractive soft parts of a carcass have been consumed, they will continue with the hide, and even the bones, gorging themselves until they can barely fly. They have backward-pointing spikes on the tongue to help remove meat from bone. Despite their size, power and adaptations, they are not the most dominant vulture in their range, which is considered to be the even larger [[lappet-faced vulture]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://vultures.homestead.com/Ruppells.html | title=Website Disabled}}</ref>\n\n=== Reproduction ===\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = vertical\n| header_align = center\n| image1 = Vautour de R\u00fcppell MHNT.jpg\n| width1 = 180\n| caption1 = <center>Egg</center>\n| image2 = Nestling Sperbergeier.JPG\n| width2 = 180\n| caption2 = <center>Nestling</center>\n| background color=;border:none;\n}}\nThis species of vulture is considered to be monogamous, forming lifelong breeding pairs. After courtship the pair will work together to build a nest using sticks, grass, and leaves that they have gathered or stolen from other nests.<ref name=nationalzoo/><ref name=Animalia>{{Cite web|url=http://animalia.bio/ruppells-vulture|title=R\u00fcppell's Vulture - Facts, Diet, Habitat & Pictures on Animalia.bio|publisher=Animalia|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref> R\u00fcppell's vultures build these nests on cliffs, and in key breeding areas they are known to nest in large colonies containing hundreds of breeding pairs. Both parents share in incubation of their egg over a period of 55 days. Once the chick hatches, both parents will feed and tend to it for about 150 days when it fledges.<ref name=Animalia/><ref name=nationalzoo/><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.arkive.org/rueppells-griffon/gyps-rueppellii/|title = Rueppell's griffon videos, photos and facts - Gyps rueppellii|website = ARKive|language = en-GB|access-date = 2016-02-29|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160322105430/http://www.arkive.org/rueppells-griffon/gyps-rueppellii/|archive-date = 2016-03-22|url-status = dead}}</ref> Young remain dependent on their parents after fledging, not reaching independence until the next breeding season.  During this time they learn how to find and compete for food.\n\n== Status ==\nSince first being assessed by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] during 1988, populations of R\u00fcppell's vulture have decreased. The species has been listed with an [[IUCN Red List]] status of \"near threatened\" since 2007 and the IUCN predicts that populations of the species will continue to decrease.<ref name=\"iucn\"/><ref name=Animalia/> From 2012 to 2014 the R\u00fcppell's vulture was listed as [[Endangered species|Endangered]]; however, the species was reassessed in 2015 and was declared [[Critically endangered|Critically Endangered]].<ref name=\"iucn\"/>\n\nThe R\u00fcppell's vulture is currently listed as an Appendix II species under [[CITES]], which regulates the international trade of animals and plants.<ref name=\"iucn\"/> Under this designation, the R\u00fcppell's vulture is defined as not being immediately at risk of extinction, although the current population could become threatened without a careful regulation of trade.<ref>{{Cite web|url =https://cites.org/eng/app/index.php|title = The CITES Appendices {{!}} CITES|website = cites.org|access-date = 2016-02-29}}</ref>\n\nThe total population of R\u00fcppell's vulture has been estimated to be somewhere around 22,000 individuals, with specific populations in the following areas: [[Tanzania]] (3,000 pairs); [[Kenya]] (2,000 pairs); [[Ethiopia]] (2,000 pairs); [[Sudan]] (2,000 pairs); and West Africa (2,000 pairs).<ref name=Animalia/>\n\nSince 1992, R\u00fcppell's vulture has been occurring as a [[vagrancy in birds|vagrant]] in Spain and Portugal, with annual records since 1997, mainly in the Cadiz / Straits of Gibraltar area, but also further north.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Guti\u00e9rrez |first=Ricard |year=2003 |title=Occurrence of R\u00fcppell's Griffon Vulture in Europe |journal=[[Dutch Birding]] |volume=25 |issue=5 |pages=289\u2013303 |url=https://www.dutchbirding.nl/journal/pdf/DB_2003_25_5.pdf }}</ref>\n\n== Threats ==\n\nR\u00fcppell's vulture populations are experiencing declining populations throughout their entire range. These declines can be attributed to loss of habitat related to human-related land use, poisoning, human use for medicine or meat,<ref>{{Cite journal\n| last = Thiollay\n| first = Jean-Marc\n| date = 2006-04-01\n| title = The decline of raptors in West Africa: long-term assessment and the role of protected areas\n| journal = Ibis\n| language = en\n| volume = 148\n| issue = 2\n| pages = 240\u2013254\n| doi = 10.1111/j.1474-919X.2006.00531.x\n| issn = 1474-919X\n}}</ref> loss of nesting sites, and declining availability of food sources.<ref>{{Cite journal\n| last = Virani\n| first = Munir Z.\n| last2 = Kendall\n| first2 = Corinne\n| last3 = Njoroge\n| first3 = Peter\n| last4 = Thomsett\n| first4 = Simon\n| date = 2011-02-01\n| title = Major declines in the abundance of vultures and other scavenging raptors in and around the Masai Mara ecosystem, Kenya\n| journal = Biological Conservation\n| volume = 144\n| issue = 2\n| pages = 746\u2013752\n| doi = 10.1016/j.biocon.2010.10.024\n}}</ref> Poisoning is currently thought to be the most serious threat to all vulture populations in Africa, although they are not usually the intended target. In events where predators such as lions or hyenas have killed livestock, [[carbofuran]] poisons have been placed into carcasses as retaliation against the predators.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal\n| last = Ogada\n| first = Darcy L.\n| date = 2014-08-01\n| title = The power of poison: pesticide poisoning of Africa's wildlife\n| journal = Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences\n| language = en\n| volume = 1322\n| issue = 1\n| pages = 1\u201320\n| doi = 10.1111/nyas.12405\n| issn = 1749-6632\n| pmid=24716788\n}}</ref> Unfortunately, vultures utilize carrion as their main food source and one carcass has the potential to attract hundreds of birds to feed because this species identifies food by sight. One evaluation of 10 poisoning events found that each event caused the death of 37 to 600 individuals.<ref>{{Cite journal\n| last = Ogada\n| first = Darcy\n| last2 = Shaw\n| first2 = Phil\n| last3 = Beyers\n| first3 = Rene L.\n| last4 = Buij\n| first4 = Ralph\n| last5 = Murn\n| first5 = Campbell\n| last6 = Thiollay\n| first6 = Jean Marc\n| last7 = Beale\n| first7 = Colin M.\n| last8 = Holdo\n| first8 = Ricardo M.\n| last9 = Pomeroy\n| first9 = Derek\n| date = 2015-06-01\n| title = Another Continental Vulture Crisis: Africa's Vultures Collapsing toward Extinction\n| journal = Conservation Letters\n| language = en\n| pages = 89\u201397\n| doi = 10.1111/conl.12182\n| issn = 1755-263X\n| volume=9\n| issue = 2\n| url = https://research-repository.st-andrews.ac.uk/bitstream/10023/8817/1/Ogada_Shaw_et_al_2016_African_vulture_Cons_Letters.pdf\n}}</ref>\n\nKilling of R\u00fcppell's vultures for use in medicine has also greatly contributed to the rapid population decline. In many African cultures, vultures are used for medicine and magic related to superstitions that they are clairvoyant and can be used to increase a child's intelligence.<ref name=\":1\" /> Establishing protected wildlife areas is thought to be an effective route to protect the R\u00fcppell's vulture from extinction. The R\u00fcppell's vulture breed and nests in cliffs in northern and southern Kenya, as well as Tanzania. These breeding and nesting grounds amass huge numbers of R\u00fcppell's vultures which will raise young and forage in the surrounding area.<ref>{{Cite journal\n| last = Virani \n| first = Munir Z. \n| last2 = Monadjem\n| first2 = Ara\n| last3 = Thomsett\n| first3 = Simon\n| last4 = Kendall\n| first4 = Corinne\n| date = 2012-09-01\n| title = Seasonal variation in breeding R\u00fcppell's Vultures Gyps rueppellii at Kwenia, southern Kenya and implications for conservation\n| url = http://journals.cambridge.org/article_S0959270911000505\n| journal = Bird Conservation International\n| volume = 22\n| issue = 3\n| pages = 260\u2013269\n| doi = 10.1017/S0959270911000505\n| issn = 1474-0001\n| doi-access = free\n}}</ref> Considering that the detection rate of R\u00fcppell's vultures was found to be lower in protected areas than outside of them, extending protection to these key breeding sites could help support their population.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* The [[white-backed vulture]], which is slightly smaller and has a shorter neck.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2\n| refs =\n\n\n<ref name=\"laybourne\">{{cite journal | title=Collision between a Vulture and an Aircraft at an Altitude of 37,000 Feet | date=December 1974 | last=Laybourne | first=Roxie C. | journal=The Wilson Bulletin | volume=86 | issue=4 | pages=461\u2013462 | issn=0043-5643 | jstor=4160546 | url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/wilson/v086n04/p0461-p0462.pdf | oclc=46381512}}</ref>\n\n<!--  <ref name=\"size\">{{cite web | url=http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/species/index.html?action=SpcHTMDetails.asp&sid=3376&m=0 | title=Bird Life Species Factsheet&nbsp;\u2014 Rueppell's Vulture ''Gyps rueppellii'' | publisher=Bird Life International | work=Bird Life International website | accessdate=2010-06-10 | year=2010 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090104160056/http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/species/index.html?action=SpcHTMDetails.asp&sid=3376&m=0 | archivedate=2009-01-04 | quote=Identification 85-97 cm. Medium-sized vulture. | url-status=dead}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"iucn_redlist\">{{cite iucn | url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22695207/0 | title=''Gyps rueppellii'' | accessdate=2010-06-09 | year=2010 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111143559/http://www.iucnredlist.org/apps/redlist/details/144351/0 | archivedate=2012-11-11 | quote=This long-lived vulture has experienced a moderately rapid reduction in its global population which is likely to continue. For these reasons it is listed as Near Threatened. | url-status=live}}</ref>-->\n\n<ref name=\"hemoglobin\">{{cite journal | title=High altitude and hemoglobin function in the vultures Gyps rueppellii and Aegypius monachus | date=April 1988 | last=Weber | first=RE | last2=Hiebl | first2=I | last3=Braunitzer | first3=G. | journal=Biological Chemistry Hoppe-Seyler | volume=369 | issue=4 | pages=233\u201340 | issn=0177-3593 | doi=10.1515/bchm3.1988.369.1.233 | pmid=3401328}}</ref>\n\n}}\n* {{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22695207/0 |title=''Gyps rueppellii'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013\n  | ref = {{harvid|IUCN Red List|2012}}\n  }}\n* BirdLife International (2007a): [http://www.birdlife.org/action/science/species/global_species_programme/whats_new.html 2006\u20132007 Red List status changes]. Retrieved 26 August 2007.\n* BirdLife International (2007b): [http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/search/species_search.html?action=SpcHTMDetails.asp&sid=3376&m=0 R\u00fcppell's Vulture - BirdLife Species Factsheet]. Retrieved 26 August 2007.\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Gyps rueppellii}}\n{{wikispecies|Gyps rueppelli}}\n*{{InternetBirdCollection|ruppells-vulture-gyps-rueppelli|R\u00fcppell's vulture}}\n\n{{Vulture}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q648745}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ruppell's vulture}}\n[[Category:Birds of prey of Sub-Saharan Africa]]\n[[Category:Gyps]]\n[[Category:Old World vultures]]\n[[Category:Critically endangered fauna of Africa]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1852]]\n[[Category:Biological records]]<!--Highest flying bird -->\n[[Category:Taxa named by Alfred Brehm]]\n", "name_user": "Declangi", "label": "safe", "comment": "IUCN status: use cite iucn", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R%C3%BCppell%27s_vulture"}
{"title_page": "George Jellicoe, 2nd Earl Jellicoe", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = The Earl Jellicoe\n| honorific-suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|KBE|DSO|MC|PC|FRS|FRGS}}\n| image = George Jellicoe, 2nd Earl Jellicoe.jpg\n| imagesize = 200px\n| alt = George Jellicoe, 2nd Earl Jellicoe (1960's photo by Phillippa, Countess Jellicoe)\n| caption = George Jellicoe, 2nd Earl Jellicoe<br>(1960s photo by Phillippa, Countess Jellicoe)\n| office2 = [[Leader of the House of Lords]]<br/>[[Lord Privy Seal|Lord Keeper of the Privy Seal]]\n| term_start2 = 20 June 1970\n| term_end2 = 23 May 1973\n| monarch2 = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Edward Heath]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Edward Shackleton, Baron Shackleton|The Lord Shackleton]]\n| successor2 = [[David Hennessy, 3rd Baron Windlesham|The Lord Windlesham]]\n| office4 = [[First Lord of the Admiralty]]\n| term_start4 = 22 October 1963\n| term_end4 = 1 April 1964\n| monarch4 = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| primeminister4 = [[Alec Douglas-Home|Sir Alec Douglas Home]]\n| predecessor4 = [[Peter Carington, 6th Baron Carrington|The Lord Carrington]]\n| successor4 = [[Elizabeth II]]<br/><small>as [[Lord High Admiral of the United Kingdom|Lord High Admiral]]\n| office3 = [[Minister of Defence|Minister of State for Navy]]\n| term_start3 = 1 April 1964\n| term_end3 = 16 October 1964\n| monarch3 = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Alec Douglas-Home|Sir Alec Douglas Home]]\n| office5 = [[Under-Secretary of State for the Home Department|Minister of State for Home Affairs]]\n| term_start5 = 17 July 1962\n| term_end5 = 21 October 1963\n| monarch5 = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| primeminister5 = [[Harold Macmillan]]\n| predecessor5 = [[David Renton]]\n| successor5 = [[Patrick Vanden-Bempde-Johnstone, 4th Baron Derwent|The Lord Derwent]]\n| office6 = [[Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government|Parliamentary Secretary to the Minister of Housing and Local Government]]\n| term_start6 = 27 June 1961\n| term_end6 = 16 July 1962\n| monarch6 = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| primeminister6 = [[Harold Macmillan]]\n| predecessor6 = [[Keith Joseph]]\n| successor6 = [[Frederick Corfield]]\n| office7 = [[Lord-in-waiting]]<br>[[Government Whip]]\n| monarch7 = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| primeminister7 = [[Harold Macmillan]]\n| term_start7 = 8 February 1961\n| term_end7 = 27 June 1961\n| predecessor7 = [[Henry Bathurst, 8th Earl Bathurst|The Earl Bathurst]]\n| successor7 = [[Bertram Bowyer, 2nd Baron Denham|The Lord Denham]]\n| office15 = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n| term_start15 = 17 November 1999\n| term_end15 = 22 February 2007<br>[[Life Peerage]]\n| term_start16 = 25 July 1939\n| term_end16 = 11 November 1999<br>[[Hereditary Peerage]]\n| predecessor16 = [[John Jellicoe, 1st Earl Jellicoe|The 1st Earl Jellicoe]]\n| successor16 = ''[[House of Lords Act 1999|Seat abolished ]]''\n| birth_date = 4 April 1918\n| birth_place = [[Hatfield, Hertfordshire|Hatfield]], [[Hertfordshire]]<br/>[[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2007|2|22|1918|4|4|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Fosbury|Tidcombe]], [[Wiltshire]]<br/>[[United Kingdom]]\n| restingplace = \n| restingplacecoordinates = \n| birthname = \n| citizenship = \n| nationality = UK\n| party = [[Conservative Party (United Kingdom)|Conservative]]\n| otherparty = \n| spouse = \n| relations = \n| children = eight\n| residence = Tidcombe\n| alma_mater = Winchester\n| occupation = Politician, businessman\n| committees = \n| portfolio = \n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n| allegiance = United Kingdom\n| branch = [[British Army]]\n| unit = [[Coldstream Guards]]<br/>[[Special Boat Service]]\n| serviceyears = \n| rank = [[Brigadier]]\n| battles = [[Second World War]]\n| mawards = [[Distinguished Service Order]]<br/>[[Military Cross]]<br/>[[Mentioned in Despatches]] (3)\n}}\n'''George Patrick John Rushworth Jellicoe, 2nd Earl Jellicoe, Baron Jellicoe of Southampton''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|KBE|DSO|MC|PC|FRS|FRGS}}<ref name=\"frs\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Waldegrave | first1 = W. | authorlink1 = William Waldegrave, Baron Waldegrave of North Hill| doi = 10.1098/rsbm.2008.0004 | title = [[George Patrick John Rushworth Jellicoe, 2nd Earl Jellicoe|George Jellicoe, 2nd Earl Jellicoe]]. 4 April 1918 \u2013 22 February 2007 | journal = [[Biographical Memoirs of Fellows of the Royal Society]] | volume = 54 | pages = 169 | year = 2008 | pmid =  | pmc = | doi-access = free }}</ref> (4 April 1918&nbsp;\u2013 22 February 2007) was a British politician, diplomat and businessman.\n\nLord Jellicoe was the only son but sixth and youngest child of [[John Jellicoe, 1st Earl Jellicoe]], who was a [[First World War]] naval commander, commander at the Battle of [[Battle of Jutland|Jutland]], and [[Admiral of the Fleet (Royal Navy)|Admiral of the Fleet]], and his wife Florence Gwendoline (died 1964), who was the second daughter of [[Sir Charles Cayzer, 1st Baronet|Sir Charles Cayzer]], 1st [[Baronet|Bt.]], of [[Gartmore]], [[Perthshire]]. George Jellicoe was one of the longest-serving parliamentarians in the world, being a member of the [[House of Lords]] for 68 years (1939\u20132007).{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n\n==Early life==\nJellicoe was born at Hatfield and was christened on 29 July 1918 by the [[Most Reverend|Most Rev.]] and [[The Right Honourable|Right Hon.]] [[Cosmo Lang]], 89th [[Archbishop of York]], while [[George V of Great Britain and Ireland|King George V]] (represented by [[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]] [[Stanley Colville|Sir Stanley Colville]]) and HRH [[Princess Patricia of Connaught]] (later known as Lady Patricia Ramsay) stood sponsor as two of his godparents. The others were: Miss Lilian Lear, Admiral [[Lionel Halsey|Sir Lionel Halsey]] (Third Sea Lord), Mr. Eustace Burrows (cousin), [[Baron Rotherwick|Major Herbert Cayzer]] (uncle), and [[The Reverend|The Rev.]] Frederick G. G. Jellicoe (uncle, and Rector of [[New Alresford]]).\n\nMuch of his childhood was spent at St Lawrence Hall, near [[Ventnor]] on the [[Isle of Wight]]; at [[St Peter's Court]], a prep school at [[Broadstairs]], Kent; in London; and in the [[Dominion of New Zealand]], where his father was [[viceroy]] with the title of [[Governor-General of New Zealand|Governor-General]] between 1921 and 1924. He was educated at [[Winchester College]], where he was styled and known as [[Earl Jellicoe|Viscount Brocas]]. He won the Vere Herbert Smith history prize and secured an exhibition to [[Trinity College, Cambridge]] (matriculated 1936. BA, Modern History tripos 1939, but awarded 1966). He was chairman of the [[Pitt Club]], and his tutor [[Steven Runciman]] became a lifelong friend.\n\n==Second World War==\nIn October 1939, the young Jellicoe was a cadet in the first wartime intake at the [[Royal Military College, Sandhurst|RMC, Sandhurst]].<ref>Windmill, Lorna Almonds. ''A British Achilles: George, 2nd Earl Jellicoe KBE DSO MC FRS 20th Century Soldier, Politician, Statesman''. Barnsley: Pen & Sword Military, 2008. {{ISBN|9781844158812}} {{OCLC|244652725}} Page 9.</ref> He was commissioned into the [[Coldstream Guards]] on 23 March 1940, before joining [[No. 8 (Guards) Commando]], with whom on 31 January 1941 he sailed to the Middle East with [[Robert Laycock|Colonel Bob Laycock's]] [[Layforce]] (whose commando officers included [[Evelyn Waugh]], [[Randolph Churchill]], [[Philip Russell Rendel Dunne|Philip Dunne]], [[Carol Mather]], [[David Stirling]], and many distinguished others). He served with '' L Detachment'' (from April 1942) (with some of the above and [[Stephen Hastings]]), which was the nucleus of the [[Special Air Service]]. He was [[Mentioned in Despatches|mentioned in despatches]] thrice, and wounded (bullet in shoulder) once whilst with the 3rd Battalion, Coldstream Guards, in 22 (Guards) Brigade in the Western Desert in January 1941. He won the DSO in November 1942 for [[Operation Albumen|operating on a raid]] that claimed to have blown up more than 20 German aircraft ([[Junkers Ju 88|Ju 88s]]) on [[Heraklion]] airfield, Crete, that June:\n<blockquote>\nHis cool and resolute leadership, skill and courage throughout this very hazardous operation were mainly responsible for the high measure of success achieved. He&nbsp;... placed charges on the enemy aircraft and brought off the survivors after the four [[Free French Forces|Free French]] members of the party had been betrayed and killed or captured.<ref>''[[London Gazette]]'', 5 November 1942, quoted from L. Almonds Windmill, page 49</ref>\n</blockquote>\nIn September 1943, Jellicoe was sent to the Italian-held island of [[Rhodes]] to negotiate with the Italian Admiral [[Inigo Campioni]] for the surrender of his forces to the Allies. However, negotiations were pre-empted by a surprise German attack on the island on 9 September. He was able to escape from Rhodes during the resulting chaos while the Italian garrison was captured by the German invasion force. This was part of the [[Dodecanese Campaign]].\n\nIn 1943, he was named Commander of the [[Special Boat Service|Special Boat Regiment ''Middle East'']] and he was promoted to the rank of lieutenant-colonel. He was eventually promoted to brigadier.<ref>Churchill's secret warriors. Damien Lewis 2014.</ref> For the remainder of the war, his SBS command conducted secretive and dangerous operations along the coasts of Italy and Yugoslavia. In 1944, he won the MC for one of these actions. At the end of the war, Jellicoe was among the first Allied soldiers to enter German-occupied [[Athens]], beating the communist-controlled guerrillas [[Greek People's Liberation Army|ELAS]], to create a pro-Allied presence in the capital.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.independent.co.uk/people/obituaries/article2300414.ece |date=24 February 2007 |title=Earl Jellicoe |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071119112513/http://news.independent.co.uk/people/obituaries/article2300414.ece |archive-date=19 November 2007 |newspaper=[[The Independent]] }}</ref>\n\nYears later, when First Lord of the Admiralty, Jellicoe told at least one reporter, \"The only serious military distinction I ever achieved was having a new type of assault boat named after me. It was called I am ashamed to say, the Jellicoe Inflatable Intruder Mark One.\"\n\nIn March 1944, Lord Jellicoe married Patricia Christine O'Kane (October 1917 \u2013 March 2012),<ref>{{cite web|title=Patricia Christine Jellicoe (n\u00e9e O'Kane), Countess Jellicoe (1917\u20132012)|url=http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp85238/patricia-christine-jellicoe-nee-okane-countess-jellicoe|publisher=National Portrait Gallery}}</ref> who was employed at the [[British Embassy]] in [[Beirut]]. She had been born and raised in [[Shanghai]] and was the daughter of a [[Greenock]]-born Irish father and an English mother. Patricia, Countess Jellicoe (popularly known as Patsy Jellicoe), would remain married to Lord Jellicoe until 1966, when they divorced. They had two sons and two daughters together, the eldest son being the [[Earl Jellicoe|3rd Earl Jellicoe]].\n\n==HM Foreign Service 1947\u20131958==\nSoon after the war Lord Jellicoe joined His Majesty's [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Foreign Service]], (appointed a Foreign Service Officer, Grade 8 in the Senior Branch of the Foreign Service, 10 September 1947). He served in London (German political department, Third Secretary); [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]] (Third Secretary, when [[Donald Duart Maclean|Donald Maclean]] of the [[Cambridge Five|''Cambridge five'']] was Head of Chancery, and then as one of the 11 Second Secretaries with [[Kim Philby|H. A. R. Philby]], seeing [[NATO]] signed on 4 April 1949, all when [[Oliver Franks, Baron Franks|Sir Oliver Franks]] was Ambassador); transferred to [[Brussels]] 10 September 1951 (Head of Chancery) acted as Charg\u00e9 d'Affaires in 1952); London (no. 2 in Northern department in charge of the Soviet Desk from September 1953); and Baghdad from January 1956 (First Secretary and Deputy Secretary General of [[Baghdad Pact|the Baghdad Pact]] Organisation). The [[Suez Crisis]] (from July 1956) wrecked everything the Pact was trying to achieve; Jellicoe was appalled by British policy and came close to resigning (L. Windmill p.&nbsp;136).\n\nJellicoe eventually left the Foreign Office in March 1958, after marital difficulties had caused an impasse (February 1958, [[Permanent Secretary]] Sir Derek Hoyar-Millar wrote; 'You have a choice of ceasing your relationship with this lady [Philippa Dunne] or changing your job'). He became a director of the Cayzer dynasty's [[Clan Line]] Steamers (cargo ships), and [[Union-Castle Line|Union Castle Steamship Co.]] (passengers).\n\nHowever, enthusiasm for his mother's family's businesses ultimately gave way to the call of the [[Palace of Westminster]], where, back from [[Iraq]], he took the [[Oath of Allegiance (United Kingdom)|Oath]] in the [[House of Lords|Lords]] on 3 December 1957, in the Third Session of the [[41st Parliament of the United Kingdom|41st Parliament]].\n\n==House of Lords and 1960s==\n[[File:JellicoeGrin.jpg|thumb|Jellicoe during a skiing holiday.]]\n[[File:JellicoeSkiing.jpg|thumb|Jellicoe skiing in France.]]\nHaving first sat in parliament on 25 July 1939, Jellicoe waited until 28 July 1958 to make his maiden speech in the [[House of Lords]] during a debate entitled \"The International Situation: The Middle East\". He spoke from the [[cross-bencher|Cross-Benches]] about the Baghdad Pact and Iraq:\n{{quote|...&nbsp;Having lately lived for a year or so in [[Baghdad]] I confess that I have not been untouched by the charm of that ugly yet fascinating city, and, if I may say so, of the diverse peoples of Iraq&nbsp;... Like all your Lordships, I felt, and feel, a deep sense of shock, indeed revulsion, at the brutal butchery of the young King and his family, and of that great, and greatly human, statesman, [[Nuri as-Said|Nuri Pasha]]. I have also been shocked by the tendency which one sees current at the moment to write off the Nuri regime as decadent, feudal and corrupt. That picture, in my view, is a travesty of the truth&nbsp;... As part of the admirable development programme which the Nuri regime was carrying through there was a large schools programme. These schools were built for the purpose your Lordships might expect-to educate Iraqis in. But the Iraqis did not believe that; they thought-it was a very widespread belief which one could not eradicate-that these schools were camouflaged barracks intended for the British Army when they reoccupied Iraq. These are the sorts of 'ingrowing toenails' in the Iraqi consciousness which I feel we must try to eradicate, to draw out&nbsp;...}}\n\nBy October 1958 he had joined the Conservatives, in the Lords a natural home for such a ''distinctly pink''<ref>[[Piers Dixon]] in Philip Ziegler & Desmond Seward (eds): ''Brooks's: A Social History'', 1991.</ref>{{clarification needed|date=May 2019}} [[British Whig Party|Whig]], who gave him the honour of moving \"an humble Address in Reply to Her Majesty's Most Gracious Speech\"\n{{quote|My Lords, I am acutely, indeed somewhat painfully, conscious of the great honour which the noble Earl [[Alec Douglas-Home|Lord Home]]'' (i.e. Alec Douglas-Home)'', the Leader of the House, has done me in inviting me to move the humble Address to Her Majesty. The last time that I addressed your Lordships' House was from the platonic sanctity of the Cross-Benches. I then had the aesthetic pleasure of seeing your Lordships in profile: I now have the equal pleasure of seeing some of your Lordships full face. I do not know why I find myself in this particular hot spot this afternoon. I can only surmise that the noble Earl, fishing for a good large Tory trout, cast over the Cross-Benches for an ex-Ambassador and hooked an ex-First Secretary by mistake.}}\n\nOn 7 May 1959, he asked a prescient starred question on the Planning of Motorways:\n{{quote|...&nbsp;Just as the Roman roads are with us to-day, so these great new roads may be with our successors 1,000 years hence. With this in mind, can my noble friend assure us, first, that the advice of the Advisory Committee [on the Landscape Treatment of Trunk Roads] to which he referred will in all cases in future be sought at a very early stage in the planning of these new roads;  and, secondly, that permanent professional advice will be enlisted from the outset at the planning, the reconnaissance stage, in order to ensure that these great new roads blend as harmoniously as possible with the land-scape through which they pass?}}\n\nOn 20 July 1959 he initiated a debate on ''Western Aid for Uncommitted Countries'', and by January 1961 he was a [[Lord-in-waiting]] to H.M. the Queen, a Government Whip, in [[Harold Macmillan|Macmillan]]'s administration. He was Joint Parliamentary Secretary, Ministry of Housing and Local Government June 1961 \u2013 July 1962; Minister of State, Home Office July 1962 \u2013 October 1963; [[First Lord of the Admiralty]] October 1963 \u2013 April 1964; [[Minister of Defence for the Royal Navy]] April\u2013October 1964; delegate to the [[Council of Europe]] and the Western European Union (WEU) 1965\u20131967; president of the National Federation of Housing Societies 1965\u20131970; a governor of the [[Centre for Environmental Studies]] 1967\u20131970; chairman of the British Advisory Committee on Oil Pollution at Sea 1968; chairman of the third International Conference on oil pollution of the sea 1968; an hon. vice-president of [[Tory Reform Group|PEST]] (Pressure for Economic and Social Toryism); and deputy Leader of the Opposition in the Lords 1967\u20131970. From April 1967 Lords Jellicoe and [[Peter Carington, 6th Baron Carrington|Carrington]] represented the Conservatives in the Lords on the Inter-Party conference group on Lords' reform, which came up with the unsuccessful Parliament (No.2) Bill (1968\u20131969). Leading the debate for the (Conservative) Opposition in November 1968 Jellicoe said:\n{{quote|We hold that a grave constitutional change of this kind should not be brought into effect in the dying years of a discredited Government&nbsp;... a viable Upper House has an essential part to play in our parliamentary structure. We now have a quite considerable constitutional prize in our grasp, the opportunity to build a really viable Upper House on the basis of a broad consensus of support from all Parties&nbsp;... (19 November 1968, Hansard via L. Windmill).}}\n\nDuring the late 1960s he worked in the [[City of London]] where he became chairman of British Reserve Insurance and a director of [[S. G. Warburg & Co.|S G Warburg (Finance and Development) Ltd]].\n\n==Cabinet minister and resignation==\nIn [[Edward Heath|Ted Heath's]] [[Conservative Government 1970-1974|administration]] he was Minister in charge for the Civil Service Department (CSD), [[Lord Privy Seal]] (as such he was eighth on the [[Order of precedence in England and Wales|Roll of The Lords]]) and [[Leader of the House of Lords]] from 20 June 1970 until 24 May 1973.\n\nHaving earlier re-established relations with the miners' union leaders in February 1972, Heath appointed Jellicoe \"energy supremo\" to restore power supplies around the time of the [[Three-Day Week]] and had him set up and chair a Civil Contingencies Unit, which was, when an internal crisis arose, to operate through \"COBRA\" ([[Cabinet Office Briefing Rooms]]).\n\nIn June 1972 Jellicoe was sent to lead [[Concorde]]'s first sales expedition. As Alan Trengove in ''My Lord, the super salesman'', in the Australian ''The Sun'' of 22 June 1972 put it,\n{{quote|There has probably never been a sales team [122 strong] quite like the aristocratic British contingent that is trying to sell the Anglo-French supersonic Concorde to Qantas&nbsp;... The earl is an astute salesman who has obviously done his homework&nbsp;... He has the stamina to address a couple of press conferences each day as well as make daily speeches&nbsp;... cultivate politicians, DCA personnel and Qantas bosses. At fifty-four, the earl looks a rugged character. He has a strong broad chin and speaks with a directness that appeals to Australians&nbsp;... Inevitably, he is beginning to be known in Australia as 'Aeroplane Jellicoe'. If he can land the Concorde deal with Qantas, they may soon be singing in Britain:\n::''I like Aeroplane Jellicoe''\n::''Aeroplane Jellicoe for me.''\n::''I like it for dinner, like it for tea,''\n::''Aeroplane Jellicoe has goodness for me''.}}\n\nTrengove considered [[George Edwards (aviation)|Sir George Edwards]] and Sir Geoffrey Tuttle \"equally impressive members of the sales team\". (Supersonic flights were on the prototype Concorde G-BSST, certificate signed by [[Brian Trubshaw]], and dated 15 June 1972). Jellicoe, with the help of his very experienced Chief Whip, the second [[Earl St Aldwyn|Earl St. Aldwyn]], steered the [[European Communities Act 1972 (UK)|''European Communities Act'' (1972)]] through the Lords, allowing no amendments. The ''Industrial Relations Act'' was another legislative highlight.\n\nIn May 1973 Jellicoe admitted \"some casual affairs\" with [[call girl]]s (from ''Mayfair Escorts'') in the wake of an accidental confusion with [[Antony Lambton|Lord Lambton]]'s prostitution scandal.<ref>{{cite news |first=Alvin |last=Shuster |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1973/05/27/archives/a-proper-government-scandal-britain.html |title=A Proper Government Scandal; Britain |date=27 May 1973 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] }}</ref> The name Jellicoe seems to have emerged as a result of a connection between Lambton, the madame Norma Levy, and a tenement house or community hall in [[Somers Town, London|Somers Town]] in the London district of St. Pancras called ''Jellicoe'' Hall or House, after Basil Jellicoe (1899\u20131935) the housing reformer, and priest. The word Jellicoe was seen in Levy's notebook, and a connection was assumed to the Minister rather than the building; a structure named after the earl's distant cousin, and one that may have been opened by the Admiral himself in June 1928.\n\nThe resignation ended Jellicoe's third career in government service. After the resignation (over his marginal involvement in a minor indiscretion) [[Richard Crossman]], writing in ''The Times'', 30 May 1973 (page 18), described Jellicoe as:\n{{quote|...&nbsp;among the bravest, ablest, most decent members of the Heath Government&nbsp;... [B]ut need the Prime Minister have got rid of Lord Jellicoe in such peremptory style? Could he not have refused his resignation until all the facts were available?}}\n\nOn return from the Whitsun recess, tributes were paid in the Lords to their departed leader: The (Labour Party) Opposition leader and Jellicoe's predecessor as Lord Privy Seal, [[Edward Shackleton, Baron Shackleton|Lord Shackleton]] said:\n{{quote|Lord Jellicoe&nbsp;... has been as good a leader of this House as we have known [cheers].. I don't think we can let him go \u2013 though happily this is not an epitaph \u2013 without expressing our very deep sorrow to the House and to the country [cheers]&nbsp;... with immense thoroughness, patience and personal sensitivity Lord Jellicoe fulfilled his role as Leader of your Lordships House [cheers]&nbsp;... we [Lords Byers and Shackleton] found him an admirable open-minded and wise colleague; my Lords, I believe that we and the country have suffered a grievous loss&nbsp;... (Hansard, 5 June 1973, and ''The Times'', 6 June 1973, for the cheers)}}\n\nLord Byers for the Liberal Party added: \"we regret bitterly his resignation&nbsp;... He was a reforming innovator and the House owes a great deal more than it probably knows to the interest he took in this House and to his initiatives.\" (Hansard, 5 June 1973)\n\nFrom the Cross-Benches [[William Strang, 1st Baron Strang|Lord Strang]] added:\n{{quote|To some of us it had been a comfort to have had Lord Jellicoe as Leader. I doubt whether he realises how much we shall miss him. We have been deeply saddened by what has happened. The outstanding record of his achievements will not be dimmed; our warm regard for him will remain. (Hansard, 5 June 1973)}}\n\nWilliam Kendall, general secretary of the [[Civil and Public Services Association]] said:\n{{quote|In our union we respected him as a tough, capable and fair negotiator'' (quoted from ''The Times'', 25 May 1973, page 2); or, as Daniel McGeachie (of ''The Daily Express'') reported on 25 May 1973, ''He was a man in the Macmillan mould&nbsp;... [H]e gave the impression of a solid and straightforward approach to life, to the cut and thrust of debate-but at the same time he was an extraordinarlily subtle person.}}\n\nIn July 1973 the [[Kenneth Diplock, Baron Diplock|Diplock]] Commission, which had been set up to look into the security implications of Lambton and Jellicoe's adventures, concluded its section on Jellicoe (paragraph 24):\n{{quote|...&nbsp;it was Lord Jellicoe's misfortune that his use of 'call girls' happened to come to light at the particular moment that it did, when the attention of the Press was focused on the private conduct of Ministers in connection with the entirely separate case of Lord Lambton.}}\n\n==Business and post-government public career==\nLoss of government office soon seemed somewhat serendipitous. With no estates to distract him Jellicoe was free to re-join [[S. G. Warburg & Co.]] (1 October 1973), and with the help of [[Alan Lennox-Boyd, 1st Viscount Boyd of Merton|Alan Lennox-Boyd]], who was soon to retire from the board, he became a non-executive director of the sugar company [[Tate & Lyle]] 1973\u20131993. Thanks in the main to Sir Saxon Tate, and presumedly because he had succeeded as chairman (until June 1978) of their subsidiary Tunnel Refineries, the family made him Tate & Lyle's first non-family chairman 1978\u20131983. Having revived and retrenched Tate & Lyle Jellicoe became chairman of Booker Tate, 1988\u201391.\n\nOther non-governmental jobs include: chairman of engineering plant company the Davy Corporation (Davy McKee) (now subsumed into [[Aker Kv\u00e6rner]]) 1985\u20131990; director [[Sotheby's]] Holdings 1973\u20131993; Morgan Crucible 1974\u201388; [[Smiths Group|Smiths Industries Ltd]] 1973\u20131986; S. G. Warburg & Co 1964\u20131970, 1973\u20131988. He was president of the London Chamber of Commerce and Industry 1979\u20131982. He succeeded [[Patrick Pery, 6th Earl of Limerick|Lord Limerick]] as chairman of the [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|Department of Trade and Industry]]'s [[British Overseas Trade Board]] (BOTB) 1983\u20131986, for which he was knighted. That was followed by chairmanship (1986\u20131990) and then the presidency (1990\u20131995) of the East European Trade Council (EETC). He was chairman of the Greek Fund Ltd 1988\u20131994 ([[Schroders]]) and of European Capital Ltd 1991\u20131995.\n\nLord Jellicoe was chairman of the council of [[King's College London]] (KCL) 1974\u20131983; chairman of the [[Medical Research Council (UK)|Medical Research Council]] (MRC) 1982\u20131990; a trustee of the National Aids Trust (alongside the likes of [[Arnold Goodman, Baron Goodman|Lord Goodman]], [[David Puttnam]] and [[Robert Maxwell]]);\npresident of the [[Royal Geographical Society]] (RGS) (and of the Institute of British Geographers (IBG) after amalgamation) 1993\u20131997; president of the [[Anglo-Hellenic League]] 1978\u20131986; president of the [[Kennet and Avon Canal]] Trust 1987\u20131994; president of the UK [[Crete]] Veterans Association 1991\u20132001; president of the [[British Heart Foundation]] (BHF) 1992\u20131995; [[chancellor (education)|chancellor]] of [[Southampton University]] 1984\u20131995, and has been closely associated with research and higher education. He was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society]] in 1990.<ref name=\"frs\"/>\n\nIn 1995 he helped found [[Hakluyt & Company]], a strategic intelligence and advisory firm, for which he was a director 1996\u20132000. He was president of the SAS Regimental Association 1996\u20132000, when he became its patron. Jellicoe was a member of the Onassis International Prizes Committee (1983\u20131992); a vice-president of The European-Atlantic Group and of the [[George Byron, 6th Baron Byron|Byron Society]]; he was on the board of the Hellenic College London; patron of the City of Southampton Society; a patron of the Greek Archaeological Committee (UK); one of five patrons of The Community Foundation for Wiltshire and Swindon; a director of The Landscape Foundation (now dormant); patron of Friends of The Royal Hospital School; patron of the Hampshire and Wight Trust for Maritime Archaeology; a member of the World Innovation Fund (WIF) and an associate member of INEED.{{Clarify|name of organization|date=January 2018}} In 2002 he became a patron of ''The Second World War Experience Centre'' in [[Leeds]].\n\n==Later state contributions==\nBack in the Lords and affairs of state; he was chairman of the Select Committee on Committees (1990\u20131993) and President of the [[Parliamentary and Scientific Committee]] (1980\u20131983). In 1983 he was author of the '''Jellicoe Report''' which reviewed the ''Operation of the Prevention of Terrorism (Temporary Provisions) Act 1976''. ''The Times'' saw this appointment as the end of nine years penance in the political wilderness.\n\nBetween 1963 and 1973 Jellicoe had averaged 90 House of Lords daily attendances per parliamentary session. From 1973 to 1989 his attendance plummeted to a meagre average of nine appearances per session. However, between 1990 and 2001 he turned up a conscientious average of 72 visits per session. He maintained this rate until early 2006, though Jellicoe's last full speech in the Lords was made as part of the ''Address in Reply to Her Majesty's Most Gracious Speech'' (the Queen's Speech debate) on 28 October 1996, his subject was [[Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199697/ldhansrd/vo961028/text/61028-06.htm#61028-06_spnew0|title=Lords Hansard text for 28 Oct 1996 (161028-06) |publisher=Department of the Official Report (Hansard), House of Lords, Westminster }}</ref>\n\nWhen the [[House of Lords Act 1999]] removed his hereditary automatic entitlement to attend and sit in the House of Lords, he was created a [[life peer]] as '''Baron Jellicoe of Southampton''', of [[Southampton]] in the County of Hampshire, so that he could continue to be summoned<blockquote>1. Earl Jellicoe (Lord Jellicoe of Southampton) \u2014The Rt Hon. George Patrick John Rushworth Earl Jellicoe, having been created Baron Jellicoe of Southampton, of Southampton in the County of Hampshire, for life by Letters Patent dated 6 o'clock in the forenoon of 17th&nbsp;November 1999, took and subscribed the oath pursuant to statute.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55676 |page=12465 |date=23 November 1999 }}</ref></blockquote>\n\nLord Jellicoe remained an active member of the House of Lords for the rest of his life. He died on 22 February 2007, six weeks shy of his 89th birthday.\n\nAt his death, Lord Jellicoe was the longest-serving member of the House of Lords, and arguably the longest-serving parliamentarian in the world, having succeeded his father on 20 November 1935 and come of age and sat first in parliament on 25 July 1939. Because he waited until 28 July 1958 to make his maiden speech, a few peers (viz. [[Robert Shirley, 13th Earl Ferrers|Earl Ferrers]] and [[David Renton, Baron Renton|Lords Renton]], [[Peter Carington, 6th Baron Carrington|Carrington]], [[Denis Healey|Healey]], and [[David Kenworthy, 11th Baron Strabolgi|Strabolgi]]) could have been considered to have been active parliamentarians longer. Moreover, at the time of his death, on the Privy Council only the [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Duke of Edinburgh]] (1951) and Lords [[Peter Carington, 6th Baron Carrington|Carrington]] (1959), [[Bill Deedes|Deedes]] and [[David Renton, Baron Renton|Renton]] (both 1962) had served longer.\n\n==Character==\nIn May 1973, at the time of his resignation from the government, friends are quoted as saying:\n{{quote|If he has a fault it is because he wears his weaknesses on his sleeve. He is too frank. I suppose though, that is no bad thing. He was not flamboyant but he was a hedonist. He is the sort of non-pompous person who does not try to hide his weaknesses. (quoted from Christopher Sweeney's article in ''The Times'', 25 May 1973, page 2)}}\n\nIn July 1970, as one of the first people to be [[Breathalyzer|breathalized]], he was banned from driving for a year and fined 75 pounds with 20 guineas costs for ''having consumed more than the permitted level of alcohol'' in Old Brompton Road at 4 a.m. on 21 March 1970. The trouble was that his new [[Reliant Scimitar]] had a stiff gearbox, or so his story went. Luck saw to it that the case came after the General Election and the ban coincided with the arrival of his right to a full-time government car. {{Citation needed|date=March 2010}}\n\nIn 2000, his friend, the former [[British Ambassador to the United States]], [[Nicholas Henderson|Sir Nicholas Henderson]], wrote:\n{{quote|George is a man of moods. He is not complicated but a many-sided character. There are in fact four Georges: there is George the First, the unabstemious, boisterous [[Lothario]], with a leer like a rou\u00e9 in a [[Peter Arno]] cartoon, blessed with an iron constitution and athletic prowess that enabled him to have been on the verge of the British Olympic ski and sleigh teams; then we have Hero George, the dashing man of action, a leader who whether descending by parachute or commanding by sea, kept the enemy on tenterhooks in the Eastern Mediterranean throughout the war; thirdly, there is George the aesthete and sightseer, who, with little finger raised, will speak discerningly of paintings, mosaics and furniture, a great patron of the arts, his talent as a collector manqu\u00e9 only due to lack of funds, which has not prevented some bold purchases; and finally we have pensive George, scholar and public servant, concerned to promote the national interest, high-minded, cautious and conscientious&nbsp;... [A] striking and irrepressible feature of that character has been his easy communion with members of the opposite sex, and this may have been prefigured by an early experience. He spent some time as a small boy in New Zealand where his father was Governor-General. George wanted to become a [[cub scout|wolf cub]], but no pack was available, so instead he joined the [[Brownie (Girl Guides)|Brownies]]. He got on very well with them. (''Old Friends and Modern Instances'', 2000)}}\n\nLord Jellicoe married firstly, 23 March 1944, Patricia O'Kane (1917\u20132012),<ref>{{cite news | url =http://announcements.telegraph.co.uk/deaths/146959/jellicoe| title = Daily Telegraph Deaths Announcements \u2013 Patricia, Countess Jellicoe| accessdate = 21 March 2012 | work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> by whom he had two sons and two daughters. He married secondly, in 1966, Philippa, daughter of [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]] [[Philip Russell Rendel Dunne|Philip Dunne]] (1904\u20131965), by whom he had one son and two daughters. He had eight children in total, born between 1944 and 1984. He was a member of [[Brooks's]] (since 1940), the [[Special Forces]] Club, the [[Ski Club of Great Britain]] and was a liveryman of the [[Worshipful Company of Mercers]].\n\nLorna Windmill's biography termed Jellicoe ''a British Achilles'' on account of two of his careers derailing as a result of women: in the 1950s for love, and in the 1970s for escorts. {{Citation needed|date=March 2010}}\n\n==Honours==\n*Page of Honour (one of nine) to [[George VI of the United Kingdom|King George VI]] at his Coronation (12 May 1937)\n*[[Distinguished Service Order]] (DSO) (1942)\n*[[Military Cross]] (MC) (1944)\n*[[1939-45 Star]]\n*[[Africa Star]]\n*[[Italy Star]]\n*[[1939-45 War Medal]]\n*[[L\u00e9gion d'honneur]] (France) (1945)\n*[[Croix de guerre 1939\u20131945|Croix de Guerre]] (France) (1945)\n*[[Order of Honour (Greece)|Greek Order of Honour]] (1950)\n*[[War Cross (Greece)|Greek War Cross]] (1950)\n*[[Privy Counsellor]] (PC) (1963)\n*Freeman of the City of Athens\n*[[Order of the British Empire|Knight Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (KBE) (1986)\n*Honorary Citizenship of the [[Southampton (village), New York|Village of Southampton, New York]] (12 September 1987)\n*Companion of the British Institute of Management (elected 11 October 1988)\n*Hon. Admiral in the [[Texas Navy]] (1988)\n*27 October 1988 was ''Lord Earl Jellicoe Day'' in the City of [[Houston]]\n*[[Fellow of the Royal Society]] (FRS) (8 November 1990)\n*Grand Commander [[Order of Honour (Greece)|Order of Honour]] (Greece, 1991)\n*La Medaille de la Ville de Paris (echelon vermeil), (6 June 1994)\n*UK Life Peer (1999)\n*27 April 2001 was ''Earl Jellicoe Day'' in the City of [[Vancouver]]\n*''Winston S. Churchill Allied Nations Award'' from World War II Veterans Committee (8 November 2003, USA).\n*Hon. degrees from:\n:*[[King's College London]] (Fellow (FKC) 1979)\n:*[[Southampton University]] (LLD, 1985)\n:*[[Long Island University]] (Doctor of Laws, 12 September 1987).\n\n==Bibliography==\n*''Old Friends and Modern Instances'', by [[Nicholas Henderson]], Profile, 2001 (all chapter nine, pages&nbsp;105\u2013116).\n*''A British Achilles: The Story of George, 2nd Earl Jellicoe'', by Lorna Almonds Windmill, Pen and Sword Books Ltd, Barnsley, 2006.\n*''Dod's Parliamentary Companion'', 2007.\n*''Burke's Peerage'', 107th edition, 2003.\n*''Review of the Operation of the Prevention of Terrorism (Temporary Provisions) Act 1976'', by the Rt. Hon. Earl Jellicoe, DSO, MC., Command 8803, HMSO, February 1983.\n*''The Boxer Rebellion'', The Fifth Wellington Lecture, University of Southampton, by the Rt Hon the Earl Jellicoe, KBE, DSO, MC, LLD, FRS, PC, University of Southampton, 1993.\n*''Lord Shackleton'', by Lord Jellicoe, in ''Biographical Memoirs of Fellows of the Royal Society'', number 45, 1999, printed by the Cambridge University Press for the Royal Society.\n*''Special Boat Squadron'', ''The Story of the SBS in the Mediterranean'', by Barrie Pitt, Century Publishing, London, 1983.\n*''The Life of John Rushworth, Earl Jellicoe, G.C.B., O.M., G.C.V.O, L.L.D., D.C.L.'', by Admiral Sir [[R. H. Bacon]], K.C.B., K.C.V.O., D.S.O., Cassell, London, Toronto, Melbourne & Sydney, 1936.\n*''Tatler'', 30 August 1939.\n*''News Chronicle'', 30 January 1942.\n*(Australian) ''The Sun'', Alan Trengove, 22 June 1972\n*''International Herald Tribune'', 21 February 1978. Article on Patricia, Countess Jellicoe by Naomi Barry.\n*''Financial Weekly'', 20 April 1979, profile by Judi Bevan, page 12.\n*''Country Life'', 1 July 1999, profile, with a photo by [[Derry Moore, 12th Earl of Drogheda|Derry Moore]].\n*''Twenty-One: Coming of Age in the Second World War'', by James Holland, HarperCollins, London, 2006 (whole of chapter five).\n*[[Baron Chidgey|Lord Chidgey]] in ''The House Magazine'', Dods, 12 February 2007.\n*''House of Lords Hansard'', Monday 26 February 2007: ''Tributes: Earl Jellicoe''.\n*Obituaries\n:*''The Independent'' (Dennis Kavanagh), Saturday 24 February 2007.\n:*''The Times'', ''The Daily Telegraph'', & ''The Guardian'' ([[Andrew Roth]]): Monday 26 February 2007.\n:*''Financial Times'', (Sue Cameron): Tuesday 27 February 2007.\n:*''Yesterday in Parliament'', (David Wilby), BBC Radio Four, Tuesday 27 February 2007.\n:*''The Scotsman'', (Alasdair Steven), Wednesday 28 February 2007.\n:*''The Times'', (Lives Remembered, by Christopher Roberts), 28 February 2007.\n:*''The Wiltshire Gazette and Herald'', Thursday 1 March 2007.\n:*''The Week'', (a digest of the above), 3 March 2007.\n:*''The Spectator'', ([[Patrick Leigh Fermor]]), 3 March 2007.\n:*BBC Radio Four, ''Last Word'' (John Wilson), Friday 2 March 2007, (tx: circa 15:20\u201315:28).\n:*''The Herald'', Glasgow, Monday 5 March 2007.\n:*''The Anglo-Hellenic Review'', no. 36, Autumn 2007.\n*''The Times'', and ''The Daily Telegraph'', 1 June 2007, approximate list of those who attended his memorial service at the [[Guards Chapel, Wellington Barracks|Guards Chapel]], [[Wellington Barracks, London|Wellington Barracks]], [[Birdcage Walk]], St James's Park, Westminster, on 31 May 2007.\n:*''The Oldie'', James Hughes Onslow on Earl Jellicoe's memorial service, page 69, July 2007.\n* The Anglo-Hellenic League's ''reception in remembrance of its former Chairman and Patron'', Cholmondeley Room, House of Lords, 14 February 2008.\n::spoken tributes by [[Colin Moynihan|Lord Moynihan]], Tryphon Kedros, [[Viscount Norwich|John Julius Norwich]], Sir James Gowans, Dimitris Paraskevas, & the Hon. Nicholas Jellicoe.\n:::This event was reported in ''The Anglo-Hellenic Review'', no. 37, Spring 2008, page 2.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Hansard-contribs | mr-george-jellicoe | the Earl Jellicoe }}\n*[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199900/minutes/991123/ldminute.htm Announcement of his taking the oath] for the first time as ''Baron Jellicoe of Southampton'', House of Lords Minutes of proceedings, 23 November 1999\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040222114039/http://www.winstonchurchill.org/i4a/pages/index.cfm?pageid=631 Speech] to The Churchill Centre Inc., from proceedings of the International Churchill Societies 1994\u201395.\n*[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199697/ldhansrd/vo961028/text/61028-06.htm#61028-06_spnew0 Jellicoe on the Ukraine. His last full speech in the Lords, 28 October 1996].\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071119112513/http://news.independent.co.uk/people/obituaries/article2300414.ece ''Independent'' obituary]\n*[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200607/ldhansrd/text/70226-0001.htm#0702269000010 Tributes: Earl Jelicoe] Link to Hansard, Monday 26 February 2007.\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-off}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Henry Bathurst, 8th Earl Bathurst|The Earl Bathurst]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Lord-in-waiting]]|years=1961}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Bertram Bowyer, 2nd Baron Denham|The Lord Denham]]}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Peter Carington, 6th Baron Carrington|The Lord Carrington]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Admiralty|First Lord of the Admiralty]]|years=1963\u20131964}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Queen Elizabeth II]]|as=Lord High Admiral}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Edward Shackleton, Baron Shackleton|The Lord Shackleton]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Lord Privy Seal]]<br />[[Leader of the House of Lords]]|years=1970\u20131973}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[David Hennessy, 3rd Baron Windlesham|The Lord Windlesham]]}}\n{{S-ppo}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Peter Carington, 6th Baron Carrington|The Lord Carrington]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Leader of the Conservative Party (UK)|Leader of the Conservative Party]] in the [[House of Lords]]|years=1970\u20131973}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[David Hennessy, 3rd Baron Windlesham|The Lord Windlesham]]}}\n{{s-hon}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dominick Browne, 4th Baron Oranmore and Browne|The Lord Oranmore and Browne]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Father of the House (United Kingdom)#Longest-serving member of the House of Lords|Longest-serving member in the House of Lords]]|years=1999\u20132007}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Peter Carington, 6th Baron Carrington|The Lord Carrington]]}}\n{{S-reg|uk}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[John Jellicoe, 1st Earl Jellicoe|John Jellicoe]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Earl Jellicoe]]|years=1935\u20132007}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Patrick Jellicoe, 3rd Earl Jellicoe|Patrick Jellicoe]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{FRS 1990}}\n{{First Lords of the Admiralty|state=collapsed}}\n{{Heath Ministry}}\n{{RGSPresidents}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2011}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jellicoe, George Jellicoe, 2nd Earl}}\n[[Category:1918 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:British diplomats]]\n[[Category:Coldstream Guards officers]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Distinguished Service Order]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) Baronesses- and Lords-in-Waiting]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Earls in the Peerage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:English bankers]]\n[[Category:Fellows of King's College London]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Honour]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Croix de Guerre 1939\u20131945 (France)]]\n[[Category:Graduates of the Royal Military College, Sandhurst]]\n[[Category:Grand Commanders of the Order of Honour (Greece)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the War Cross (Greece)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Military Cross]]\n[[Category:First Lords of the Admiralty]]\n[[Category:Lords Privy Seal]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People educated at St Peter's Court]]\n[[Category:People educated at Winchester College]]\n[[Category:People associated with King's College London]]\n[[Category:Chancellors of the University of Southampton]]\n[[Category:People from Ventnor]]\n[[Category:People from Wiltshire]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Royal Geographical Society]]\n[[Category:Special Air Service officers]]\n[[Category:Special Boat Service officers]]\n[[Category:Crete in World War II]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the House of Lords]]\n[[Category:British Army Commandos officers]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Geographical Society]]\n[[Category:Cayzer family]]\n[[Category:Schroders people]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Scottish Geographical Society]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = The Earl Jellicoe\n| honorific-suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|KBE|DSO|MC|PC|FRS|FRGS}}\n| image = George Jellicoe, 2nd Earl Jellicoe.jpg\n| imagesize = 200px\n| alt = George Jellicoe, 2nd Earl Jellicoe (1960's photo by Phillippa, Countess Jellicoe)\n| caption = George Jellicoe, 2nd Earl Jellicoe<br>(1960s photo by Phillippa, Countess Jellicoe)\n| office2 = [[Leader of the House of Lords]]<br/>[[Lord Privy Seal|Lord Keeper of the Privy Seal]]\n| term_start2 = 20 June 1970\n| term_end2 = 23 May 1973\n| monarch2 = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Edward Heath]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Edward Shackleton, Baron Shackleton|The Lord Shackleton]]\n| successor2 = [[David Hennessy, 3rd Baron Windlesham|The Lord Windlesham]]\n| office4 = [[First Lord of the Admiralty]]\n| term_start4 = 22 October 1963\n| term_end4 = 1 April 1964\n| monarch4 = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| primeminister4 = [[Alec Douglas-Home|Sir Alec Douglas Home]]\n| predecessor4 = [[Peter Carington, 6th Baron Carrington|The Lord Carrington]]\n| successor4 = [[Elizabeth II]]<br/><small>as [[Lord High Admiral of the United Kingdom|Lord High Admiral]]\n| office3 = [[Minister of Defence|Minister of State for Navy]]\n| term_start3 = 1 April 1964\n| term_end3 = 16 October 1964\n| monarch3 = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Alec Douglas-Home|Sir Alec Douglas Home]]\n| office5 = [[Under-Secretary of State for the Home Department|Minister of State for Home Affairs]]\n| term_start5 = 17 July 1962\n| term_end5 = 21 October 1963\n| monarch5 = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| primeminister5 = [[Harold Macmillan]]\n| predecessor5 = [[David Renton]]\n| successor5 = [[Patrick Vanden-Bempde-Johnstone, 4th Baron Derwent|The Lord Derwent]]\n| office6 = [[Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government|Parliamentary Secretary to the Minister of Housing and Local Government]]\n| term_start6 = 27 June 1961\n| term_end6 = 16 July 1962\n| monarch6 = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| primeminister6 = [[Harold Macmillan]]\n| predecessor6 = [[Keith Joseph]]\n| successor6 = [[Frederick Corfield]]\n| office7 = [[Lord-in-waiting]]<br>[[Government Whip]]\n| monarch7 = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| primeminister7 = [[Harold Macmillan]]\n| term_start7 = 8 February 1961\n| term_end7 = 27 June 1961\n| predecessor7 = [[Henry Bathurst, 8th Earl Bathurst|The Earl Bathurst]]\n| successor7 = [[Bertram Bowyer, 2nd Baron Denham|The Lord Denham]]\n| office15 = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n| term_start15 = 17 November 1999\n| term_end15 = 22 February 2007<br>[[Life Peerage]]\n| term_start16 = 25 July 1939\n| term_end16 = 11 November 1999<br>[[Hereditary Peerage]]\n| predecessor16 = [[John Jellicoe, 1st Earl Jellicoe|The 1st Earl Jellicoe]]\n| successor16 = ''[[House of Lords Act 1999|Seat abolished ]]''\n| birth_date = 4 April 1918\n| birth_place = [[Hatfield, Hertfordshire|Hatfield]], [[Hertfordshire]]<br/>[[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2007|2|22|1918|4|4|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Fosbury|Tidcombe]], [[Wiltshire]]<br/>[[United Kingdom]]\n| restingplace = \n| restingplacecoordinates = \n| birthname = \n| citizenship = \n| nationality = UK\n| party = [[Conservative Party (United Kingdom)|Conservative]]\n| otherparty = \n| spouse = \n| relations = \n| children = eight\n| residence = Tidcombe\n| alma_mater = Winchester\n| occupation = Politician, businessman\n| committees = \n| portfolio = \n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n| allegiance = United Kingdom\n| branch = [[British Army]]\n| unit = [[Coldstream Guards]]<br/>[[Special Boat Service]]\n| serviceyears = \n| rank = [[Brigadier]]\n| battles = [[Second World War]]\n| mawards = [[Distinguished Service Order]]<br/>[[Military Cross]]<br/>[[Mentioned in Despatches]] (3)\n}}\n'''George Patrick John Rushworth Jellicoe, 2nd Earl Jellicoe, Baron Jellicoe of Southampton''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|KBE|DSO|MC|PC|FRS|FRGS}}<ref name=\"frs\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Waldegrave | first1 = W. | authorlink1 = William Waldegrave, Baron Waldegrave of North Hill| doi = 10.1098/rsbm.2008.0004 | title = [[George Patrick John Rushworth Jellicoe, 2nd Earl Jellicoe|George Jellicoe, 2nd Earl Jellicoe]]. 4 April 1918 \u2013 22 February 2007 | journal = [[Biographical Memoirs of Fellows of the Royal Society]] | volume = 54 | pages = 169 | year = 2008 | pmid =  | pmc = | doi-access = free }}</ref> (4 April 1918&nbsp;\u2013 22 February 2007) was a British politician, diplomat and businessman.\n\nLord Jellicoe was the only son but sixth and youngest child of [[John Jellicoe, 1st Earl Jellicoe]], who was a [[First World War]] naval commander, commander at the Battle of [[Battle of Jutland|Jutland]], and [[Admiral of the Fleet (Royal Navy)|Admiral of the Fleet]], and his wife Florence Gwendoline (died 1964), who was the second daughter of [[Sir Charles Cayzer, 1st Baronet|Sir Charles Cayzer]], 1st [[Baronet|Bt.]], of [[Gartmore]], [[Perthshire]]. George Jellicoe was one of the longest-serving parliamentarians in the world, being a member of the [[House of Lords]] for 68 years (1939\u20132007).{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n\n==Early life==\nJellicoe was born at Hatfield and was christened on 29 July 1918 by the [[Most Reverend|Most Rev.]] and [[The Right Honourable|Right Hon.]] [[Cosmo Lang]], 89th [[Archbishop of York]], while [[George V of Great Britain and Ireland|King George V]] (represented by [[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]] [[Stanley Colville|Sir Stanley Colville]]) and HRH [[Princess Patricia of Connaught]] (later known as Lady Patricia Ramsay) stood sponsor as two of his godparents. The others were: Miss Lilian Lear, Admiral [[Lionel Halsey|Sir Lionel Halsey]] (Third Sea Lord), Mr. Eustace Burrows (cousin), [[Baron Rotherwick|Major Herbert Cayzer]] (uncle), and [[The Reverend|The Rev.]] Frederick G. G. Jellicoe (uncle, and Rector of [[New Alresford]]).\n\nMuch of his childhood was spent at St Lawrence Hall, near [[Ventnor]] on the [[Isle of Wight]]; at [[St Peter's Court]], a prep school at [[Broadstairs]], Kent; in London; and in the [[Dominion of New Zealand]], where his father was [[viceroy]] with the title of [[Governor-General of New Zealand|Governor-General]] between 1921 and 1924. He was educated at [[Winchester College]], where he was styled and known as [[Earl Jellicoe|Viscount Brocas]]. He won the Vere Herbert Smith history prize and secured an exhibition to [[Trinity College, Cambridge]] (matriculated 1936. BA, Modern History tripos 1939, but awarded 1966). He was chairman of the [[Pitt Club]], and his tutor [[Steven Runciman]] became a lifelong friend.\n\n==Second World War==\nIn October 1939, the young Jellicoe was a cadet in the first wartime intake at the [[Royal Military College, Sandhurst|RMC, Sandhurst]].<ref>Windmill, Lorna Almonds. ''A British Achilles: George, 2nd Earl Jellicoe KBE DSO MC FRS 20th Century Soldier, Politician, Statesman''. Barnsley: Pen & Sword Military, 2008. {{ISBN|9781844158812}} {{OCLC|244652725}} Page 9.</ref> He was commissioned into the [[Coldstream Guards]] on 23 March 1940, before joining [[No. 8 (Guards) Commando]], with whom on 31 January 1941 he sailed to the Middle East with [[Robert Laycock|Colonel Bob Laycock's]] [[Layforce]] (whose commando officers included [[Evelyn Waugh]], [[Randolph Churchill]], [[Philip Russell Rendel Dunne|Philip Dunne]], [[Carol Mather]], [[David Stirling]], and many distinguished others). He served with '' L Detachment'' (from April 1942) (with some of the above and [[Stephen Hastings]]), which was the nucleus of the [[Special Air Service]]. He was [[Mentioned in Despatches|mentioned in despatches]] thrice, and wounded (bullet in shoulder) once whilst with the 3rd Battalion, Coldstream Guards, in 22 (Guards) Brigade in the Western Desert in January 1941. He won the DSO in November 1942 for [[Operation Albumen|operating on a raid]] that claimed to have blown up more than 20 German aircraft ([[Junkers Ju 88|Ju 88s]]) on [[Heraklion]] airfield, Crete, that June:\n<blockquote>\nHis cool and resolute leadership, skill and courage throughout this very hazardous operation were mainly responsible for the high measure of success achieved. He&nbsp;... placed charges on the enemy aircraft and brought off the survivors after the four [[Free French Forces|Free French]] members of the party had been betrayed and killed or captured.<ref>''[[London Gazette]]'', 5 November 1942, quoted from L. Almonds Windmill, page 49</ref>\n</blockquote>\nIn September 1943, Jellicoe was sent to the Italian-held island of [[Rhodes]] to negotiate with the Italian Admiral [[Inigo Campioni]] for the surrender of his forces to the Allies. However, negotiations were pre-empted by a surprise German attack on the island on 9 September. He was able to escape from Rhodes during the resulting chaos while the Italian garrison was captured by the German invasion force. This was part of the [[Dodecanese Campaign]].\n\nIn 1943, he was named Commander of the [[Special Boat Service|Special Boat Regiment ''Middle East'']] and he was promoted to the rank of lieutenant-colonel. He was eventually promoted to brigadier.<ref>Churchill's secret warriors. Damien Lewis 2014.</ref> For the remainder of the war, his SBS command conducted secretive and dangerous operations along the coasts of Italy and Yugoslavia. In 1944, he won the MC for one of these actions. At the end of the war, Jellicoe was among the first Allied soldiers to enter German-occupied [[Athens]], beating the communist-controlled guerrillas [[Greek People's Liberation Army|ELAS]], to create a pro-Allied presence in the capital.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.independent.co.uk/people/obituaries/article2300414.ece |date=24 February 2007 |title=Earl Jellicoe |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071119112513/http://news.independent.co.uk/people/obituaries/article2300414.ece |archive-date=19 November 2007 |newspaper=[[The Independent]] }}</ref>\n\nYears later, when First Lord of the Admiralty, Jellicoe told at least one reporter, \"The only serious military distinction I ever achieved was having a new type of assault boat named after me. It was called I am ashamed to say, the Jellicoe Inflatable Intruder Mark One.\"\n\nIn March 1944, Lord Jellicoe married Patricia Christine O'Kane (October 1917 \u2013 March 2012),<ref>{{cite web|title=Patricia Christine Jellicoe (n\u00e9e O'Kane), Countess Jellicoe (1917\u20132012)|url=http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp85238/patricia-christine-jellicoe-nee-okane-countess-jellicoe|publisher=National Portrait Gallery}}</ref> who was employed at the [[British Embassy]] in [[Beirut]]. She had been born and raised in [[Shanghai]] and was the daughter of a [[Greenock]]-born Irish father and an English mother. Patricia, Countess Jellicoe (popularly known as Patsy Jellicoe), would remain married to Lord Jellicoe until 1966, when they divorced. They had two sons and two daughters together, the eldest son being the [[Earl Jellicoe|3rd Earl Jellicoe]].\n\n==HM Foreign Service 1947\u20131958==\nSoon after the war Lord Jellicoe joined His Majesty's [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Foreign Service]], (appointed a Foreign Service Officer, Grade 8 in the Senior Branch of the Foreign Service, 10 September 1947). He served in London (German political department, Third Secretary); [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]] (Third Secretary, when [[Donald Duart Maclean|Donald Maclean]] of the [[Cambridge Five|''Cambridge five'']] was Head of Chancery, and then as one of the 11 Second Secretaries with [[Kim Philby|H. A. R. Philby]], seeing [[NATO]] signed on 4 April 1949, all when [[Oliver Franks, Baron Franks|Sir Oliver Franks]] was Ambassador); transferred to [[Brussels]] 10 September 1951 (Head of Chancery) acted as Charg\u00e9 d'Affaires in 1952); London (no. 2 in Northern department in charge of the Soviet Desk from September 1953); and Baghdad from January 1956 (First Secretary and Deputy Secretary General of [[Baghdad Pact|the Baghdad Pact]] Organisation). The [[Suez Crisis]] (from July 1956) wrecked everything the Pact was trying to achieve; Jellicoe was appalled by British policy and came close to resigning (L. Windmill p.&nbsp;136).\n\nJellicoe eventually left the Foreign Office in March 1958, after marital difficulties had caused an impasse (February 1958, [[Permanent Secretary]] Sir Derek Hoyar-Millar wrote; 'You have a choice of ceasing your relationship with this lady [Philippa Dunne] or changing your job'). He became a director of the Cayzer dynasty's [[Clan Line]] Steamers (cargo ships), and [[Union-Castle Line|Union Castle Steamship Co.]] (passengers).\n\nHowever, enthusiasm for his mother's family's businesses ultimately gave way to the call of the [[Palace of Westminster]], where, back from [[Iraq]], he took the [[Oath of Allegiance (United Kingdom)|Oath]] in the [[House of Lords|Lords]] on 3 December 1957, in the Third Session of the [[41st Parliament of the United Kingdom|41st Parliament]].\n\n==House of Lords and 1960s==\n[[File:JellicoeGrin.jpg|thumb|Jellicoe during a skiing holiday.]]\n[[File:JellicoeSkiing.jpg|thumb|Jellicoe skiing in France.]]\nHaving first sat in parliament on 25 July 1939, Jellicoe waited until 28 July 1958 to make his maiden speech in the [[House of Lords]] during a debate entitled \"The International Situation: The Middle East\". He spoke from the [[cross-bencher|Cross-Benches]] about the Baghdad Pact and Iraq:\n{{quote|...&nbsp;Having lately lived for a year or so in [[Baghdad]] I confess that I have not been untouched by the charm of that ugly yet fascinating city, and, if I may say so, of the diverse peoples of Iraq&nbsp;... Like all your Lordships, I felt, and feel, a deep sense of shock, indeed revulsion, at the brutal butchery of the young King and his family, and of that great, and greatly human, statesman, [[Nuri as-Said|Nuri Pasha]]. I have also been shocked by the tendency which one sees current at the moment to write off the Nuri regime as decadent, feudal and corrupt. That picture, in my view, is a travesty of the truth&nbsp;... As part of the admirable development programme which the Nuri regime was carrying through there was a large schools programme. These schools were built for the purpose your Lordships might expect-to educate Iraqis in. But the Iraqis did not believe that; they thought-it was a very widespread belief which one could not eradicate-that these schools were camouflaged barracks intended for the British Army when they reoccupied Iraq. These are the sorts of 'ingrowing toenails' in the Iraqi consciousness which I feel we must try to eradicate, to draw out&nbsp;...}}\n\nBy October 1958 he had joined the Conservatives, in the Lords a natural home for such a ''distinctly pink''<ref>[[Piers Dixon]] in Philip Ziegler & Desmond Seward (eds): ''Brooks's: A Social History'', 1991.</ref>{{clarification needed|date=May 2019}} [[British Whig Party|Whig]], who gave him the honour of moving \"an humble Address in Reply to Her Majesty's Most Gracious Speech\"\n{{quote|My Lords, I am acutely, indeed somewhat painfully, conscious of the great honour which the noble Earl [[Alec Douglas-Home|Lord Home]]'' (i.e. Alec Douglas-Home)'', the Leader of the House, has done me in inviting me to move the humble Address to Her Majesty. The last time that I addressed your Lordships' House was from the platonic sanctity of the Cross-Benches. I then had the aesthetic pleasure of seeing your Lordships in profile: I now have the equal pleasure of seeing some of your Lordships full face. I do not know why I find myself in this particular hot spot this afternoon. I can only surmise that the noble Earl, fishing for a good large Tory trout, cast over the Cross-Benches for an ex-Ambassador and hooked an ex-First Secretary by mistake.}}\n\nOn 7 May 1959, he asked a prescient starred question on the Planning of Motorways:\n{{quote|...&nbsp;Just as the Roman roads are with us to-day, so these great new roads may be with our successors 1,000 years hence. With this in mind, can my noble friend assure us, first, that the advice of the Advisory Committee [on the Landscape Treatment of Trunk Roads] to which he referred will in all cases in future be sought at a very early stage in the planning of these new roads;  and, secondly, that permanent professional advice will be enlisted from the outset at the planning, the reconnaissance stage, in order to ensure that these great new roads blend as harmoniously as possible with the land-scape through which they pass?}}\n\nOn 20 July 1959 he initiated a debate on ''Western Aid for Uncommitted Countries'', and by January 1961 he was a [[Lord-in-waiting]] to H.M. the Queen, a Government Whip, in [[Harold Macmillan|Macmillan]]'s administration. He was Joint Parliamentary Secretary, Ministry of Housing and Local Government June 1961 \u2013 July 1962; Minister of State, Home Office July 1962 \u2013 October 1963; [[First Lord of the Admiralty]] October 1963 \u2013 April 1964; [[Minister of Defence for the Royal Navy]] April\u2013October 1964; delegate to the [[Council of Europe]] and the Western European Union (WEU) 1965\u20131967; president of the National Federation of Housing Societies 1965\u20131970; a governor of the [[Centre for Environmental Studies]] 1967\u20131970; chairman of the British Advisory Committee on Oil Pollution at Sea 1968; chairman of the third International Conference on oil pollution of the sea 1968; an hon. vice-president of [[Tory Reform Group|PEST]] (Pressure for Economic and Social Toryism); and deputy Leader of the Opposition in the Lords 1967\u20131970. From April 1967 Lords Jellicoe and [[Peter Carington, 6th Baron Carrington|Carrington]] represented the Conservatives in the Lords on the Inter-Party conference group on Lords' reform, which came up with the unsuccessful Parliament (No.2) Bill (1968\u20131969). Leading the debate for the (Conservative) Opposition in November 1968 Jellicoe said:\n{{quote|We hold that a grave constitutional change of this kind should not be brought into effect in the dying years of a discredited Government&nbsp;... a viable Upper House has an essential part to play in our parliamentary structure. We now have a quite considerable constitutional prize in our grasp, the opportunity to build a really viable Upper House on the basis of a broad consensus of support from all Parties&nbsp;... (19 November 1968, Hansard via L. Windmill).}}\n\nDuring the late 1960s he worked in the [[City of London]] where he became chairman of British Reserve Insurance and a director of [[S. G. Warburg & Co.|S G Warburg (Finance and Development) Ltd]].\n\n==Cabinet minister and resignation==\nIn [[Edward Heath|Ted Heath's]] [[Conservative Government 1970-1974|administration]] he was Minister in charge for the Civil Service Department (CSD), [[Lord Privy Seal]] (as such he was eighth on the [[Order of precedence in England and Wales|Roll of The Lords]]) and [[Leader of the House of Lords]] from 20 June 1970 until 24 May 1973.\n\nHaving earlier re-established relations with the miners' union leaders in February 1972, Heath appointed Jellicoe \"energy supremo\" to restore power supplies around the time of the [[Three-Day Week]] and had him set up and chair a Civil Contingencies Unit, which was, when an internal crisis arose, to operate through \"COBRA\" ([[Cabinet Office Briefing Rooms]]).\n\nIn June 1972 Jellicoe was sent to lead [[Concorde]]'s first sales expedition. As Alan Trengove in ''My Lord, the super salesman'', in the Australian ''The Sun'' of 22 June 1972 put it,\n{{quote|There has probably never been a sales team [122 strong] quite like the aristocratic British contingent that is trying to sell the Anglo-French supersonic Concorde to Qantas&nbsp;... The earl is an astute salesman who has obviously done his homework&nbsp;... He has the stamina to address a couple of press conferences each day as well as make daily speeches&nbsp;... cultivate politicians, DCA personnel and Qantas bosses. At fifty-four, the earl looks a rugged character. He has a strong broad chin and speaks with a directness that appeals to Australians&nbsp;... Inevitably, he is beginning to be known in Australia as 'Aeroplane Jellicoe'. If he can land the Concorde deal with Qantas, they may soon be singing in Britain:\n::''I like Aeroplane Jellicoe''\n::''Aeroplane Jellicoe for me.''\n::''I like it for dinner, like it for tea,''\n::''Aeroplane Jellicoe has goodness for me''.}}\n\nTrengove considered [[George Edwards (aviation)|Sir George Edwards]] and Sir Geoffrey Tuttle \"equally impressive members of the sales team\". (Supersonic flights were on the prototype Concorde G-BSST, certificate signed by [[Brian Trubshaw]], and dated 15 June 1972). Jellicoe, with the help of his very experienced Chief Whip, the second [[Earl St Aldwyn|Earl St. Aldwyn]], steered the [[European Communities Act 1972 (UK)|''European Communities Act'' (1972)]] through the Lords, allowing no amendments. The ''Industrial Relations Act'' was another legislative highlight.\n\nIn May 1973 Jellicoe admitted \"some casual affairs\" with [[call girl]]s (from ''Mayfair Escorts'') in the wake of an accidental confusion with [[Antony Lambton|Lord Lambton]]'s prostitution scandal.<ref>{{cite news |first=Alvin |last=Shuster |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1973/05/27/archives/a-proper-government-scandal-britain.html |title=A Proper Government Scandal; Britain |date=27 May 1973 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] }}</ref> The name Jellicoe seems to have emerged as a result of a connection between Lambton, the madame Norma Levy, and a tenement house or community hall in [[Somers Town, London|Somers Town]] in the London district of St. Pancras called ''Jellicoe'' Hall or House, after Basil Jellicoe (1899\u20131935) the housing reformer, and priest. The word Jellicoe was seen in Levy's notebook, and a connection was assumed to the Minister rather than the building; a structure named after the earl's distant cousin, and one that may have been opened by the Admiral himself in June 1928.\n\nThe resignation ended Jellicoe's third career in government service. After the resignation (over his marginal involvement in a minor indiscretion) [[Richard Crossman]], writing in ''The Times'', 30 May 1973 (page 18), described Jellicoe as:\n{{quote|...&nbsp;among the bravest, ablest, most decent members of the Heath Government&nbsp;... [B]ut need the Prime Minister have got rid of Lord Jellicoe in such peremptory style? Could he not have refused his resignation until all the facts were available?}}\n\nOn return from the Whitsun recess, tributes were paid in the Lords to their departed leader: The (Labour Party) Opposition leader and Jellicoe's predecessor as Lord Privy Seal, [[Edward Shackleton, Baron Shackleton|Lord Shackleton]] said:\n{{quote|Lord Jellicoe&nbsp;... has been as good a leader of this House as we have known [cheers].. I don't think we can let him go \u2013 though happily this is not an epitaph \u2013 without expressing our very deep sorrow to the House and to the country [cheers]&nbsp;... with immense thoroughness, patience and personal sensitivity Lord Jellicoe fulfilled his role as Leader of your Lordships House [cheers]&nbsp;... we [Lords Byers and Shackleton] found him an admirable open-minded and wise colleague; my Lords, I believe that we and the country have suffered a grievous loss&nbsp;... (Hansard, 5 June 1973, and ''The Times'', 6 June 1973, for the cheers)}}\n\nLord Byers for the Liberal Party added: \"we regret bitterly his resignation&nbsp;... He was a reforming innovator and the House owes a great deal more than it probably knows to the interest he took in this House and to his initiatives.\" (Hansard, 5 June 1973)\n\nFrom the Cross-Benches [[William Strang, 1st Baron Strang|Lord Strang]] added:\n{{quote|To some of us it had been a comfort to have had Lord Jellicoe as Leader. I doubt whether he realises how much we shall miss him. We have been deeply saddened by what has happened. The outstanding record of his achievements will not be dimmed; our warm regard for him will remain. (Hansard, 5 June 1973)}}\n\nWilliam Kendall, general secretary of the [[Civil and Public Services Association]] said:\n{{quote|In our union we respected him as a tough, capable and fair negotiator'' (quoted from ''The Times'', 25 May 1973, page 2); or, as Daniel McGeachie (of ''The Daily Express'') reported on 25 May 1973, ''He was a man in the Macmillan mould&nbsp;... [H]e gave the impression of a solid and straightforward approach to life, to the cut and thrust of debate-but at the same time he was an extraordinarlily subtle person.}}\n\nIn July 1973 the [[Kenneth Diplock, Baron Diplock|Diplock]] Commission, which had been set up to look into the security implications of Lambton and Jellicoe's adventures, concluded its section on Jellicoe (paragraph 24):\n{{quote|...&nbsp;it was Lord Jellicoe's misfortune that his use of 'call girls' happened to come to light at the particular moment that it did, when the attention of the Press was focused on the private conduct of Ministers in connection with the entirely separate case of Lord Lambton.}}\n\n==Business and post-government public career==\nLoss of government office soon seemed somewhat serendipitous. With no estates to distract him Jellicoe was free to re-join [[S. G. Warburg & Co.]] (1 October 1973), and with the help of [[Alan Lennox-Boyd, 1st Viscount Boyd of Merton|Alan Lennox-Boyd]], who was soon to retire from the board, he became a non-executive director of the sugar company [[Tate & Lyle]] 1973\u20131993. Thanks in the main to Sir Saxon Tate, and presumedly because he had succeeded as chairman (until June 1978) of their subsidiary Tunnel Refineries, the family made him Tate & Lyle's first non-family chairman 1978\u20131983. Having revived and retrenched Tate & Lyle Jellicoe became chairman of Booker Tate, 1988\u201391.\n\nOther non-governmental jobs include: chairman of engineering plant company the Davy Corporation (Davy McKee) (now subsumed into [[Aker Kv\u00e6rner]]) 1985\u20131990; director [[Sotheby's]] Holdings 1973\u20131993; Morgan Crucible 1974\u201388; [[Smiths Group|Smiths Industries Ltd]] 1973\u20131986; S. G. Warburg & Co 1964\u20131970, 1973\u20131988. He was president of the London Chamber of Commerce and Industry 1979\u20131982. He succeeded [[Patrick Pery, 6th Earl of Limerick|Lord Limerick]] as chairman of the [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|Department of Trade and Industry]]'s [[British Overseas Trade Board]] (BOTB) 1983\u20131986, for which he was knighted. That was followed by chairmanship (1986\u20131990) and then the presidency (1990\u20131995) of the East European Trade Council (EETC). He was chairman of the Greek Fund Ltd 1988\u20131994 ([[Schroders]]) and of European Capital Ltd 1991\u20131995.\n\nLord Jellicoe was chairman of the council of [[King's College London]] (KCL) 1974\u20131983; chairman of the [[Medical Research Council (UK)|Medical Research Council]] (MRC) 1982\u20131990; a trustee of the National Aids Trust (alongside the likes of [[Arnold Goodman, Baron Goodman|Lord Goodman]], [[David Puttnam]] and [[Robert Maxwell]]);\npresident of the [[Royal Geographical Society]] (RGS) (and of the Institute of British Geographers (IBG) after amalgamation) 1993\u20131997; president of the [[Anglo-Hellenic League]] 1978\u20131986; president of the [[Kennet and Avon Canal]] Trust 1987\u20131994; president of the UK [[Crete]] Veterans Association 1991\u20132001; president of the [[British Heart Foundation]] (BHF) 1992\u20131995; [[chancellor (education)|chancellor]] of [[Southampton University]] 1984\u20131995, and has been closely associated with research and higher education. He was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society]] in 1990.<ref name=\"frs\"/>\n\nIn 1995 he helped found [[Hakluyt & Company]], a strategic intelligence and advisory firm, for which he was a director 1996\u20132000. He was president of the SAS Regimental Association 1996\u20132000, when he became its patron. Jellicoe was a member of the Onassis International Prizes Committee (1983\u20131992); a vice-president of The European-Atlantic Group and of the [[George Byron, 6th Baron Byron|Byron Society]]; he was on the board of the Hellenic College London; patron of the City of Southampton Society; a patron of the Greek Archaeological Committee (UK); one of five patrons of The Community Foundation for Wiltshire and Swindon; a director of The Landscape Foundation (now dormant); patron of Friends of The Royal Hospital School; patron of the Hampshire and Wight Trust for Maritime Archaeology; a member of the World Innovation Fund (WIF) and an associate member of INEED.{{Clarify|name of organization|date=January 2018}} In 2002 he became a patron of ''The Second World War Experience Centre'' in [[Leeds]].\n\n==Later state contributions==\nBack in the Lords and affairs of state; he was chairman of the Select Committee on Committees (1990\u20131993) and President of the [[Parliamentary and Scientific Committee]] (1980\u20131983). In 1983 he was author of the '''Jellicoe Report''' which reviewed the ''Operation of the Prevention of Terrorism (Temporary Provisions) Act 1976''. ''The Times'' saw this appointment as the end of nine years penance in the political wilderness.\n\nBetween 1963 and 1973 Jellicoe had averaged 90 House of Lords daily attendances per parliamentary session. From 1973 to 1989 his attendance plummeted to a meagre average of nine appearances per session. However, between 1990 and 2001 he turned up a conscientious average of 72 visits per session. He maintained this rate until early 2006, though Jellicoe's last full speech in the Lords was made as part of the ''Address in Reply to Her Majesty's Most Gracious Speech'' (the Queen's Speech debate) on 28 October 1996, his subject was [[Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199697/ldhansrd/vo961028/text/61028-06.htm#61028-06_spnew0|title=Lords Hansard text for 28 Oct 1996 (161028-06) |publisher=Department of the Official Report (Hansard), House of Lords, Westminster }}</ref>\n\nWhen the [[House of Lords Act 1999]] removed his hereditary automatic entitlement to attend and sit in the House of Lords, he was created a [[life peer]] as '''Baron Jellicoe of Southampton''', of [[Southampton]] in the County of Hampshire, so that he could continue to be summoned<blockquote>1. Earl Jellicoe (Lord Jellicoe of Southampton) \u2014The Rt Hon. George Patrick John Rushworth Earl Jellicoe, having been created Baron Jellicoe of Southampton, of Southampton in the County of Hampshire, for life by Letters Patent dated 6 o'clock in the forenoon of 17th&nbsp;November 1999, took and subscribed the oath pursuant to statute.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55676 |page=12465 |date=23 November 1999 }}</ref></blockquote>\n\nLord Jellicoe remained an active member of the House of Lords for the rest of his life. He died on 22 February 2007, six weeks shy of his 89th birthday.\n\nAt his death, Lord Jellicoe was the longest-serving member of the House of Lords, and arguably the longest-serving parliamentarian in the world, having succeeded his father on 20 November 1935 and come of age and sat first in parliament on 25 July 1939. Because he waited until 28 July 1958 to make his maiden speech, a few peers (viz. [[Robert Shirley, 13th Earl Ferrers|Earl Ferrers]] and [[David Renton, Baron Renton|Lords Renton]], [[Peter Carington, 6th Baron Carrington|Carrington]], [[Denis Healey|Healey]], and [[David Kenworthy, 11th Baron Strabolgi|Strabolgi]]) could have been considered to have been active parliamentarians longer. Moreover, at the time of his death, on the Privy Council only the [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Duke of Edinburgh]] (1951) and Lords [[Peter Carington, 6th Baron Carrington|Carrington]] (1959), [[Bill Deedes|Deedes]] and [[David Renton, Baron Renton|Renton]] (both 1962) had served longer.\n\n==Character==\nIn May 1973, at the time of his resignation from the government, friends are quoted as saying:\n{{quote|If he has a fault it is because he wears his weaknesses on his sleeve. He is too frank. I suppose though, that is no bad thing. He was not flamboyant but he was a hedonist. He is the sort of non-pompous person who does not try to hide his weaknesses. (quoted from Christopher Sweeney's article in ''The Times'', 25 May 1973, page 2)}}\n\nIn July 1970, as one of the first people to be [[Breathalyzer|breathalized]], he was banned from driving for a year and fined 75 pounds with 20 guineas costs for ''having consumed more than the permitted level of alcohol'' in Old Brompton Road at 4 a.m. on 21 March 1970. The trouble was that his new [[Reliant Scimitar]] had a stiff gearbox, or so his story went. Luck saw to it that the case came after the General Election and the ban coincided with the arrival of his right to a full-time government car. {{Citation needed|date=March 2010}}\n\nIn 2000, his friend, the former [[British Ambassador to the United States]], [[Nicholas Henderson|Sir Nicholas Henderson]], wrote:\n{{quote|George is a man of moods. He is not complicated but a many-sided character. There are in fact four Georges: there is George the First, the unabstemious, boisterous [[Lothario]], with a leer like a rou\u00e9 in a [[Peter Arno]] cartoon, blessed with an iron constitution and athletic prowess that enabled him to have been on the verge of the British Olympic ski and sleigh teams; then we have Hero George, the dashing man of action, a leader who whether descending by parachute or commanding by sea, kept the enemy on tenterhooks in the Eastern Mediterranean throughout the war; thirdly, there is George the aesthete and sightseer, who, with little finger raised, will speak discerningly of paintings, mosaics and furniture, a great patron of the arts, his talent as a collector manqu\u00e9 only due to lack of funds, which has not prevented some bold purchases; and finally we have pensive George, scholar and public servant, concerned to promote the national interest, high-minded, cautious and conscientious&nbsp;... [A] striking and irrepressible feature of that character has been his easy communion with members of the opposite sex, and this may have been prefigured by an early experience. He spent some time as a small boy in New Zealand where his father was Governor-General. George wanted to become a [[cub scout|wolf cub]], but no pack was available, so instead he joined the [[Brownie (Girl Guides)|Brownies]]. He got on very well with them. (''Old Friends and Modern Instances'', 2000)}}\n\nLord Jellicoe married firstly, 23 March 1944, Patricia O'Kane (1917\u20132012),<ref>{{cite news | url =http://announcements.telegraph.co.uk/deaths/146959/jellicoe| title = Daily Telegraph Deaths Announcements \u2013 Patricia, Countess Jellicoe| accessdate = 21 March 2012 | work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> by whom he had two sons and two daughters. He married secondly, in 1966, Philippa, daughter of [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]] [[Philip Russell Rendel Dunne|Philip Dunne]] (1904\u20131965), by whom he had one son and two daughters. He had eight children in total, born between 1944 and 1984. He was a member of [[Brooks's]] (since 1940), the [[Special Forces]] Club, the [[Ski Club of Great Britain]] and was a liveryman of the [[Worshipful Company of Mercers]].\n\nLorna Windmill's biography termed Jellicoe ''a British Achilles'' on account of two of his careers derailing as a result of women: in the 1950s for love, and in the 1970s for escorts. {{Citation needed|date=March 2010}}\n\n==Honours==\n*Page of Honour (one of nine) to [[George VI of the United Kingdom|King George VI]] at his Coronation (12 May 1937)\n*[[Distinguished Service Order]] (DSO) (1942)\n*[[Military Cross]] (MC) (1944)\n*[[1939-45 Star]]\n*[[Africa Star]]\n*[[Italy Star]]\n*[[1939-45 War Medal]]\n*[[L\u00e9gion d'honneur]] (France) (1945)\n*[[Croix de guerre 1939\u20131945|Croix de Guerre]] (France) (1945)\n*[[Order of Honour (Greece)|Greek Order of Honour]] (1950)\n*[[War Cross (Greece)|Greek War Cross]] (1950)\n*[[Privy Counsellor]] (PC) (1963)\n*Freeman of the City of Athens\n*[[Order of the British Empire|Knight Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (KBE) (1986)\n*Honorary Citizenship of the [[Southampton (village), New York|Village of Southampton, New York]] (12 September 1987)\n*Companion of the British Institute of Management (elected 11 October 1988)\n*Hon. Admiral in the [[Texas Navy]] (1988)\n*27 October 1988 was ''Lord Earl Jellicoe Day'' in the City of [[Houston]]\n*[[Fellow of the Royal Society]] (FRS) (8 November 1990)\n*Grand Commander [[Order of Honour (Greece)|Order of Honour]] (Greece, 1991)\n*La Medaille de la Ville de Paris (echelon vermeil), (6 June 1994)\n*UK Life Peer (1999)\n*27 April 2001 was ''Earl Jellicoe Day'' in the City of [[Vancouver]]\n*''Winston S. Churchill Allied Nations Award'' from World War II Veterans Committee (8 November 2003, USA).\n*Hon. degrees from:\n:*[[King's College London]] (Fellow (FKC) 1979)\n:*[[Southampton University]] (LLD, 1985)\n:*[[Long Island University]] (Doctor of Laws, 12 September 1987).\n\n==Bibliography==\n*''Old Friends and Modern Instances'', by [[Nicholas Henderson]], Profile, 2001 (all chapter nine, pages&nbsp;105\u2013116).\n*''A British Achilles: The Story of George, 2nd Earl Jellicoe'', by Lorna Almonds Windmill, Pen and Sword Books Ltd, Barnsley, 2006.\n*''Dod's Parliamentary Companion'', 2007.\n*''Burke's Peerage'', 107th edition, 2003.\n*''Review of the Operation of the Prevention of Terrorism (Temporary Provisions) Act 1976'', by the Rt. Hon. Earl Jellicoe, DSO, MC., Command 8803, HMSO, February 1983.\n*''The Boxer Rebellion'', The Fifth Wellington Lecture, University of Southampton, by the Rt Hon the Earl Jellicoe, KBE, DSO, MC, LLD, FRS, PC, University of Southampton, 1993.\n*''Lord Shackleton'', by Lord Jellicoe, in ''Biographical Memoirs of Fellows of the Royal Society'', number 45, 1999, printed by the Cambridge University Press for the Royal Society.\n*''Special Boat Squadron'', ''The Story of the SBS in the Mediterranean'', by Barrie Pitt, Century Publishing, London, 1983.\n*''The Life of John Rushworth, Earl Jellicoe, G.C.B., O.M., G.C.V.O, L.L.D., D.C.L.'', by Admiral Sir [[R. H. Bacon]], K.C.B., K.C.V.O., D.S.O., Cassell, London, Toronto, Melbourne & Sydney, 1936.\n*''Tatler'', 30 August 1939.\n*''News Chronicle'', 30 January 1942.\n*(Australian) ''The Sun'', Alan Trengove, 22 June 1972\n*''International Herald Tribune'', 21 February 1978. Article on Patricia, Countess Jellicoe by Naomi Barry.\n*''Financial Weekly'', 20 April 1979, profile by Judi Bevan, page 12.\n*''Country Life'', 1 July 1999, profile, with a photo by [[Derry Moore, 12th Earl of Drogheda|Derry Moore]].\n*''Twenty-One: Coming of Age in the Second World War'', by James Holland, HarperCollins, London, 2006 (whole of chapter five).\n*[[Baron Chidgey|Lord Chidgey]] in ''The House Magazine'', Dods, 12 February 2007.\n*''House of Lords Hansard'', Monday 26 February 2007: ''Tributes: Earl Jellicoe''.\n*Obituaries\n:*''The Independent'' (Dennis Kavanagh), Saturday 24 February 2007.\n:*''The Times'', ''The Daily Telegraph'', & ''The Guardian'' ([[Andrew Roth]]): Monday 26 February 2007.\n:*''Financial Times'', (Sue Cameron): Tuesday 27 February 2007.\n:*''Yesterday in Parliament'', (David Wilby), BBC Radio Four, Tuesday 27 February 2007.\n:*''The Scotsman'', (Alasdair Steven), Wednesday 28 February 2007.\n:*''The Times'', (Lives Remembered, by Christopher Roberts), 28 February 2007.\n:*''The Wiltshire Gazette and Herald'', Thursday 1 March 2007.\n:*''The Week'', (a digest of the above), 3 March 2007.\n:*''The Spectator'', ([[Patrick Leigh Fermor]]), 3 March 2007.\n:*BBC Radio Four, ''Last Word'' (John Wilson), Friday 2 March 2007, (tx: circa 15:20\u201315:28).\n:*''The Herald'', Glasgow, Monday 5 March 2007.\n:*''The Anglo-Hellenic Review'', no. 36, Autumn 2007.\n*''The Times'', and ''The Daily Telegraph'', 1 June 2007, approximate list of those who attended his memorial service at the [[Guards Chapel, Wellington Barracks|Guards Chapel]], [[Wellington Barracks, London|Wellington Barracks]], [[Birdcage Walk]], St James's Park, Westminster, on 31 May 2007.\n:*''The Oldie'', James Hughes Onslow on Earl Jellicoe's memorial service, page 69, July 2007.\n* The Anglo-Hellenic League's ''reception in remembrance of its former Chairman and Patron'', Cholmondeley Room, House of Lords, 14 February 2008.\n::spoken tributes by [[Colin Moynihan|Lord Moynihan]], Tryphon Kedros, [[Viscount Norwich|John Julius Norwich]], Sir James Gowans, Dimitris Paraskevas, & the Hon. Nicholas Jellicoe.\n:::This event was reported in ''The Anglo-Hellenic Review'', no. 37, Spring 2008, page 2.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Hansard-contribs | mr-george-jellicoe | the Earl Jellicoe }}\n*[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199900/minutes/991123/ldminute.htm Announcement of his taking the oath] for the first time as ''Baron Jellicoe of Southampton'', House of Lords Minutes of proceedings, 23 November 1999\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040222114039/http://www.winstonchurchill.org/i4a/pages/index.cfm?pageid=631 Speech] to The Churchill Centre Inc., from proceedings of the International Churchill Societies 1994\u201395.\n*[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199697/ldhansrd/vo961028/text/61028-06.htm#61028-06_spnew0 Jellicoe on the Ukraine. His last full speech in the Lords, 28 October 1996].\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071119112513/http://news.independent.co.uk/people/obituaries/article2300414.ece ''Independent'' obituary]\n*[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200607/ldhansrd/text/70226-0001.htm#0702269000010 Tributes: Earl Jelicoe] Link to Hansard, Monday 26 February 2007.\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-off}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Henry Bathurst, 8th Earl Bathurst|The Earl Bathurst]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Lord-in-waiting]]|years=1961}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Bertram Bowyer, 2nd Baron Denham|The Lord Denham]]}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Peter Carington, 6th Baron Carrington|The Lord Carrington]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Admiralty|First Lord of the Admiralty]]|years=1963\u20131964}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Queen Elizabeth II]]|as=Lord High Admiral}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Edward Shackleton, Baron Shackleton|The Lord Shackleton]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Lord Privy Seal]]<br />[[Leader of the House of Lords]]|years=1970\u20131973}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[David Hennessy, 3rd Baron Windlesham|The Lord Windlesham]]}}\n{{S-ppo}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Peter Carington, 6th Baron Carrington|The Lord Carrington]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Leader of the Conservative Party (UK)|Leader of the Conservative Party]] in the [[House of Lords]]|years=1970\u20131973}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[David Hennessy, 3rd Baron Windlesham|The Lord Windlesham]]}}\n{{s-hon}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dominick Browne, 4th Baron Oranmore and Browne|The Lord Oranmore and Browne]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Father of the House (United Kingdom)#Longest-serving member of the House of Lords|Longest-serving member in the House of Lords]]|years=1999\u20132007}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Peter Carington, 6th Baron Carrington| The Lord Carrington]]}}\n{{S-reg|uk}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[John Jellicoe, 1st Earl Jellicoe|John Jellicoe]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Earl Jellicoe]]|years=1935\u20132007}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Patrick Jellicoe, 3rd Earl Jellicoe|Patrick Jellicoe]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{FRS 1990}}\n{{First Lords of the Admiralty|state=collapsed}}\n{{Heath Ministry}}\n{{RGSPresidents}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2011}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jellicoe, George Jellicoe, 2nd Earl}}\n[[Category:1918 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni 