 (\u2021):\n{{Reflist|group=\"\u2021\"}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Cite web |url=http://theconversation.com/youtube-games-star-pewdiepie-is-playing-for-global-dominance-32681 |title=YouTube games star PewDiePie is playing for global dominance |last=C-Scott |first=Marc |date=9 October 2014 |work=[[The Conversation (website)|The Conversation]] |access-date=3 January 2019}}\n*{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2013/jul/08/pewdiepie-youtube-channel-games-popularity |title=With 50m weekly views, PewDiePie is world's most popular YouTube channel |last=Dredge |first=Stuart |date=8 July 2013 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=3 January 2019}}\n\n{{PewDiePie}}\n[[Category:2010s YouTube videos]]\n[[Category:2020s YouTube videos]]\n[[Category:PewDiePie|Videography]]\n[[Category:Videographies of YouTubers]]\n", "name_user": "Soulbust", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFormatted vlog series", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PewDiePie_videography"}
{"title_page": "Johannes of Ljubljana", "text_new": "[[File:Janez Ljubljanski - Sv. Miklav\u017e re\u0161i mladeni\u010de.jpg|thumb|Copy of Johannes of Ljubljana's fresco ''Saint Nicholas Saves Three Innocents'' (1443), [[National Gallery of Slovenia]]]]\n'''Johannes of Ljubljana'''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Campbell |first1=Gordon |title=The Grove Encyclopedia of Northern Renaissance Art |date=2009 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |page=274}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Hourihane |first1=Colum |title=The Grove Encyclopedia of Medieval Art and Architecture |date=2012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=New York |page=625}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Turner |first1=Jane |title=The Dictionary of Art, vol. 16 |date=2005 |publisher=Grove |location=New York |page=494}}</ref> ({{lang-la|Johannes de Laybaco}}, Slovenized as ''Janez Ljubljanski''), was a painter active between 1433 and 1460.\n\n==Life and work==\nJohannes was the son of [[Frederic of Villach]],<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kri\u017enar |first1=Anabelle |title=A Comparative Study of Wall Painting Materials and Techniques Used in Fifteenth Century Austria by Frederich of Villach and His Followers |journal=Studies in Conservation |date=2014 |volume=59 |issue=5 |pages=289-299 |url=https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1179/2047058413Y.0000000114 |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kri\u017enar |first1=Anabelle |title=Plasters in Mediaeval Mural Paintings of Carinthia and Their Influence on Slovenia |journal=Journal of Architectural Conservation |date=2014 |volume=20 |issue=1 |pages=43-55 |url=https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/13556207.2014.886375 |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref> and he became a citizen of the town of [[Ljubljana]] around 1440.<ref name=\"Rozman\">{{cite encyclopedia |last=Rozman |first=Ksenija |encyclopedia=Enciklopedija Slovenije |title=Janez Ljubljanski |year=1990 |publisher=Mladinska knjiga |volume=4 |location=Ljubljana |pages=263-264}}</ref> He initially worked in his father's workshop in [[Duchy of Carinthia|Carinthia]], where he created his first independent works. He is believed to have had close contact with the [[Cistercians]], and in [[Carniola]] he worked on commissions from [[Sti\u010dna Abbey]]. His bet-known signed and dated frescoes are in the Gothic Saint Nicholas's Church in [[Visoko, Ig|Visoko]] (1443) and in [[Muljava]] (1456). A work of his bearing only a date (1459) is found in Saint Peter's Church in Kamni Vrh pri Ambrusu. His independent works also include paintings at the monastery in [[Sti\u010dna]] and at the churches in [[Metnaj]] and [[Ma\u010dkovec pri Dvoru]], and together with painters from his workshop he also created works in [[Tro\u0161\u010dine]] and at Saint Nicholas's Chapel of Ease in [[\u017du\u017eemberk]]. Products of his workshop are also considered the frescoes in [[Menge\u0161]] and the pilgrimage church dedicated to the [[Annunciation]] in [[Crngrob]], where he painted ''Holy Sunday'' around 1460.<ref name=\"Rozman\"/>\n\nJohannes brought a late soft style of painting to Carniola from Carinthia, pervaded by Bohemian and Italian influences. His works are characterized by the skill of his workshop, their colorful plastic modeling, idealized calm, and the beauty of the figures. With regard to his iconography, his work shows some adaptation to the painting style common to Carniolan chancels.<ref name=\"Rozman\"/>\n \n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Carniolan painters]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:Year of death unknown]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Janez Ljubljanski - Sv. Miklav\u017e re\u0161i mladeni\u010de.jpg|thumb|Copy of the fresco ''Saint Nicholas Saves Three Innocents'' (1443), [[National Gallery of Slovenia]]]]\n'''Johannes of Ljubljana'''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Campbell |first1=Gordon |title=The Grove Encyclopedia of Northern Renaissance Art |date=2009 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |page=274}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Hourihane |first1=Colum |title=The Grove Encyclopedia of Medieval Art and Architecture |date=2012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=New York |page=625}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Turner |first1=Jane |title=The Dictionary of Art, vol. 16 |date=2005 |publisher=Grove |location=New York |page=494}}</ref> ({{lang-la|Johannes de Laybaco}}, Slovenized as ''Janez Ljubljanski''), was a painter active between 1433 and 1460.\n\n==Life and work==\nJohannes was the son of [[Frederic of Villach]],<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kri\u017enar |first1=Anabelle |title=A Comparative Study of Wall Painting Materials and Techniques Used in Fifteenth Century Austria by Frederich of Villach and His Followers |journal=Studies in Conservation |date=2014 |volume=59 |issue=5 |pages=289-299 |url=https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1179/2047058413Y.0000000114 |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kri\u017enar |first1=Anabelle |title=Plasters in Mediaeval Mural Paintings of Carinthia and Their Influence on Slovenia |journal=Journal of Architectural Conservation |date=2014 |volume=20 |issue=1 |pages=43-55 |url=https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/13556207.2014.886375 |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref> and he became a citizen of the town of [[Ljubljana]] around 1440.<ref name=\"Rozman\">{{cite encyclopedia |last=Rozman |first=Ksenija |encyclopedia=Enciklopedija Slovenije |title=Janez Ljubljanski |year=1990 |publisher=Mladinska knjiga |volume=4 |location=Ljubljana |pages=263-264}}</ref> He initially worked in his father's workshop in [[Duchy of Carinthia|Carinthia]], where he created his first independent works. He is believed to have had close contact with the [[Cistercians]], and in [[Carniola]] he worked on commissions from [[Sti\u010dna Abbey]]. His bet-known signed and dated frescoes are in the Gothic Saint Nicholas's Church in [[Visoko, Ig|Visoko]] (1443) and in [[Muljava]] (1456). A work of his bearing only a date (1459) is found in Saint Peter's Church in Kamni Vrh pri Ambrusu. His independent works also include paintings at the monastery in [[Sti\u010dna]] and at the churches in [[Metnaj]] and [[Ma\u010dkovec pri Dvoru]], and together with painters from his workshop he also created works in [[Tro\u0161\u010dine]] and at Saint Nicholas's Chapel of Ease in [[\u017du\u017eemberk]]. Products of his workshop are also considered the frescoes in [[Menge\u0161]] and the pilgrimage church dedicated to the [[Annunciation]] in [[Crngrob]], where he painted ''Holy Sunday'' around 1460.<ref name=\"Rozman\"/>\n\nJohannes brought a late soft style of painting to Carniola from Carinthia, pervaded by Bohemian and Italian influences. His works are characterized by the skill of his workshop, their colorful plastic modeling, idealized calm, and the beauty of the figures. With regard to his iconography, his work shows some adaptation to the painting style common to Carniolan chancels.<ref name=\"Rozman\"/>\n \n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Carniolan painters]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:Year of death unknown]]\n", "name_user": "Doremo", "label": "safe", "comment": "attribution in caption", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johannes_of_Ljubljana"}
{"title_page": "Homebrew (package manager)", "text_new": "{{other uses|Homebrew (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|Software instalation management software}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name                   = Homebrew\n| logo                   = Homebrew logo.svg\n| logo alt               = Homebrew\u2019s logo\n| screenshot             = Sample of Homebrew 2.2.12 in Mac Terminal.png\n| caption                = Sample of Homebrew 2.2.12 in Mac Terminal\n| author                 = Max Howell\n| released               = {{Start date and age|2009|05|21|df=yes}}<ref name=\"brew-release-0.1\">{{GitHub|https://github.com/Homebrew/brew/releases/tag/0.1|Homebrew release 0.1}}</ref>\n| latest release version = 2.2.13\n| latest release date    = {{Start date and age|2020|04|13|df=yes}}<ref>{{GitHub|https://github.com/Homebrew/brew/releases/tag/2.2.13|Homebrew release 2.2.13}}</ref>\n| programming language   = [[Ruby (programming language)|Ruby]]\n| operating system       = [[macOS]], [[Linux]]\n| language               = English\n| genre                  = [[Package manager]]\n| license                = [[BSD license]]\n| website                = {{URL|https://brew.sh}}\n}}\n'''Homebrew''' is a [[free software|free]] and [[Open-source software|open-source]] software [[Package manager|package management system]] that simplifies the installation of software on [[Apple Inc.|Apple's]] [[macOS]] operating system and [[Linux]]. The name is intended to suggest the idea of building software on the Mac depending on the user's taste. Originally written by Max Howell, the package manager has gained popularity in the [[Ruby on Rails]] community and earned praise for its [[extensibility]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.engineyard.com/2010/homebrew-os-xs-missing-package-manager/ |title=Homebrew: OS X\u2019s Missing Package Manager |first=Andre |last=Arko |publisher=[[Engine Yard]] |work=Engine Yard blog |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150708101237/https://blog.engineyard.com/2010/homebrew-os-xs-missing-package-manager/ |archivedate=July 8, 2015 }}</ref> Homebrew has been recommended for its ease of use<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hoffman|first1=Chris|title=Homebrew for OS X Easily Installs Desktop Apps and Terminal Utilities|url=http://www.howtogeek.com/211541/homebrew-for-os-x-easily-installs-desktop-apps-and-terminal-utilities/|website=How-to Geek|accessdate=24 June 2015}}</ref> as well as its integration into the [[command line interface|command line]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Terpstra|first1=Brett|title=Homebrew, the perfect gift for command line lovers|url=https://www.engadget.com/2009/12/25/homebrew-the-perfect-gift-for-command-line-lovers/|website=Engadget|accessdate=24 June 2015}}</ref> Homebrew is a non-profit project member of the [[Software Freedom Conservancy]], and is run entirely by unpaid volunteers.<ref name=\"homebrew-readme-whoareyou\">{{cite web|last1=McQuaid|first1=Mike|title=Homebrew/brew/README.md|url=https://github.com/Homebrew/brew/blob/master/README.md#who-are-you|website=GitHub|accessdate=4 December 2018|archive-url=https://github.com/Homebrew/brew/blob/d51a9e8564d5135b5d2cbe1702a51b810b4e25ea/README.md#who-are-you|archive-date=5 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHomebrew has made extensive use of [[GitHub]] to expand the support of several packages through user contributions. In 2010, Homebrew was the third-most-[[Fork (software development)|forked]] repository on GitHub.<ref>{{cite web|title=Popular Forked Repositories|url=https://github.com/popular/forked|website=GitHub|accessdate=24 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100311081541/http://github.com/popular/forked|archivedate=11 March 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2012, Homebrew had the largest number of new contributors on GitHub.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/blog/1359-the-octoverse-in-2012|title=The Octoverse in 2012|publisher=[[GitHub]]}}</ref> In 2013, Homebrew had both the largest number of contributors and issues closed of any project on GitHub.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://octoverse.github.com |title=GitHub Octoverse 2013}}</ref>\n\nHomebrew has spawned several sub-projects such as Linuxbrew, a Linux [[Porting|port]] now officially merged into Homebrew;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://linuxbrew.sh|title=Linuxbrew|website=Linuxbrew|accessdate=2019-02-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/Linuxbrew/brew/blob/93389fde63974f096156344e281610acec44130c/README.md|title=Linuxbrew Readme|website=GitHub|accessdate=2019-03-29}}</ref> Homebrew Cask, which builds upon Homebrew and focuses on the installation of [[GUI]] applications;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/homebrew/homebrew-cask|title=Homebrew Cask|website=Github|accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref> and \"taps\" dedicated to specific areas or programming languages like [[PHP]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/Homebrew/homebrew-php|title=Homebrew/homebrew-php|website=GitHub|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nHomebrew was written by Max Howell in 2009.<ref name=\"brew-release-0.1\" /><ref>{{cite web|last1=Howell|first1=Max|title=I'll start with a rare Belgian yeast and Sussex hops|url=https://github.com/Homebrew/homebrew/commit/29d85578e75170a6c0eaebda4d701b46f1acf446|website=GitHub|accessdate=24 June 2015}}</ref> In March 2013, Homebrew successfully completed a [[Kickstarter]] campaign to raise funds for servers to test and build formulae and managed to raise {{Currency|14859|GBP}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=brew test-bot|url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/homebrew/brew-test-bot/description|website=Kickstarter|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref> On December 13, 2013, the Homebrew repository migrated from Howell's GitHub account to its own project account.<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=MacHomebrew |number=410681585407901696 |date= 11 December 2013|title=This Saturday morning at 0100 GMT we will be migrating Homebrew}}</ref> In February 2015, due to downtime at [[SourceForge]] which resulted in binaries being unavailable, Homebrew moved their hosting to bintray.<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=MacHomebrew |number=569872540845387777 |date= 23 February 2015|title=Homebrew's bottles (binary packages) are now hosted by @bintray}}</ref> On September 21, 2016, Homebrew version 1.0.0 was released.<ref>{{GitHub|https://github.com/Homebrew/brew/releases/tag/1.0.0|Homebrew release 1.0.0}}</ref> As of December 2018, Homebrew is maintained by a team of 21 people.<ref name=\"homebrew-readme-whoareyou\" /> In January 2019, Linuxbrew was merged back into Homebrew, adding beta support for Linux and the [[Windows Subsystem for Linux]] to Homebrew's feature set.<ref>{{cite web |title=Homebrew 1.9.0 |url=https://brew.sh/2019/01/09/homebrew-1.9.0/ |website=Homebrew |accessdate=10 January 2019}}</ref> On February 2, 2019, Homebrew version 2.0.0 was released.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McQuaid |first1=Mike |title=2.0.0 |url=https://brew.sh/2019/02/02/homebrew-2.0.0/ |website=Homebrew |accessdate=3 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Implementation==\nHomebrew is written in the [[Ruby programming language]] and targets the version of Ruby that comes installed with the macOS operating system. It is by default installed into <code>/usr/local</code> and consists of a [[Git (software)|git]] repository, allowing the user to update Homebrew by pulling an updated repository from GitHub. The package manager builds software from source using \"formulae\", Ruby scripts constructed with Homebrew's [[domain-specific language]] (DSL) for managing dependencies, downloading source files, and configuring and compiling software. Binary packages called \"bottles\" provide pre-built formulae with default options.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nHomebrew does not honor the default [[Privilege (computing)|privileges]] of <code>/usr/local</code>; directory [[Chmod|ownership]] is changed from [[Superuser|root]] with group permissions for the [[Wheel (computing)|wheel]] group to the installing user and the \"admin\" group. Specifically, the mode changes from <code>drwxr-xr-x root wheel</code> to <code> drwxrwxr-x myuser admin</code>.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ounsworth |first1=Mike |title=What are the security implications of Homebrew and Macports? |url=https://security.stackexchange.com/a/191614 |website=StackExchange Information Security |accessdate=2 April 2019}}</ref> All files, not just the directories, have their ownership changed by the installer. This is considered by some as a major security flaw.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Phil |first1=Stokes |title=How Homebrew invites users to get pwned |url=https://applehelpwriter.com/2018/03/21/how-homebrew-invites-users-to-get-pwned/ |website=AppleHelpWriter.com |accessdate=2 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Data collection==\nHomebrew collects installation, build error, and operating system version statistics via [[Google Analytics]].<ref name=\"analytics\">{{cite web |title=Homebrew's Anonymous Aggregate User Behaviour Analytics |url=https://github.com/Homebrew/brew/blob/master/docs/Analytics.md |website=GitHub |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161127041156/https://github.com/Homebrew/brew/blob/master/docs/Analytics.md |archive-date=26 November 2016  |url-status=live |date=20 September 2016 |access-date=26 November 2016}}</ref> It is possible to opt out with the command <code>brew analytics off</code>.<ref name=\"analytics\"/>\n\nUsers can view analytics data from the last 30, 90, and 365 days on the Homebrew website.<ref>{{cite web |title=Homebrew Analytics Data |url=https://formulae.brew.sh/analytics/ |website=Homebrew |accessdate=1 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Free and open-source software}}\n* [[Fink (software)|Fink]]\n* [[Gentoo/Alt]]\n* [[MacPorts]]\n* [[Nix package manager|Nix]]\n* [[Pkgsrc]]\n* [[FreeBSD Ports]]\n* [[Installer (macOS)]]\n* [[List of software package management systems]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{Github|Homebrew/brew|Homebrew}}\n* [https://changelog.com/podcast/223 \"The Changelog #223: Homebrew and Package Management with Mike McQuaid\"]. 2016-10-07.\n\n{{Ruby programming language}}\n{{Package management systems}}\n\n[[Category:2009 software]]\n[[Category:Console applications]]\n[[Category:Free package management systems]]\n[[Category:Free software programmed in Ruby]]\n[[Category:Software using the BSD license]]\n[[Category:Utilities for macOS]]\n[[Category:Utilities for Linux]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses|Homebrew (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|Software instalation management software}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name                   = Homebrew\n| logo                   = Homebrew logo.svg\n| logo alt               = Homebrew\u2019s logo\n| screenshot             = Sample of Homebrew 2.2.12 in Mac Terminal.png\n| caption                = Sample of Homebrew 2.2.12 in Mac Terminal\n| author                 = Max Howell\n| released               = {{Start date and age|2009|05|21|df=yes}}<ref name=\"brew-release-0.1\">{{GitHub|https://github.com/Homebrew/brew/releases/tag/0.1|Homebrew release 0.1}}</ref>\n| latest release version = 2.2.2\n| latest release date    = {{Start date and age|2019|12|23|df=yes}}<ref>{{GitHub|https://github.com/Homebrew/brew/releases/tag/2.2.2}}</ref>\n| programming language   = [[Ruby (programming language)|Ruby]]\n| operating system       = [[macOS]], [[Linux]]\n| language               = English\n| genre                  = [[Package manager]]\n| license                = [[BSD license]]\n| website                = {{URL|https://brew.sh}}\n}}\n'''Homebrew''' is a [[free software|free]] and [[Open-source software|open-source]] software [[Package manager|package management system]] that simplifies the installation of software on [[Apple Inc.|Apple's]] [[macOS]] operating system and [[Linux]]. The name is intended to suggest the idea of building software on the Mac depending on the user's taste. Originally written by Max Howell, the package manager has gained popularity in the [[Ruby on Rails]] community and earned praise for its [[extensibility]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.engineyard.com/2010/homebrew-os-xs-missing-package-manager/ |title=Homebrew: OS X\u2019s Missing Package Manager |first=Andre |last=Arko |publisher=[[Engine Yard]] |work=Engine Yard blog |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150708101237/https://blog.engineyard.com/2010/homebrew-os-xs-missing-package-manager/ |archivedate=July 8, 2015 }}</ref> Homebrew has been recommended for its ease of use<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hoffman|first1=Chris|title=Homebrew for OS X Easily Installs Desktop Apps and Terminal Utilities|url=http://www.howtogeek.com/211541/homebrew-for-os-x-easily-installs-desktop-apps-and-terminal-utilities/|website=How-to Geek|accessdate=24 June 2015}}</ref> as well as its integration into the [[command line interface|command line]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Terpstra|first1=Brett|title=Homebrew, the perfect gift for command line lovers|url=https://www.engadget.com/2009/12/25/homebrew-the-perfect-gift-for-command-line-lovers/|website=Engadget|accessdate=24 June 2015}}</ref> Homebrew is a non-profit project member of the [[Software Freedom Conservancy]], and is run entirely by unpaid volunteers.<ref name=\"homebrew-readme-whoareyou\">{{cite web|last1=McQuaid|first1=Mike|title=Homebrew/brew/README.md|url=https://github.com/Homebrew/brew/blob/master/README.md#who-are-you|website=GitHub|accessdate=4 December 2018|archive-url=https://github.com/Homebrew/brew/blob/d51a9e8564d5135b5d2cbe1702a51b810b4e25ea/README.md#who-are-you|archive-date=5 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHomebrew has made extensive use of [[GitHub]] to expand the support of several packages through user contributions. In 2010, Homebrew was the third-most-[[Fork (software development)|forked]] repository on GitHub.<ref>{{cite web|title=Popular Forked Repositories|url=https://github.com/popular/forked|website=GitHub|accessdate=24 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100311081541/http://github.com/popular/forked|archivedate=11 March 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2012, Homebrew had the largest number of new contributors on GitHub.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/blog/1359-the-octoverse-in-2012|title=The Octoverse in 2012|publisher=[[GitHub]]}}</ref> In 2013, Homebrew had both the largest number of contributors and issues closed of any project on GitHub.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://octoverse.github.com |title=GitHub Octoverse 2013}}</ref>\n\nHomebrew has spawned several sub-projects such as Linuxbrew, a Linux [[Porting|port]] now officially merged into Homebrew;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://linuxbrew.sh|title=Linuxbrew|website=Linuxbrew|accessdate=2019-02-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/Linuxbrew/brew/blob/93389fde63974f096156344e281610acec44130c/README.md|title=Linuxbrew Readme|website=GitHub|accessdate=2019-03-29}}</ref> Homebrew Cask, which builds upon Homebrew and focuses on the installation of [[GUI]] applications;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/homebrew/homebrew-cask|title=Homebrew Cask|website=Github|accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref> and \"taps\" dedicated to specific areas or programming languages like [[PHP]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/Homebrew/homebrew-php|title=Homebrew/homebrew-php|website=GitHub|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nHomebrew was written by Max Howell in 2009.<ref name=\"brew-release-0.1\" /><ref>{{cite web|last1=Howell|first1=Max|title=I'll start with a rare Belgian yeast and Sussex hops|url=https://github.com/Homebrew/homebrew/commit/29d85578e75170a6c0eaebda4d701b46f1acf446|website=GitHub|accessdate=24 June 2015}}</ref> In March 2013, Homebrew successfully completed a [[Kickstarter]] campaign to raise funds for servers to test and build formulae and managed to raise {{Currency|14859|GBP}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=brew test-bot|url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/homebrew/brew-test-bot/description|website=Kickstarter|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref> On December 13, 2013, the Homebrew repository migrated from Howell's GitHub account to its own project account.<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=MacHomebrew |number=410681585407901696 |date= 11 December 2013|title=This Saturday morning at 0100 GMT we will be migrating Homebrew}}</ref> In February 2015, due to downtime at [[SourceForge]] which resulted in binaries being unavailable, Homebrew moved their hosting to bintray.<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=MacHomebrew |number=569872540845387777 |date= 23 February 2015|title=Homebrew's bottles (binary packages) are now hosted by @bintray}}</ref> On September 21, 2016, Homebrew version 1.0.0 was released.<ref>{{GitHub|https://github.com/Homebrew/brew/releases/tag/1.0.0|Homebrew release 1.0.0}}</ref> As of December 2018, Homebrew is maintained by a team of 21 people.<ref name=\"homebrew-readme-whoareyou\" /> In January 2019, Linuxbrew was merged back into Homebrew, adding beta support for Linux and the [[Windows Subsystem for Linux]] to Homebrew's feature set.<ref>{{cite web |title=Homebrew 1.9.0 |url=https://brew.sh/2019/01/09/homebrew-1.9.0/ |website=Homebrew |accessdate=10 January 2019}}</ref> On February 2, 2019, Homebrew version 2.0.0 was released.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McQuaid |first1=Mike |title=2.0.0 |url=https://brew.sh/2019/02/02/homebrew-2.0.0/ |website=Homebrew |accessdate=3 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Implementation==\nHomebrew is written in the [[Ruby programming language]] and targets the version of Ruby that comes installed with the macOS operating system. It is by default installed into <code>/usr/local</code> and consists of a [[Git (software)|git]] repository, allowing the user to update Homebrew by pulling an updated repository from GitHub. The package manager builds software from source using \"formulae\", Ruby scripts constructed with Homebrew's [[domain-specific language]] (DSL) for managing dependencies, downloading source files, and configuring and compiling software. Binary packages called \"bottles\" provide pre-built formulae with default options.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nHomebrew does not honor the default [[Privilege (computing)|privileges]] of <code>/usr/local</code>; directory [[Chmod|ownership]] is changed from [[Superuser|root]] with group permissions for the [[Wheel (computing)|wheel]] group to the installing user and the \"admin\" group. Specifically, the mode changes from <code>drwxr-xr-x root wheel</code> to <code> drwxrwxr-x myuser admin</code>.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ounsworth |first1=Mike |title=What are the security implications of Homebrew and Macports? |url=https://security.stackexchange.com/a/191614 |website=StackExchange Information Security |accessdate=2 April 2019}}</ref> All files, not just the directories, have their ownership changed by the installer. This is considered by some as a major security flaw.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Phil |first1=Stokes |title=How Homebrew invites users to get pwned |url=https://applehelpwriter.com/2018/03/21/how-homebrew-invites-users-to-get-pwned/ |website=AppleHelpWriter.com |accessdate=2 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Data collection==\nHomebrew collects installation, build error, and operating system version statistics via [[Google Analytics]].<ref name=\"analytics\">{{cite web |title=Homebrew's Anonymous Aggregate User Behaviour Analytics |url=https://github.com/Homebrew/brew/blob/master/docs/Analytics.md |website=GitHub |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161127041156/https://github.com/Homebrew/brew/blob/master/docs/Analytics.md |archive-date=26 November 2016  |url-status=live |date=20 September 2016 |access-date=26 November 2016}}</ref> It is possible to opt out with the command <code>brew analytics off</code>.<ref name=\"analytics\"/>\n\nUsers can view analytics data from the last 30, 90, and 365 days on the Homebrew website.<ref>{{cite web |title=Homebrew Analytics Data |url=https://formulae.brew.sh/analytics/ |website=Homebrew |accessdate=1 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Free and open-source software}}\n* [[Fink (software)|Fink]]\n* [[Gentoo/Alt]]\n* [[MacPorts]]\n* [[Nix package manager|Nix]]\n* [[Pkgsrc]]\n* [[FreeBSD Ports]]\n* [[Installer (macOS)]]\n* [[List of software package management systems]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{Github|Homebrew/brew|Homebrew}}\n* [https://changelog.com/podcast/223 \"The Changelog #223: Homebrew and Package Management with Mike McQuaid\"]. 2016-10-07.\n\n{{Ruby programming language}}\n{{Package management systems}}\n\n[[Category:2009 software]]\n[[Category:Console applications]]\n[[Category:Free package management systems]]\n[[Category:Free software programmed in Ruby]]\n[[Category:Software using the BSD license]]\n[[Category:Utilities for macOS]]\n[[Category:Utilities for Linux]]\n", "name_user": "Synoli", "label": "safe", "comment": "Bump version to 2.2.13", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homebrew_(package_manager)"}
